title: Saving Christmas
review: Saving Christmas will hold little interest for anyone not already a believer. It’s too single-minded in its instructional purpose, too averse to multidimensional characters, too youth-pastor-like in its dorky humor.

title: Saving Christmas
review: Beyond the leaps in logic, the most troubling part of this film is that it just feels like a defense of the excess of Christmas.

title: Saving Christmas
review: Saving Christmas seems determined to win any perceived war on Christmas through brute force.

title: Saving Christmas
review: This may be one of the least artful holiday films ever made. Even devout born-again Christians will find this hard to stomach.

title: Saving Christmas
review: Every holiday season sees a new influx of Christmas movies desperate to become the next big seasonal perennial destined to provide laughter, tears, humanity and healthy residuals for years to come.

title: Saving Christmas
review: A glorified infomercial in defense of the holiday that contains about 15 minutes of actual content padded out with almost an hour of filler.

title: Saving Christmas
review: An unholy mess co-produced by Cameron's faith-based Camfam Studios.

title: Saving Christmas
review: Preaching aside, though, Saving Christmas is a shoddy 80-minute feature that contains approximately 50 minutes of actual moving footage. When Cameron narrates that materialism doesn’t go against Christmas because it celebrates the son of God being made material himself, it sounds like a defense of any kind of cheap, poorly made holiday crap — this movie included.

title: Saving Christmas
review: Director Doane offers no storytelling pizzazz; the lighting is careless, the pacing is deadly, the occasional stabs at comedy fall flat. Ultimately, Saving Christmas has nothing to share that Linus Van Pelt didn't already say better on “A Charlie Brown Christmas.”

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: The Farrelly brothers could burp out a movie funnier than The Hottie & the Nottie, a farce of corrupt stereotypes that's never more grotesque than when it pretends to be more than skin-deep.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Like Nate, we are mere Notties. And we are supposed to feel oh-so privileged for getting to watch Paris through the glass.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Though Hilton may be a model, if her work in Hottie is any indication, she is no actress.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Verdict: not so hot

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: A cinematic excursion so horrific that it's an insult to bad movies to call it a bad movie.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: That generous half star rating I tacked onto this comedy abomination is all for Paris Hilton. Come on, it takes guts (or gross dim-wittedness) to appear on screen again after "House of Wax."

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Crass, shrill, disingenuous, tawdry, mean-spirited, vulgar, idiotic, boring, slapdash, half-assed, and very, very unfunny.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Paris Hilton has already ushered a remarkable three features into the Internet Movie Database's "Bottom 100." The Hottie and the Nottie will make it an even four.

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: How is Paris Hilton in her first starring role to receive a national release? Pretty bad, actually. She's limited to a single, all-too-familiar expression of smug self-satisfaction, and she delivers her lines in a tone somewhere between "seductive" and "dish-soap commercial."

title: The Hottie & the Nottie
review: Preposterous, disingenuous, remarkably unfunny and genuinely distasteful.

title: Disaster Movie
review: The movie is merciless sending up "Juno's" self-satisfied hipster gobbledygook, and it's quite funny to see Hannah Montana still promoting her tie-in products as she lies crushed and dying under a meteor.

title: Disaster Movie
review: Lazy, superficially au courant and utterly forgettable.

title: Disaster Movie
review: Seldom has a pic been more appropriately titled than Disaster Movie, yet another frantically unfunny free-form farce.

title: Disaster Movie
review: Real disaster movies have more laughs than this spoof.

title: Disaster Movie
review: Why would you watch a bad movie about better movies, when you could just rent the originals instead?

title: Disaster Movie
review: Does little more than congratulate its audience on recognizing the source of its riffs. "High School Musical" -- ha ha ha!

title: Disaster Movie
review: A horrific waste of time, money and oxygen.

title: Disaster Movie
review: It's too easy to say Disaster Movie deserves its title, but why put more effort into trashing it than the filmmakers did into writing it?

title: Disaster Movie
review: The filmmakers are idiots.

title: Disaster Movie
review: This carpet-fouling mongrel of a movie no more deserves release than do anthrax spores.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: The film's moral? Turn off the TV, young 'uns, and go outside and play! And avoid Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2 matinees while you're at it.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: The sequel retains not only the same gimmicky premise as the original but its preference for cliche-ridden dialogue and flat-footed comedy as well.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: Entirely too convoluted for kids and implausible even by the standards set by the original concept.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: Here's a late-August dog-days atrocity from the "aren't farts funny?" school of filmmaking.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: Features even more toddlers acting in a way only collectors of velvet paintings will consider irresistible.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: As for anyone else who may experience a sudden need for therapy after sitting through this, you're on your own.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: Falls short on nearly every level, from production values to an inexplicable cameo by Whoopi Goldberg.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: So bad that I predict there will be drinking games set around viewing it someday.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: The first Baby Geniuses, released in 1999, was one of the most inane, humorless, ill-conceived, poorly acted comedies of the year. As difficult as it is to imagine, the sequel is even worse, earning an F.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
review: Villainy toward the infant class now comes from Jon Voight, descending to the depths of his 37-year-career.

title: House of the Dead
review: Whether this is a good or bad thing depends on just how much 14-year-old boy you've got in ya.

title: House of the Dead
review: There's scarcely a whiff of originality in the zombie horror picture House of the Dead, but Uwe Boll has directed it with enough energy and style that it adds up to passably mindless if grisly fun.

title: House of the Dead
review: Director Uwe Boll wholeheartedly embraces the film's concept, and with some fancy editing and a pulsing soundtrack, the effect really is like watching a video game.

title: House of the Dead
review: Somewhere between cartoonishly bad for comic effect and bad because the filmmakers didn't really give a damn, The House of the Dead is, at least, unpretentiously dumb.

title: House of the Dead
review: House of the Dead, sadly, is so bad it's bad.

title: House of the Dead
review: Does little more than add another title to the very long list of movies influenced by George Romero's 1968 horror classic, "Night of the Living Dead."

title: House of the Dead
review: Much poorly choreographed gunplay, many lovingly rendered head explosions, and some half-assed exposition about centuries-old, immortality-seeking pirates follow, with nothing to recommend House Of The Dead to anyone but the most undiscriminating zombie-movie fans.

title: House of the Dead
review: Here’s a would-be horror film that contains not one ounce of professional pride in its making, not one shred of technical competence. This is one of the worst films of recent times.

title: House of the Dead
review: Laughable performances.

title: House of the Dead
review: Based on a video game, far exceeds expectations -- in negative ways that inspire thoughts of less than zero stars.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: Full of gumption, Clarkson and Guarini soldier on, seemingy unaware that the perfectly adequate singing voices that brought them to the big screen are being drowned out, on a half-dozen same-sounding songs, by an overlayered backup group.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: They play cotton candy effigies of themselves named Kelly and Justin, and the best that can be said is that they don't embarrass themselves.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: The most resounding thuds in From Justin to Kelly, however, come from the musical numbers.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: A feather-light musical rushed into production to capitalize on American Idol-frenzy, is nothing more than an excuse to give the two leads several musical numbers, a la those Frankie Avalon-Annette Funicello "Beach Blanket Bingo" movies, and with just about the same amount of substance, too.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: In this frothy beach movie, they make pop-music lite together but create an utterly unconvincing romantic couple, seeming more like siblings or best friends. From Ruben to Clay might work better.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: Arguably the most insipid movie released so far this century.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: Aspires to be a "Beach Blanket Bingo" redux with a gangbang Grease finale, but it plays like junior high Neil LaBute filmed by an elementary school AV squad.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: Just one of those films, a bottomless well of snark fodder that may come and go in theatres but will surely be spun innumerable times on DVD at parties in the years to come.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: More than anything, From Justin To Kelly needs Simon Cowell, the fork-tongued Idol judge who gives the show its only sliver of tension.

title: From Justin to Kelly
review: More than awful, more than dreadful, and easily the worst beach movie ever made.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: The tired racial stereotypes that Caddy inserts into the old Caddyshack-style "slobs vs. snobs" formula should probably make it much more offensive than it is.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: An instantly forgettable trifle.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: His C-Note is essentially a one-note character. And that note is flat.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: Ultimately this is utterly forgettable stuff, not even managing to fulfill its mandate of mindless summer fun.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: No, it’s not Caddyshack -- just swap Jews (Rodney Dangerfield) for blacks (Big Boi) and you’ve got Who’s Your Caddy?. The movie, of course, is terrible.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: There’s probably more wit and pointed social commentary in the average four-minute OutKast song than in the entirety of Who’s Your Caddy?

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: As it develops, Who's Your Caddy? just becomes depressing. You want to alert the United Negro College Fund: A mind has terribly gone to waste.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: Must be counted as a forfeit.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: The sport of golf has seen its fair share of vulgar comedies over the last 30 years or so.

title: Who's Your Caddy?
review: An offensive, comedy-free comedy.

title: Glitter
review: Glitter is the week's only major Hollywood release, and it offers considerable escapist entertainment while hitting an affirmative note.

title: Glitter
review: Glitter is, if nothing else, comfortable with what it is, namely earnestly made, wholehearted schlock.

title: Glitter
review: This is the worst performance by a pop star in a dramatic role since Madonna suited up for "Shanghai Surprise."

title: Glitter
review: It doesn't help that Glitter is such a derivative mishmash of cinematic and real-life situations that it's nearly impossible to count all the ways.

title: Glitter
review: It's doubtful that even a real actress could have triumphed over the rusty tinsel of Glitter, a hapless, retro-'80s ''Star Is Born.''

title: Glitter
review: A butt-numbing exercise in tedium, sporadically redeemed by moments of unintentional hilarity.

title: Glitter
review: Glitter does no one any favors.

title: Glitter
review: Glitter deserves yet another title: "A Star Is Dull." As phony a vehicle as one could possibly concoct for a wannabe movie star, pic carries Mariah Carey into a swamp of gloppy melodrama.

title: Glitter
review: Mostly dross, an unintentionally hilarious compendium of time-tested cinematic clichés that illustrates the chasm between hopeful imitation and successful duplication.

title: Glitter
review: Worst movie of the year.

title: Son of the Mask
review: The characters twirl around like mini tornadoes, but between random brash moments of technological eye-tickling, Son of the Mask sags more than it spins.

title: Son of the Mask
review: In actuality, it's silly fun custom-tailored for reluctant young fathers and that entire clan of 20-something man-children who still read comic books and play video games, guys who do everything possible to resist the notion of adult responsibility.

title: Son of the Mask
review: At its heart is a deep, unresolved ambivalence about child rearing.

title: Son of the Mask
review: Even with a new leading man and a more family-friendly rating, some things never change: The Mask still stars Industrial Light & Magic.

title: Son of the Mask
review: The net result is a truly numbing experience.

title: Son of the Mask
review: Most of the animated sequences, capably mixed with live action, leave a bad aftertaste, particularly when the ultimate fate of one beaten and battered human bystander after another is left callously unresolved. In other words, parents beware.

title: Son of the Mask
review: Cumming's antic acting is the only asset of this boisterous comedy.

title: Son of the Mask
review: Loud, mean-spirited and generally obnoxious, Son of the Mask makes the boisterous 1994 original look downright demure and refined.

title: Son of the Mask
review: One presumes the only thing worse than making this disaster is actually watching it; wouldn't wish either on anyone.

title: Son of the Mask
review: An irredeemable mess, a computer-animated Punch and Judy show without wit, heart or a single memorable performance.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Since the film is based on the Atari video game of the same name, it also has much to appeal to headbangers: fast pace, lots of gadgets, monsters, explosive special effects, plenty of inscrutable plot twists and turns.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Here is the horror-action genre at its silliest and most uninspired.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Fans of the source material probably won't be switching platforms to catch this bizarre Lions Gate pickup, and non-fans definitely won't.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: That this bit of pustulence is based on a video game of the same name is no surprise. It explains the thin plot, characters and abundant gunplay.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Slater narrates as if reading a restaurant menu. Reid seems to have learned each long sentence in segments, so she wouldn't be overtaxed.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Even Boll seems to lose interest as the story unravels. By that time, the supernatural cliches, plot inconsistencies, dead ends and red herrings have piled up so high you can barely see the screen.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: Director Uwe Boll ("House of the Dead") has made a cottage industry out of this kind of junk. Maybe it's time for him to close up shop.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: One of those rare instances of a movie being so bad ... it's still really bad.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: This is definitely for people who 1) love the video game, 2) think Slater and Dorff are eminently watchable, no matter what bad flick they're in and 3) are wearing industrial-strength ear plugs.

title: Alone in the Dark
review: So inept on every level, you wonder why the distributor didn't release it straight to video, or better, toss it directly into the trash.

title: Gigli
review: A watchable bad movie, but it's far from your typical cookie-cutter blockbuster. There are no shoot-outs or car chases, and there isn't much romantic suspense, either.

title: Gigli
review: Writer-director Martin Brest lends the film a professional sheen, and his stars (who some rumors suggest may have become romantically involved) have charisma to spare, but the film has all the charge and momentum of a Paxil ad.

title: Gigli
review: Turns out to be merely bad -- not a train wreck, not the crime against humanity it's been rumored to be.

title: Gigli
review: After five minutes, Christopher Walken vanishes. We wait vainly for the next 90 minutes for someone, anyone to bring that kind of danger, unpredictability and vitality to a story as drab as army fatigues.

title: Gigli
review: The problem with Gigli is that it is an inept attempt to do Elmore Leonard by Martin Brest, a filmmaker whose coarse sensibility makes him catastrophically unqualified to the task.

title: Gigli
review: Excruciating...The movie proves to be singularly unfunny and static almost from the non-get-go. Virtually nothing happens; the movie is all premise.

title: Gigli
review: Gigli is a disaster.

title: Gigli
review: A hypnotic, black hole of a movie that sucks reputations, careers and goodwill down its vortex. Rarely has a movie that doesn't star Madonna achieved such a skin-crawling mixture of deluded preening and bungled humour.

title: Gigli
review: The worst movie -- all right, the worst allegedly major movie -- of our admittedly young century. More stupefying follies may come, but it's impossible to imagine how they'll beat this one for staggering idiocy, fatuousness or pretension.

title: Gigli
review: The most thoroughly joyless and inept film of the year, and one of the worst of the decade. We're talking about a disaster, and not of the fun "Showgirls" variety, either.

title: Epic Movie
review: The humor is coarse and occasionally funny. The archly bombastic score, by Edward Sheamur, is the only thing you might call witty. But happily, Jennifer Coolidge and Fred Willard show up, as the White Bitch and Aslo the Lion, to add some easy, demented class.

title: Epic Movie
review: If imitation is the sincerest form of flattery, big studio Hollywood hitmakers should consider themselves lauded to the max in Jason Friedberg and Aaron Selzer's Epic Movie, the latest (and epically unfunny) entry in the movie parody franchise.

title: Epic Movie
review: The cinematic equivalent of a tapeworm, this delivers few laughs beyond the initial chuckles of recognition. Seltzer and Friedberg (who also directed) have another script in development called "Raunchy Movie"; apparently one idea they haven't yet considered is "Watchable Movie."

title: Epic Movie
review: Epic Movie is a waste of time. It's like a bad issue of "Cracked Magazine" come to life. It's not so much painful as it is sleep inducing.

title: Epic Movie
review: The sadists responsible for the painfully unfunny "Date Movie" (2006) are back, and this time they've outdone themselves: This theater-clearer is even less amusing than its terrible predecessor, a spoof so devoid of laughs it can longer be categorized as a comedy.

title: Epic Movie
review: Still, if it gets little else right, at least Epic Movie is accurately titled: It may be only 86 minutes long, but it feels as if it lasts forever.

title: Epic Movie
review: Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer must be stopped. For the last two years, this filmmaking team has created a series of spoof movies so feeble, shoddy and unfunny that they may be part of a diabolical, "Manchurian Candidate"-like plot to stunt the intellectual development of American adolescents.

title: Epic Movie
review: By the time this dud drops on NetFlix, it'll be as obsolete as a Chia pet jokebook.

title: Epic Movie
review: This spoof of "The Da Vinci Code," "Pirates of the Caribbean," "Harry Potter," "The Chronicles of Narnia" and other recent blockbusters piles up sex gags, toilet gags and make-you-gag gags.

title: Epic Movie
review: The willful sloppiness and retrograde gags make Epic Movie, which was not shown to critics, an inevitable byproduct of our Internet video era. It seems downloaded and projected onto the screen, a failing online-film-school project paid for and put out by a Hollywood movie studio. That said, very little on YouTube is this unentertaining.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: Scientology or not, the movie is a battlefield bummer that makes you want to revolt.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: So heavy and lifeless that you keep waiting for those three little front-row kibitzers from "Mystery Science Theatre 3000" to appear at the bottom of the screen to start goofing on it.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: Shot after shot photographed at wobbly, off-center angles for no particular reason, weigh every action sequence down with super-slo-mo in lame imitation of "The Matrix" or end every single scene with a vertical wipe.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: Yet the overall look, though derivative ("The Matrix," "Blade Runner," "Waterworld," etc.), rates as Battlefield's one non-guilty pleasure.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: A ghastly, unappealing mess that lacks a single absorbing character, engaging story line or entertaining snippet of dialogue.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: The film is Travolta's baby, but indifference and boredom is everywhere.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: The dialogue is inane, the acting wooden, and Roger Christian's directing choices are a lesson in sci-fi film cliché.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: The only danger in seeing this film is in busting a gut at its unintentional hilarity.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: In the pantheon of cinematic train wrecks, from "Ishtar" to "Waterworld," set a place at the table for Battlefield Earth.

title: Battlefield Earth
review: With this kind of epic ineptitude -- hell, the flick is set in the year 3000 -- you go for "worst of the millennium."

title: Baby Geniuses
review: This movie wasn't nearly as bad as I thought it would be. It's still not that good though.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: Bad films are easy to make, but a film as unpleasant as Baby Geniuses' achieves a kind of grandeur.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: About as endearing as unanesthetized gum surgery.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: The hokey dialogue and witless physical gags keep everything painful and hectoring.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: There are ticklish moments, but no real laughs.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: A thoroughly misguided, unfunny film that proves you shouldn't beat a dead horse.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: The worst movie of 1999.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: One way to get through Baby Geniuses is to think about whether it really is the worst movie you've ever seen. Probably not, but pretty darn close.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: A stupid comedy with toddlers talking like hip '90s grown-ups.

title: Baby Geniuses
review: Trying to encapsulate the movie's storyline is not possible; it doesn't appear to have one.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: May or may not appeal to fans of the Japanese fantasy franchise it is based on, but aficionados of apocalyptic teenybopper kung fu extravaganzas are in for a real treat.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Far more entertaining than it deserves to be, unless you're a 10-year-old boy, in which case it's only the greatest movie ever made.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: A popular Japanese manga series gets a pleasing if paint-by-numbers live-action makeover in Dragonball Evolution, which half-heartedly tries to keep the faith for its pubescent male fanbase.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Marvel at the fact that something this trippy made it to our local multiplex.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Nearly all the actors seem to be having a good time, and the action moves so fast that you don't mind when something nuts happens.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: The film is crammed with treats for old-school "Dragonball" fans, from the inclusion of all these characters (who don't actually do much) to the moment when spiky-haired Goku dons his orange gi. For everyone else, this amounts to another seen-it-before, probably-willing-to-see-it-again distraction.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Director James Wong ("Final Destination") and writer Ben Ramsey are utterly blasé in their approach to the series' mythology and structure, cobbling together an 84-minute movie that seems to exist only to rile up fanboys. On that count -- and that count alone -- Dragonball Evolution triumphs.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Bottom line: costumed Goku and Chi Chi cosplayers may argue the finer points of this adaptation, but it is fairly dazzling it its own overextended, futurist-teenpulp fashion, and Chow makes a vastly more entertaining Roshi than he did a King.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Just know there's a whole lot more great stuff out there than just what Evolution has in store for you -- namely, the anime that it was based on.

title: Dragonball Evolution
review: Completely lacking in visual, narrative or stylistic coherence, the film also suffers from cheap-looking visual effects and poorly staged and edited action sequences that will not exactly please the fanboys.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: Exceptionally well-made family entertainment, this 3 Ninjas is constantly inventive, action-filled and funny, with a flourish of good special effects.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: The incredible silliness doesn’t quite erase the bad taste of this kid’s movie featuring an implied dozen civilian casualties, but it helps.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: Pathetic yet stupidly entertaining for several minutes of its interminable running time, 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain makes half its cast look like retreads and half like fresh ponies desperately karate-kicking a dud script to see if it has any signs of life.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: For most moviegoers over 12, this, the fourth Three Ninjas movie, will be interminably boring. But it's possible that young children will enjoy the film, since it falls into both the action category and the children-are-smart-adults-can't-do-anything-right genre.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: As the fourth entry of a painfully uninspired series, this version features new actors portraying the trio of adolescent warriors. [10 Apr 1998, p.49]

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: Only small children with limited attention spans will be impressed by the lackluster kung-foolishness in 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain.

title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain
review: The best you can say is that it's all pretty harmless and pretty stupid.

title: Date Movie
review: Aaron Seltzer and Jason Friedberg, who wrote the screenplay, have crammed dozens of movie parodies into this deliberately juvenile spoof of romantic comedies. Mr. Seltzer, who directed, has made very few of them funny.

title: Date Movie
review: This anemic genre parody from two of the six writers of "Scary Movie" strives for the goofball precision of the brothers Zucker and, long before it reaches the end of its 70-odd minutes, gives you newfound respect for the comic genius of the brothers Wayans (two of the other writers of "Scary Movie").

title: Date Movie
review: A lame pastiche of Hollywood romances.

title: Date Movie
review: The choice is yours: Shell out 10 bucks for this dire spoof of recent romantic comedies a la "Scary Movie" and "Not Another Teen Movie", or toss your 12-year-old nephew a quarter and get him to act out scenes from his favorite movies for 80 minutes: The entertainment value will be about the same.

title: Date Movie
review: Arguably the lamest of all the free-wheeling genre parodies that have taken flight since "Airplane!," Date Movie is stupefyingly unfunny in its attempts to mock romantic comedies, celebrities, reality TV shows and anything else that pops into the heads of its creators.

title: Date Movie
review: The only thing remotely resembling parody in this depressing waste of time and money is Jennifer Coolidge's sendup of Barbra Streisand as an over-the-top string of Jewish mother clichés.

title: Date Movie
review: "Comedy is hard," said Steve Martin. For the writers of Date Movie, it's apparently impossible.

title: Date Movie
review: A collection of throwaway gags from other movies, a big blue recycling barrel of comedy waiting for the trash collector. It's rated PG-13 because 13 is the maximum age of those who might find it funny.

title: Date Movie
review: Elapsed time before I walked out: 29 minutes Total laughs (in that period): 0

title: Date Movie
review: Date Movie is a good date movie in one sense: If you're still speaking to the person who brought you to see this, you just might have a future together.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Less classic Mel Brooks than middling "Best Week Ever."

title: Meet the Spartans
review: The best thing in Meet the Spartans is the swift kick in the bombast it delivers to the oh-no-not-us homoeroticism of "300."

title: Meet the Spartans
review: The musical number that runs during the closing credits funnier than anything that precedes it, which isn't saying much.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Writer-directors Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer basically reprise the tired formula from their earlier efforts, which is to throw in as many pop culture references as possible to cover up the lack of any real wit.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Overkill is what Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer do best: as the uncontested titans of the parody genre (with fingers in everything from the “Scary Movie” franchise to the more recent “Epic Movie”) they continue to prove that ridiculing other movies is much easier than making your own.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Meet the Spartans is a mild improvement over their "Epic Movie," which is like saying that a debilitating fever is more fun than appendicitis, but what’s shocking is how lazy it is, which is a shame for former UK child star/pop singer Sean Maguire, whose Gerard Butler impersonation is spot-on.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Lazy, lame and painfully unfunny, Meet the Spartans is yet another scrambled-genre parody.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Meet The Spartans gamely alternates between unfunny gay jokes and violent pratfalls for a good 80 minutes, finding time for not one, but two musical dance numbers set to "I Will Survive."

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Witless, tasteless, formless spoof.

title: Meet the Spartans
review: Hey, guys, when you repurpose a disco hit to poke fun at gay men, not only do you look like assholes, you look like assholes who rip their jokes off of YouTube.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence) is just as repulsive, but far louder, and in color.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: Tom Six's threequel races to the bottom with abandon, all while indulging in tired wink-wink self-consciousness that includes Six himself showing up to witness his movie monster made real (and to be slandered by Laser as "a poop-infatuated toddler").

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: Neither Scary nor eye-rollingly fun, The Human Centipede 3 (Final Sequence) is the dullest entry in an atrocious trilogy.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: Six just wants to shock, though his imagination is so primitive that the effort is strained and a bit pathetic. Initially abrasive, the whole enterprise grows simply tedious well before the now-epically-scaled titular phenom is unveiled in the prison yard.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: Tom Six has achieved the seemingly impossible: He's made a film even less watchable than "The Human Centipede II."

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: The thing that wrecks The Human Centipede III isn’t how the film is disgustingly, degradingly unclean; instead, Six’s work is ruined by how his film is desperately, depressingly unclever.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: It’s only fitting that a series that began with the concept of linking the digestive tracts of three people would end by feasting on its own shit.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: The gross-out gore scenes and poop jokes are there, too, as is to be expected. The direction is bad, the acting is worse, and it’s lit to mimic the soap-opera effect on a poorly calibrated HDTV. Basically, The Human Centipede III is an unsexy "Ilsa" movie, and it’s just as impossible to sit through as that sounds.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: Even by the series’ already low standards, The Human Centipede Part 3 is crap.

title: The Human Centipede III (Final Sequence)
review: As horror, it's frightless and boring. As comedy, it's desperate and laughless. As exploitation, it's exceedingly dull. Even excrement was once something of substance. The Human Centipede III: Final Sequence is just rancid air. It too shall pass.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Lorraine Gary has some affecting moments as Ellen, but Jaws the Revenge is mild and predictable, the very things an adventure movie should never be.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Jaws the Revenge is not simply a bad movie, but also a stupid and incompetent one - a ripoff.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Angry fish travels to the Bahamas for the Christmas holidays, plotting revenge against the family of a vacationing New England widow (Lorraine Gary). Noel, noel, a charming gift idea with suggestions of inverted seasonal myth—until director Joseph Sargent swamps it all in antimythical literalism and predictable lunchtime theater.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Significantly worse than the rest of the series, this film is one of the worst flops in recent cinema.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: While it's mostly just a matter of waiting till feeding time, there is a hint that somebody was trying to foist some Symbolism onto the shark: as mother and son suffer an attack of the Oedipals, the creature keeps popping up grinning. Sadly, this attempt at a bit of Art (which could have had hilarious consequences) is ditched, and the film concludes with a few people getting chewed before a messy happy ending amid chunks of exploding shark.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Even the special effects are lame in this one, offering a latex shark that is about as realistic as a fake goldfish. Poorly directed by Joseph Sargent, who relies heavily on blood and fast editing to create tension since there certainly isn't any written into the script.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: Pacing leaves a lot to be desired and the moment-of-attack sequences, full of jagged cuts and a great deal of noise, more closely resemble the view from inside a washing machine.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: In a wicked mess of unmatched water shots and dreadful interior airplane sequences, the characters outlined in little blue halos, the performances range from the mortifying to the merely immemorable. Against all odds, Lance Guest and Karen Young manage to be warm and credible. Podgy but game, Michael Caine, bravely attempts mouth-to-mouth resusitation on a role which is little more than anecdotes strung together. It is not his finest hour.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: The director, Joseph Sargent, doesn't bring out any of the possibilities in the material -- not even the scary ones. And Michael Caine is wasted, though not completely. He manages to provide at least a little suspense, even if it's the extracurricular sort, by raising the question: Will an Oscar winner be allowed to become fish food?

title: Jaws: The Revenge
review: There's more suspense in On Golden Pond. And when the predictable ending comes, it has none of the titanic man-versus-beast struggle of the original. It all happens so quickly, you wonder if you've missed something. But, no you haven't, because there it is -- the familiar calm sea . . . of credits.

title: Kazaam
review: The movie is decidedly old-fashioned, aiming to send kids and their parents out of the theater feeling good about themselves.

title: Kazaam
review: As for Shaquille O'Neal, given his own three wishes the next time, he should go for a script, a director and an interesting character.

title: Kazaam
review: Is Kazaam racist? In effect, yes. But it'sracism linked to bad marketing: You can't really mix a black-pride rap film with a revamped version of "Free Willie" and expect them to magically jibe.

title: Kazaam
review: It takes the movie all of 15 minutes to descend into sub-Spielbergian banalities about poor Max's search for his absentee dad.

title: Kazaam
review: The odd truth is that the film's novice star is better than the material.

title: Kazaam
review: Memo to Shaquille O'Neal: Don't give up your night job.

title: Kazaam
review: The plot is hamstrung by trite formulas, and there's too much violence and family tension for very young viewers. Shaquille O'Neal is likable as the title character, though.

title: Kazaam
review: This is as witless as movies come -- an unamusing, moronic blend of horrible acting and inept screenwriting.

title: Kazaam
review: Original enough to come up with new ways to go wrong. For one, the film is a blatant showcase to promote O'Neal as a rap artist.

title: Kazaam
review: It's full of special effects that are big on smoke and noise, but short on logic and payoff.

title: BloodRayne
review: There are all sorts of noteworthy people in this silly vampire epic, including acting greats Sir Ben Kingsley and Geraldine Chaplin, but the only artist this critic wants to heap praise upon is the regrettably unidentified Supervisor of Blood Splatter: Nice work, dude.

title: BloodRayne
review: The only thing left unsliced is the ham in BloodRayne, yet another video game adaptation by German genre specialist Uwe Boll and a movie with more fading - or faded - talent than an Italian basketball team.

title: BloodRayne
review: With minimal flare and maximal gore, Boll simply delivers the turgid drama and incompetently staged action sequences that have made him the unstoppable Big Boss of the gaming community.

title: BloodRayne
review: Attention, Ben Kingsley (I mean, Sir Ben Kingsley): It's officially time to turn in your Oscar.

title: BloodRayne
review: Yet another ill-conceived big screen videogame adaptation.

title: BloodRayne
review: Why do moviegoers and gamers keep going to see video-game-based movies when neither group is ever happy with the results?

title: BloodRayne
review: While there's no fun in mediocrity, ludicrousness is another matter. Boll is the best at what he does, and what he does is make truly terrible films.

title: BloodRayne
review: Semicoherent.

title: BloodRayne
review: Anemic action-fantasy.

title: BloodRayne
review: Maybe everyone involved was hoping that no one would see this movie, but Madsen is the only one who should fear anyone seeing his work.

title: Rollerball
review: The game itself is meaningless, and the movie, much the same way, likes it like that.

title: Rollerball
review: What's up with director John McTiernan? The man has got to get a career of his own -- sponging off the pale leavings of Norman Jewison just won't do.

title: Rollerball
review: It's too bad this Rollerball veered off-track so swiftly, derailed by bad writing and possibly also by some of that extensive post-production reworking.

title: Rollerball
review: There's something junior varsity about the whole sensibility that makes the new version seem more dated than the old one.

title: Rollerball
review: The current version, however, like its predecessor, fails as entertainment. Mr. McTiernan's remake may be lighter on its feet -- the sober-minded original was as graceful as a tap-dancing rhino -- but it is just as boring and as obvious.

title: Rollerball
review: Only those attracted to "Waterworld" or "Last Action Hero" level big-budget disasters need bother with this one.

title: Rollerball
review: An incoherent mess, a jumble of footage in search of plot, meaning, rhythm and sense.

title: Rollerball
review: Will surely end up as one of this year’s worst films.

title: Rollerball
review: Plentiful helpings of dreadful acting, confusing action cinematography, choppy editing and embarrassing dialogue, with the added bonus of a plot almost as dumb as that of the original film.

title: Rollerball
review: Sheer chaos on wheels, a hysterically edited jumble that defies belief at nearly every juncture.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: This belabored summertime sequel is moderately less vulgar, certainly less expensive and, if possible, even less funny than its forerunning bomb, "Daddy Day Care."

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: A tired and unnecessary sequel.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: This terrible sequel to a bad movie was directed by Fred Savage, the now-grown star of "The Wonder Years," though there's no evidence of any behind-the-scenes adult supervision.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: Innocuous amusement for 5- to 8-year-olds and other people stuck in the anal stage of development.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: Any scrap of charm or honest-to-goodness humor already possessed in limited quantities by the original has been relegated to the outhouse in this sorry follow-up.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: This sequel to the 2003 Eddie Murphy comedy may appeal to auds still young enough not to have seen it all before, or who still find flatulence hilarious, or who think adults, when agitated, flail about like epileptic marionettes.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: A recruiting poster for kids, insisting that there’s no domestic problem that military values can’t solve.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: If you're looking for a modern-day "Meatballs" - or, for that matter, "Meatballs 4" - you're out of luck.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: Too predictable, but kids should like it.

title: Daddy Day Camp
review: A comedy for no ages, has an amazing amount of CGI - Cuba Gooding Incompetence.

title: Bratz
review: Finally, a postfeminist multicultural musical extravaganza for 8-year-old girls. Is Bratz not the most totally stylin' movie ever? Grownups won't think so, but for their daughters who share a "passion for fashion" with the dolls that are giving Barbie a run for her money, it will be the event of the season.

title: Bratz
review: A movie based on a doll line, is an M&M-colored high school fantasia for aspirational 10- and 12-year-old girls who'll be shocked (or, hopefully, delighted) when they get to ninth grade and find out life isn't so super-Bratz-fabulous.

title: Bratz
review: Bratz's strong anti-clique sermonizing would be slightly more convincing if it weren't tethered to a movie romanticizing the most awesome clique ever.

title: Bratz
review: Bratz’s references and parodies are consistently on-target, if always way too over-the-top. Every line of dialogue could plausibly take an exclamation point.

title: Bratz
review: This is a movie for a grade-schooler's -- a female grade-schooler's -- sensibility. It's earnest, silly and sweet, with just enough food fights and musical numbers to keep everyone else from gagging on the goo.

title: Bratz
review: A silly movie that's essentially a series of clichés strung together into a semblance of a movie.

title: Bratz
review: In the end, the most offensive part of Bratz isn't its stereotypes or brand expansion; it's the sorry state of Jon Voight's career.

title: Bratz
review: Bratz is way too long.

title: Bratz
review: It's a movie on the wrong side side of the so-bad-it's-good line.

title: Bratz
review: The most horrifying film of 2007, Bratz is based on the popular line of collagen-lipped, doe-eyed slut-ette dolls and their male companions, "the boys with a passion for fashion ... and the Bratz!" (In other words, they're bi-curious.)

title: Left Behind
review: The film’s appeal is largely dependent on Cage; Left Behind is a batshit-crazy Cage cult classic of a radically new stripe.

title: Left Behind
review: It’s inoffensive, unless you take umbrage at the idea that the only people who know not to steal are True Believers and all that keeps society from an instant meltdown are the Faithful.

title: Left Behind
review: Has all the subtlety of a sledgehammer and production values that verge on parody.

title: Left Behind
review: The Rapture won’t come soon enough for the unfortunate souls forced to suffer through Left Behind.

title: Left Behind
review: That lack of concern for the way people actually interact renders the film useless as entertainment, or as a conversion tool.

title: Left Behind
review: This Left Behind may be worse than the last Left Behind, but it’s much less boring, thanks in part to the commitment of its star, who plays the often ludicrous material with the straightest of faces. The Cage works in mysterious ways.

title: Left Behind
review: With a “Sharknado”-inspired visual style and a deeply weary lead performance from Nicolas Cage, Left Behind is cheap-looking, overwrought kitsch of the most unintentionally hilarious order.

title: Left Behind
review: This failed epic — really, an epic failure — would barely be noticed, were it not for former Oscar-winner Nicolas Cage taking on a “Sharknado”-quality remake of a Kirk Cameron movie.

title: Left Behind
review: Cage is going for manly, if conflicted, family-guy confidence in this role, but somehow it comes off as nuttier than the events surrounding him.

title: Left Behind
review: At best, Left Behind is shoddily made sensationalist propaganda — with atrocious acting — that barely registers as entertainment. At worst, it's profoundly moronic.

title: Hercules in New York
review: This unearthed cheapie and fast-forwarder's delight is redeemed by the dubbed- in cathedral tones (they're vintage gladiator pic) coming from our hero's larnyx. [20 Dec 1991, p.3D]

title: Hercules in New York
review: For some reason, producer Wisberg decided to revive the long dead Hercules craze, and luckily it didn't take.

title: Hercules in New York
review: When you become a megastar like Arnold Schwarzenegger, you must expect your past to jump up and bite you - especially if you've made a stinker like this one. A great rental for frat parties, this Manhattan melodrama features Zeus sending Arnold, as Hercules, to present-day New York. [06 Dec 1991, p.62]

title: Hercules in New York
review: It's a comedy to be laughed at rather than with, largely because the producers decided to dub Arnold's Teutonic voice with that of another actor, one who sounds like he's giving bus departure announcements at the Port Authority Terminal. [30 Jan 1992, p.C7]

title: Teen Wolf Too
review: Given the grosses of the original, a sequel to Teen Wolf was inevitable-and it was inevitable, too, that the sequel would lose the quality of innocence and unconscious artfulness that made the first film work. The material has been broken down, analyzed and reassembled with scientific precision; what was instinctive in the original has become self-conscious and calculated in the followup, and the spirit is gone.

title: Teen Wolf Too
review: No one expects realism from a movie called Teen Wolf Too... still, the film makers could pretend to know what college is like, might try to liven up the kindly werewolf formula.

title: Teen Wolf Too
review: Teen Wolf Too is nothing a jar of Nair wouldn't cure.

title: Teen Wolf Too
review: Teen Wolf Too embellishes its inane, cookie-cutter plot with remote direction, witless dialogue and charmless characters.

title: Teen Wolf Too
review: Teen Wolf Too is a relentlessly idiotic sequel to 1985's Teen Wolf. [1 Dec 1987, p.B5]

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: A flick so terrifying and brilliant that it makes the two other Chainsaw sequels seem like After-School Specials. [20 May 1995, p.E6]

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: Nothing at all is surprising about Next Generation except how enjoyable it is. It won't become a classic, but is quite a hoot, like the cockamamie Motel Hell, as funny as it is frightening. [29 Aug 1997, p.32]

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: The other thing that sets this movie apart from the current crop of tongue-in-cheek screamers (I Know What You Did Last Summer, Scream) is that it's actually perversely intriguing, rather than just clever. [03 Nov 1997, p.C2]

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: Manages the difficult feat of being genuinely scary and sharply self-satirical all at once.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: Bits and pieces of the story will, on occasion, leave you scratching your head but it, nevertheless, moves rapidly enough to keep you scurrying to keep pace with the new business at hand.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: Its own efforts to be tongue-in-cheek, as with a backwoods gunman who quotes Emerson and Machiavelli, fall seriously flat. But should anyone have the patience to look closely, the two leading players do show signs of what would soon make them famous.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: Henkel's directing debut isn't incompetent: It's just derivative, pointless and tediously repetitive.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: A slightly above-average slasher film that's only partially redeemed by small but endearingly loopy shreds of black humor.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: The movie recapitulates the absurdist tabloid-redneck comedy of the great, original Chainsaw without a hint of its primal terror.

title: The Return of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
review: The bottom line is that the only Texas Chainsaw Massacre movie that you need is to see is the first.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: There have been worse ideas, but in this case the execution isn’t good enough to bring the notion of an emoji movie to funky, surprising life.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: If not always imaginative or digestible, the look of the settings and characters should keep kids awake for 86 minutes; and if the trick that eventually saves the day makes very little sense to critical moviegoers, at least it's cutely frantic eye candy.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: The most distressing aspect about The Emoji Movie is that a spectacle this self-evidently soulless no longer feels like a new low. It doesn’t even leave a dent.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: There was probably never going to be a version of this film that would prove even remotely plausible as a movie someone felt passionately about making for artistic reasons; as far as expanding on smartphone-related IP, this is an even weaker starting point than Sony Animation’s recent The Angry Birds Movie.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: There are plenty of words that can describe The Emoji Movie. Here are a few of them: Unfunny. Saccharine. Nonsensical. Painful. And, of course, crappy. (If you prefer the poop emoji, that works too.)

title: The Emoji Movie
review: A film as mindless and disposable as most smartphone apps — and nowhere near as addictive — Sony’s animated The Emoji Movie is a calamitous comedy that inadvertently shows how difficult it is to pull off the witty, imaginative world-building that Pixar makes seem so breezy.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: The Emoji Movie is a waste of time, resources, and a bunch of comedians’ voices, plus a premise that actually had the potential to do some small good in the world. It’s less of a movie and more of an insult.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: It is a soul-crushing disaster because it lacks humor, wit, ideas, visual style, compelling performances, a point of view or any other distinguishing characteristic that would make it anything but a complete waste of your time, not to mention that of the diligent animators who brought this catastrophe into being.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: The only thing worse than the dialogue is the absurd product placement.

title: The Emoji Movie
review: It is one of the darkest, most dismaying films I have ever seen, much less one ostensibly made for children.

title: Slender Man
review: If the story behind this chilling internet creation could have matched the quality of those aforementioned strong points, Sony would have a real horror gem on their hands.

title: Slender Man
review: In a movie this flat-out dull, even a tasteful lack of direct exploitation feels like a failure of nerve.

title: Slender Man
review: Give this literally and figuratively bloodless spooker a pass.

title: Slender Man
review: The movie is a big disappointment, because ultimately Slender Man does not get the full-on creep-out treatment such an intriguing character deserves. Here he's just a generic horror bad guy, doing standard horror-bad-guy things. He could be anything, really, and therefore winds up, like the movie, being not much.

title: Slender Man
review: Birke's script is plainly straightforward, a simple supernatural chase story. It doesn't plumb the depths of what might make Slender Man scary, so Slender Man isn't scary at all.

title: Slender Man
review: Give White credit for the picture’s fairly eerie tone and look — darkened streets, foggy forests of spindly pines, shadows and more shadows. It’s just not worth more than the occasional hair-raising instant.

title: Slender Man
review: Sporadically, one can see the movie that Slender Man could have been, but it disappears like the title character’s victims.

title: Slender Man
review: Slender Man is the kind of movie in which images come before logic, because there really isn’t much logic. There’s just a movie out to goose you.

title: Slender Man
review: A tasteless and incredibly undercooked serving of the internet’s stalest Creepypasta, Slender Man aspires to be for the YouTube era what “The Ring” was to the last gasps of the VHS generation...there’s one fundamental difference that sets the two movies apart: “The Ring” is good, and Slender Man is terrible.

title: Slender Man
review: The most perfunctory horror picture I’ve seen in some time.

title: Barb Wire
review: David Hogan keeps the action moving and loaded with fights, gun battles and other action-trashy thrills. Lee is terrific.

title: Barb Wire
review: Lee elevates herself from the lower echelon of mere international super-babedom to the loftier realm of pulp myth. She is "It" with an exclamation mark.

title: Barb Wire
review: The filmmakers must have known they were not making a good movie, but they didn't use that as an excuse to be boring and lazy. Barb Wire has a high energy level, and a sense of deranged fun.

title: Barb Wire
review: It's a comic book movie in the broadest sense of the term, and although it's neither as emotionally resonant as "The Crow" nor as surreally goofy as "Tank Girl," Barb Wire still manages to get you going, Anderson Lee fan or not.

title: Barb Wire
review: Ought to be disreputable fun. Instead it ends up, all its explosions and exposed flesh notwithstanding, rather inert.

title: Barb Wire
review: Isn't much when it comes to either deliberate or inadvertent humor. But it does have a few amusing moments.

title: Barb Wire
review: Its main source is a comic book, but it might as well be a computer.

title: Barb Wire
review: The element of high camp that makes for enjoyable "good trash" isn't present.

title: Barb Wire
review: A convoluted mess, but there have been worse.

title: Barb Wire
review: Muddled futuristic thriller.

title: Feardotcom
review: Strange, how good feardotcom is, and how bad. The screenplay is a mess, and yet the visuals are so creative this is one of the rare bad films you might actually want to see.

title: Feardotcom
review: If sudden loud noises, relentless strobe lights, digital hallucinations and mutilated corpses make you jump, and you feel that nothing more is required for a good time at the movies, welcome to Feardotcom.

title: Feardotcom
review: Never quite realizes its potential to evoke the real horror of the Internet -- Yet, Malone has given the film a distinctive atmosphere and occasional flashes of his perverse sense of humor.

title: Feardotcom
review: There's a germ of an interesting idea here, but it's smothered by gloomy cinematography a la "Seven" (1995) and grating implausibilities, like the fact that everyone lives in the kind of cavernous, dankly art-directed dumps that only internet millionaires and trust fund twinkies can afford in the real New York.

title: Feardotcom
review: A low-rent, slow-witted horror flick notable chiefly for its hilariously unsuccessful attempt to pass off Luxembourg City as New York City.

title: Feardotcom
review: The story is a mess, some of the images offensive, the acting under par and the dialogue silly.

title: Feardotcom
review: Made with just enough craft to keep it from being the instantly dated camp howler its title promises, but it's quickly apparent that there's no thought or originality under its grim, familiar surface.

title: Feardotcom
review: This movie is plain stupid from the get go, but at least it looks good.

title: Feardotcom
review: The story leapfrogs abruptly from scene to scene, and it makes such a mockery of narrative logic and continuity that the cast tends to look either baffled (Dorff) or as if they're trying to remain unrecognized.

title: Feardotcom
review: The film, whose clumsy editing and dearth of establishing shots keep the viewer in an unintended state of confusion, is a corpse in its own right: It’s filled with the rotting ideas of far better movies.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Totally lame.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Hands-down, the best James Brolin-in-an-Italian-accent movie ever.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Pants and wheezes and hurls itself exhausted across the finish line after barely 65 minutes of movie, and then follows it with 15 minutes of end credits in an attempt to clock in as a feature film.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Lacking even a hint of humor or a watchable story, Disguise has distinguished itself as the summer's worst movie.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Imagine combining bad imitations of the "Ace Ventura" and "Austin Powers" movies and you'll have a rough idea of this feeble Dana Carvey farce.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Vehicle for Dana Carvey as a chameleonic crime-fighting imbecile is noisy, colorful and fart-gag-filled enough to amuse undiscriminating auds under the age of 10.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Painfully unfunny and misguided to boot.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: Mostly this happy train wreck feels like a longer, better movie that was chopped up and reassembled by retarded monkeys; what should have been a rush instead feels rushed.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: An awful, stillborn comedy assembled out of rusty spare parts from secret agent movies and run-of-the-mill ''Saturday Night Live'' skits.

title: The Master of Disguise
review: No one but a convict guilty of some truly heinous crime should have to sit through The Master of Disguise, an unbearably tedious and unfunny comedy.

title: Catwoman
review: I wouldn't call Catwoman incompetent, yet it has no visual grandeur, and very little surprise; you can tick off the story beats as if they'd been graphed.

title: Catwoman
review: Much like a cat, the movie is a superfluous gob of fluff with an attitude ranging from idiotic to nasty.

title: Catwoman
review: Catwoman, which talks about the "duality" inside all women (wild vs. docile, rapacious vs. cuddly), does have its guilty pleasures. Most of these come courtesy of ice queen Stone.

title: Catwoman
review: Like the action movies of yore (you know, the 1980s), Catwoman is simultaneously overstuffed and undernourished.

title: Catwoman
review: A howlingly silly, moderately diverting exercise in high, pointless style.

title: Catwoman
review: What the movie needs is a director, and what it gets instead is Pitof, a French visual-effects maestro so much fonder of technological wizardry than of human flesh that he manages to turn even his slinky, sinuous star attraction into a digitized synthespian frolicking about endless CGI cityscapes.

title: Catwoman
review: A catastrophe. This motion picture is an embarrassment to all involved.

title: Catwoman
review: Pitof can be blamed for the 89-cent digitized sets, the jerky or rubbery special effects, some clunky performances and more continuity errors than I could count.

title: Catwoman
review: Cartoonish effects and overacting make this more corn than catnip.

title: Catwoman
review: Silly, tedious, inept disaster.

title: Jack and Jill
review: What's more genuinely wacky is what a kick the movie can sometimes be, completely in spite of its big, flat stunt.

title: Jack and Jill
review: There are moments in Jack and Jill that are genuinely funny - and, just like countless family reunions, there are moments when you can't wait for it to end.

title: Jack and Jill
review: Then there's Pacino, out-of-place and yet somehow right at home. You want big? Al does BIG. And since is as close as we're likely to get to "Don Corleone Does Don Quixote," that alone is worth the price of admission.

title: Jack and Jill
review: There are a few funny moments in Jack and Jill, most of them celebrity cameos that also serve to affirm what a cool, connected celebrity Mr. Sandler is. The most sustained of these is the appearance of Al Pacino as himself, falling for Jill and giving the film a jolt of genuine zaniness. I'm sorry to say that this may be Mr. Pacino's most convincing performance in years.

title: Jack and Jill
review: Jack and Jill contains long stretches of squirm-inducing tedium in which Sandler riffs and ad-libs far longer than he should.

title: Jack and Jill
review: The unapologetic laziness and ineptitude of Jack's impersonation, which is played for cheap laughs, is just as lazy as Sandler's performance as the real Jill. You don't buy it for a minute.

title: Jack and Jill
review: Jack and Jill is witless and sloppily constructed, getting by on fart gags, homeless jokes, Latino stereotypes and that old favorite, explosive chimichanga diarrhea -- and no, not in an inspired "Bridesmaids" way.

title: Jack and Jill

title: Jack and Jill

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
review: Bucky Larson is a one-note joke played over and over and over.

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
review: It's an ugly movie to look at and a faintly nauseating one to sit through, truth be told.

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
review: Apparently no one told Ricci she was acting in a comedy, not a touching drama about a young woman overcoming a formative trauma to achieve her dreams.

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
review: This may be the worst movie Pauly Shore has ever been in. Think about that.

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star

title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
review: One of the most astonishingly unfunny films of this or any other year.

title: Police Academy: Mission to Moscow

title: Police Academy: Mission to Moscow

title: Police Academy: Mission to Moscow

title: Crossroads

title: Crossroads
review: So vanilla yet so transcendentally sleazy that its target audience seems to be pubescent girls and dirty old priests.

title: Crossroads

title: Crossroads

title: Crossroads

review: Spears is filmed and costumed in such a harsh, unflattering manner that it looks like Christina Aguilera bribed the crew to make her rival look as hideous as possible. title: Crossroads

title: Crossroads

review: Long, lumbering and endlessly unfunny.

title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd

title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd
review: The best thing I can say about this limp prequel to the Farrelly brothers' Dumb & Dumber is that it obliged me to check out the original, which I'd been studiously avoiding for years. If you haven't seen it, it's pretty funny, and mercifully light on the scatology and cheap sentiment of later Farrelly efforts.

title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd
review: To call it sophomoric would libel even the most pathetic, pimply underclassman.

title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd
review: Even with its scant running time, this nightmarish travesty barrels along with all the whipcord speed and nimble comedic grace of a loved one’s funeral.

review: The boys similarly deserve very minor props for choosing a satirical target that lends itself to satire: the glum, self-important Twilight novels and movies. Sadly, that's where the filmmakers' mild accomplishments end and the groaningly predictable hackwork begins.

title: Vampires Suck

title: Spice World

title: Spice World

review: Although the film is clearly trying to follow in the footsteps of the Beatles' classic, it's several long strides behind, lacking the same sense of originality, spontaneity, high energy, and joi de vivre.

title: Spice World
review: Shabbily filmed, thoroughly harmless Official Product.

title: Spice World
review: There are several non sequitur subplots woven together -- and that, along with a dearth of acting talent, is Spice World's biggest flaw.

title: Spice World
review: Bad as it may be, though, the film falls that one precious inch shy of being quite so awful that it achieves cult status; in short, it's just not bad enough to be any good.

title: Spice World
review: A promotional tool that establishes its superfluousness simply by existing, this clumsy, smirking movie has a bitter soul.

title: Spice World
review: They're so detached they can't even successfully lip-synch their own songs.

title: Spice World
review: Rarely has one movie seemed so predestined to reduce any and all attempted criticism to so many column inches of impotent gibberish.

review: The story's so sloppy that it contradicts itself constantly.

review: Sadly, the film's creaky, sometimes painful dialogue makes it all too easy to believe that it was genuinely co-written by a small child.

review: Marlon Wayans is clearly getting off on the gags, but the lazy, hard humor, and elastic joke-making eventually has a numbing effect.

review: At a minimum, a parody should be funnier than the film it’s sending up, but Fifty Shades of Black, a quick-and-dirty riff on last year’s S&M romance “Fifty Shades of Grey,” falls a laugh or two short of even that low standard.

title: Fifty Shades of Black
review: The funniest bit involves a particularly sadistic brand of torture that he inflicts on Hannah.... She quite rightly screams in protest, as should anyone forced to watch this movie.

review: A deserted island movie during which I desperately wished the characters had chosen one movie to take along if they were stranded on a deserted island, and were showing it to us instead of this one.

review: At no point should anyone mistake this for an actual movie. This is an extended beach video that will leave no one swept away.

review: There is no credible feeling here, no comedy, no eroticism.

review: This one’s for connoisseurs of the “totally preposterous crap” school of fantasy cinema.
