review: This South Korean pseudo-epic is some of the most ambitious cr-- I've ever seen.

title: D-War
review: All the thought seems to have gone into the marketing, and none into the unfathomably terrible script.

title: The Fog
review: This new Fog floats in on the fumes of the 1980 John Carpenter original, but the surprise is that it's arguably better.

title: The Fog
review: It's virtually indiscernible from any other contemporary horror film except for, well, the fog.

title: The Fog
review: Mildly scary here and there. It does not play by all the horror movie rules (e.g., the black guy always dies first). And the cast is good-looking.

title: The Fog
review: Director Rupert Wainwright fails to bring any style to the material, not producing a fraction of the suspense or wit generated by Carpenter in the original even while working with a far lesser budget.

title: The Fog
review: Unfortunately, interest lags between the grisly deaths, and, worse, none of the characters generates rooting interest.

title: The Fog
review: If the characters were more interesting, the long, long buildup to their night of ghostly reckoning might be suspenseful rather than tedious.

title: The Fog
review: Most of The Fog will seem drearily perfunctory even to those viewers who don't know Carpenter's version, which itself emulated the elegant gloom of Val Lewton's horror pics of the 1940s.

title: The Fog
review: The fog also does something genuinely eerie: It causes everyone in the cast to deliver dreadful performances and display inappropriate reactions when their friends are drowned, burned, stabbed or thrown into glass display cases.

title: The Fog
review: I was held in suspense throughout The Fog, aching to learn the answer to its central riddle: Why would any one remake such a crummy movie?

title: The Fog
review: It's too mediocre (and PG-13) to be classified as a horror film, too inane to be taken seriously and too uninteresting to be bothered with.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: In short, it’s a gift-wrapped part for Lohan, who plays her good-girl/bad-girl role with wit and an air of sly calculation.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: An intensely unpleasant killer-thriller mystery.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: The most shocking thing about this ludicrous serial-killer shocker, released the week troubled 21-year-old former child star Lindsay Lohan was arrested on DUI and cocaine-possession charges, is that it's the kind of film actresses generally make when their careers are well and truly on the skids.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: The film suggests Lohan probably (allegedly) should've gone after her agent the other night, not the mother of an ex-personal assistant.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: Much like the ongoing real-world meltdown of its troubled star, Lindsay Lohan, I Know Who Killed Me is a disaster that exerts a perverse fascination.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: Unless you derive pleasure from watching Lohan being tortured, there's no reason to subject yourself to this movie. Besides, if that's your goal, all you have to do is turn on tabloid TV. There's Lindsay's living hell of a life, being broadcast 24/7.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: Having broken free of the Disney machine that molded her, Lohan now seems intent on destroying her career and credibility on her own terms.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: There's a fresh candidate in the running for worst movie of 2007 honors.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: Sony dumped this sleazy, inept and worthless piece of torture porn into theaters yesterday.

title: I Know Who Killed Me
review: I can’t say I was too surprised by how risible, grotesque, and incoherent I Know Who Killed Me is. But I can’t say I was prepared for its pretentiousness. If the picture has any use at all, it’s as a case study in what happens when the talentless attempt to emulate the inspired.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Threadbare as it's beginning to look, the Superman series hasn't lost its raison d'etre. There's life in the old boy yet.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace doesn't attempt to disguise its sentiments - no more so than Greenpeace - but neither does it lose the campy spirit of the 1978 original. Although never as stylish as the first movie, it shows verve and a modest wit. Superman IV is not as funny as the first sequel, but it isn't as violent, either. [27 July 1987, p.1D]

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Superman IV works rather well as a children's movie. It even has a line or two for adults -- though not, one hastens to qualify, enough to actually warrant adult attendance. [25 July 1987, p.B1]

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Superman IV is a pathetic appendage to the series, a dull, shoddy film that makes the minimal 1950s TV series seem rife with production values by comparison. [27 July 1987, p.10C]

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: The earlier films in the series were far from perfect, but at their best they had some flair and agreeable humor, qualities this one sorely lacks. Hackman gets a few laughs, but has less to work with than before, and everyone else seems to be just going through the motions and having less fun doing so.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Predictably awful fourth installment.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: By ordinary movie standards it's awful, but fans of cinematic dementia should have fun for about half an hour.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Superman IV, except for a glitzy new villain named Nuclear Man, is one of the cheesiest movies ever made. It's so grainy and grossly envisioned, it seems filmed on pulp. Superman's crystalline Arctic palace looks as if it's made of no-deposit-no-return soda bottles, and his suit of primary colors has ring around the collar.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: This one is a big, big disappointment. [27 July 1987]

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
review: Sequels to big-budget popular hits usually end up super-slick, shallow and inflated. But this one isn't even super-slick; it's shallow and deflated...The overall effect is of a story atomized and dying before our eyes, collapsing into smashed pulp, ground down into big-budget Kryptonite ash. [27 July 1987, p.1]

title: Caddyshack II
review: It`s shoddy, lazy and numbingly stupid.

title: Caddyshack II
review: Beyond the anemic script, though, Caddyshack II fails because Dangerfield fits the character better. His bulging eyes and neurotic demeanor fuel his lethal jabs. Even though he's still the stand-up comic, his well-established routine makes it easier to believe him. [27 July 1988, p.D1]

title: Caddyshack II
review: A disaster. Mason founders in his poorly written role, and none of the film's endless series of gags is the least bit funny.

title: Caddyshack II
review: Caddyshack II, a feeble follow-up to the 1980 laff riot, is lamer than a duck with bunions, and dumber than grubs. It's patronizing and clumsily manipulative, and top banana Jackie Mason is upstaged by the gopher puppet.

title: Caddyshack II
review: The film features someone who walks like Jackie Mason, talks like Jackie Mason, does everything except make people laugh like Jackie Mason.

title: Caddyshack II
review: This PG-rated romp is bland bananas compared to its R-rated predecessor. Besides, immediately following the liberating craziness of Animal House, another slob comedy didn't seem like such a bad idea. Now, after nearly a decade of slob comedies, the last thing we need is yet another, tamer one.

title: Caddyshack II
review: This movie is soooo bad (How bad is it?) that it makes "Caddyshack I" look like "Godfather II."

title: The Avengers
review: This is an elaborate production, but all the jazzy sets and explosions in the world can't disguise the story's complete lack of urgency.

title: The Avengers
review: This new film version, sad to say, is a hollow shell of the original series.

title: The Avengers
review: This film is an absolute mess.

title: The Avengers
review: So how then do you duplicate a magic aura from 30 years ago? You don't.

title: The Avengers
review: The grasping novelty of the visuals doesn't rival the uncharismatic leads or the hopelessly, unironically banal plot.

title: The Avengers
review: It's shockingly inert.

title: The Avengers
review: The film flails incoherently from set to set, trying to be kicky and madcap and pop, but with no sense of the show's casual acceptance of the absurd.

title: The Avengers
review: It's a film to gall fans of the old television series and perplex anyone else.

title: The Avengers
review: It's almost fascinating to witness just how lousy The Avengers really is.

title: The Avengers
review: It's a completely botched effort -- botched in its direction, its writing and editing.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Joel Schumacher, director and ringmaster, piles on the flashy showmanship and keeps the film as big, bold, noisy and mindlessly overwhelming as possible.

title: Batman & Robin
review: There's something almost maniacally heroic about packaging the fourth sequel of a superhero action series without resorting to the old standbys of good writing, capable acting or inspired directing.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Batman & Robin, like the first three films in the series, is wonderful to look at, and has nothing authentic at its core.

title: Batman & Robin
review: This film, which places yet another actor in the batsuit, has all the necessary hallmarks of a sorry sequel -- pointless, plodding plotting; asinine action; clueless, comatose characterization; and dumb dialogue.

title: Batman & Robin
review: It's the lightest of the Batman movies, the most cartoony, the dumbest and the least ambitious. But it holds the audience's attention, brings on a few laughs and never really gets boring.

title: Batman & Robin
review: There's so much happening in the movie that it feels like nothing is happening at all. Which leaves you free to gaze, slack-jawed, on the true glory of Batman & Robin -- its fabulously color-coded set design.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Clooney's stiff cornball delivery and tendency to smile during the most tragic moments bring this as close to the cartoonish Batman television series of the 1960s as any of the movies have come.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Batman & Robin fails to engage the spirit of Batman, Robin, or decent marketing in general, and instead ends up as a limp, excruciatingly shallow knockoff that leaves viewers cringing at the unavoidable one-liners that make up the better part of the script.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Clooney fails to make much of an impression as The Batman, but to make an impression amongst all the garish theatrics, he would pretty much have to shout his dialogue in rhyming verse, backwards.

title: Batman & Robin
review: Campy costumes can't disguise the incoherent plot, confused performances and lame script that send this star vehicle spiralling downward.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: But the most stimulating, satisfying aspect of this action fantasy is the theme music.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: Its dazzling special effects make its combatants flip and fly, spin and soar, all the while punching and kicking each other like jackhammers, only to leave viewers utterly unmoved.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: It would miss the point to complain that the plot is nonsensical drivel peopled by paper-thin characters and a paucity of ideas.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: This tedious hodgepodge of martial-arts mayhem, bogus mysticism and computer-generated special effects doesn't even pretend to have a plot.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: Fragmented and monotonous, without a semblance of the gymnastic cleverness that at least made the first Mortal Kombat film into watchable trash, Mortal Kombat Annihilation is as debased as movies come.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: This film has no story, no characters, and no coherence.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: Here's the lowdown on the latest chapter in Mortal Kombat: deadly dull.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: The sequel is quite serious, charmless and critic-proof (in fact, it wasn't screened for the media), and it may attract the teenagers who have made the game so popular. [24Nov1997 Pg.10]

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: The movie is nothing more than a perpetual chain of elaborately choreographed (by returning star Robin Shou) fight sequences that mix live-action foregrounds with complexly layered digital effects and are linked together by the most flimsy and laughable of plot elements.

title: Mortal Kombat: Annihilation
review: It's cynical and it's depressing, and I would lock a child in a room before I'd show him Mortal Kombat: Annihilation.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: The special effects work fine for minor acts of magic, but the climactic aerial dragon fight is lame, and most of the performances are at the level of high school plays.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: Much of the dialogue is the silliest sort of fantasy mush, and a good deal of the picture appears to have been shot while the lighting guys were out to lunch.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: A mildly entertaining but tepid extravaganza more suited to television than the big screen.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: The audience has already checked out, long before the formulaic finish.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: Good intentions, bad writing.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: A cheap "Star Wars" rip-off with swords instead of light sabers.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: This fantasy crap, fake-o effects and all, betrays princes of dice, masters of graph and wielders of bong.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: Take this as a warning: it's not much fun.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: At once laboriously expository and defiantly incomprehensible.

title: Dungeons & Dragons
review: Tacky-looking, incoherent, badly acted and hopelessly directed disaster is easily the dullest adventure film of 2000.

title: The Room
review: This inept 2003 melodrama has become a Rocky Horror-style cult favorite...As someone who's watched more bad movies than you can imagine, I'm mostly immune to the so-bad-it's-good aesthetic, though I can see how, viewed in a theater at midnight after a few drinks, this might conjure up its own hilariously demented reality.

title: The Room
review: Tommy Wiseau's film oozes sincerity, which is then slathered in a thick coating of oblivious narcissism, and sadly serves as an example that not everyone should follow their bliss...It's the emotional earnestness that places The Room squarely within Susan Sontag's famous definition of pure camp.

title: The Room
review: You can laugh at lines like: "Hey, everybody, let's go inside and eat some cake"; "Leave your stupid comments in your pocket!"; "Man, I just can't figure women out. Sometimes they're just too smart. Sometimes they're flat out stupid. Other times they're just evil." In Wiseau's worldview, if "The Room" were a woman, she wouldn't be "evil" or "too smart." That leaves "flat-out stupid." [12 Feb 2012, p.B2]

title: The Room
review: The Room marks the writing-directing-acting debut of Tommy Wiseau, who's not just one of the most unusual looking and sounding (with an unidentifiable Eastern European accent) leading men ever to grace the screen, but a narcissist nonpareil whose movie makes Vincent Gallo's "The Brown Bunny" seem the apotheosis of cinematic self-restraint.

title: The Room
review: That’s the trick to making a cult film. It can’t just be bad, it has to be memorably so, and The Room is.

title: The Wicker Man
review: Profoundly disturbing, blood-chilling suspenser.

title: The Wicker Man
review: In the end, LaBute's remake is an interesting idea that never transforms into a particularly satisfying movie.

title: The Wicker Man
review: The Wicker Man isn't all that bad a movie; it's visually striking and ambitious in some ways. It just fails to bring enough to the table to fully distance itself from the original.

title: The Wicker Man
review: This wasn't a horror film the first time around, and LaBute makes sorry feints at effective creepiness, letting the story roam in circles just like Cage.

title: The Wicker Man
review: Unlikely to inspire a passionate following similar to the original, the film, which opened Friday without being screened for the press, ultimately induces more titters than dread.

title: The Wicker Man
review: Any provocative questions LaBute might have wanted to raise are totally obscured as the rising tide of absurdity gradually overwhelms the entire enterprise.

title: The Wicker Man
review: There may be a way to remake 1973's cult thriller The Wicker Man, in which a deeply Christian cop has his religious convictions shaken to the core as he investigates the disappearance of a child from within a cheerfully pagan community, but Neil LaBute didn't find it.

title: The Wicker Man
review: As an allegory of religious conflict, the '73 film is brilliantly constructed and ends with a punctuation mark that was shocking in its day. LaBute's movie attempts to shock, as well, and does: Given the names involved and the casting of Cage, it is shockingly bad.

title: The Wicker Man
review: Turns a cultishly creepy classic into a dull and windy farce.

title: The Wicker Man
review: A movie like this can survive an absurd premise but not incompetent execution. And Mr. LaBute, never much of an artist with the camera, proves almost comically inept as a horror-movie technician...It's neither haunting nor amusing; just boring.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Neither the best nor the worst of movies derived from videogames, Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li at least gives action fans plenty to ogle besides the titular heroine (Kristin Kreuk), whose original incarnation, legend has it, was among the first distaff figures controllable by joystick.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Reveling in the vivid Bangkok locations, Geoff Boyle’s photography is crisp and bright, and Dion Lam’s action choreography unusually witty.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Director Andrzej Bartkowiak ("Romeo Must Die") works hard to supply the appropriate grittiness, but other than a few reasonably well-staged fight sequences, the proceedings are dull and visually uninspired. Justin Marks' solemn screenplay lacks any trace of wit.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: There's something special about this underwhelming mess of a Street Fighter reboot that many cinematic cheese-lovers will find very appetizing. The fact is that The Legend of Chun-Li is not at all a good flick, but it's filled with so much cornball ineptitude that one would think some rather broken mad movie genius was behind it.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: This is a movie for the overcaffeinated, undereducated teenager in all of us.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Idiot plotting and dialogue are what you'd expect from a genre that typically rewards narrative development with a skip function. But the rote fight scenes are a disappointment.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Even with the low expectations The Legend of Chun Li engenders, it still somehow manages to be a letdown.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: Don't be fooled by the low grade: This sequel-in-spirit to Jean-Claude Van Damme's 1994 dud doesn't even succeed in being memorably bad.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: The problems with Street Fighter: The Legend Of Chun-Li began with the casting of dead-eyed, sleepy-voiced, charisma-impaired automaton Kristin Kreuk.

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
review: It boggles the mind that The Legend of Chun-Li is as vapid and dull as it is.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: Ups the self-parody so much that it's practically a Wayans Brothers spoof, albeit with fewer jokes.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: Piranha 3DD is overcrowded and pointlessly mean. The stunt casting of David Hasselhoff playing himself, riffing off his infamous 2007 drunken home video, gets in the way of the storyline.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: "Welcome to rock bottom!" sighs Hasselhoff at one stage, pretty much summing up this textbook exercise in sloppy seconds. Here's hoping the piranhas have a better agent than he does.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: It seems impossible that a sequel to a movie as ridiculous as "Piranha 3D" could disappoint but Piranha 3DD stops at mediocre before arriving at gloriously bad.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: Add to this that it takes place in the town of Merkin, and you'll get an idea of the labored spirit of dirty-old-man humor that prevails.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: John Gulager is neither artist nor genius, bringing only straight-to-video conviction to Piranha 3DD.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: "Piranha 3D" was ridiculous, gory and fun, everything Piranha 3DD is not.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: Hecklers can take the night off; ripping on a movie this bad is as rewarding as shooting fish in a barrel.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: The director, John Gulager, has no idea how to mix his ingredients to create a savvy self-parody.

title: Piranha 3DD
review: Disappointingly, Piranha 3DD, the inevitable sequel to the remake, has none of Dante's wit, Aja's directorial skills, or Greg Nicotero's grotesqueries.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: Boorman deserves credit for trying out some new ideas, even if most of them backfire. Visually, it's fascinating—sort of a blend of Minnellian baroque and Buñuelian absurdity—but the dialogue is childish, the story is incomprehensible, and the metaphysics are ridiculous. Still, an audacious failure is preferable to a chickenhearted success. More than worth a look, if only out of curiosity.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: Since any title containing Roman numerals invites comparison, the answer is: No, Exorcist II is not as good as The Exorcist. It isn't even close. Gone now is the simple clash between Good and Evil, replaced by some goofy transcendental spiritualism.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: Substantially recut by Boorman after his original version was derided in America, but it's still easy to see why New Yorkers jeered. Boorman completely avoids gore and obscenity, treating the original as a kind of sacred good-versus-evil text, and weaving its sets and characters into a highly traditional confrontation of occult forces.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: Not as awful as its notorious reputation would indicate, but certainly not the neglected masterpiece its small cult of supporters has claimed, Boorman's gorgeously shot sequel to The Exorcist has isolated moments of breathtaking imagery, but its parts do not add up to a satisfying whole.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: The film is too cadenced and exotic and too deliriously complicated to succeed with most audiences (and when it opened, there were accounts of people in theaters who threw things at the screen). But it's winged camp--a horror fairy tale gone wild, another in the long history of moviemakers' king-size follies. There's enough visual magic in it for a dozen good movies; what it lacks is judgement.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: It would be a lot easier to buy Exorcist II: The Heretic as a mood piece if it was able to sustain a tone beyond clumsy exposition and hysterical camp for longer than a few minutes.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: A famously disastrous follow-up to William Friedkin’s horror hit.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: A snooze-fest without any scares.

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: This sequel is so laden with dubious, spurious, curious and tedious stuff about theology, parapsychology, entomology and speleology that it forgets to frighten you in its frantic concern with being hip in the fad world of the occult. The Heretic simply drowns in its own malarky. [27 June 1977, p.61]

title: Exorcist II: The Heretic
review: Exorcist II begins by looking foolish and slowly becomes a straightfaced film of the absurd.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: Movies like this embrace goofiness with an almost sensual pleasure.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: Despite huge resources at Mr. De Bont's disposal and the fact that both he and Ms. Bullock have achieved stellar status since ''Speed'' screeched onto movie screens, the sequel is still a B-movie at heart.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: Not nearly as clever at taxing the audience's knuckles as its forerunner, Speed 2 still manages to stay above board long enough to merit a look-see, if only to relish the once-in-a-lifetime pleasure of Mr. Dafoe and his pet leeches.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: Speed 2 can be numbered among the worst second chapters ever made.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: This is my idea of a nightmare.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: And De Bont's effects are wildly over the top, devoid of the stylish cuts and intriguing angles that enriched the original. In fact, there's so little panache in his destructive action that it begins to seem like a weird act of self-destruction.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: The 1994 "Speed," which starred Bullock and Keanu Reeves, was hardly "King Lear" on a bus, but it was an entertaining ride. But this movie is nothing but pain to sit through.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: Speed 2 is such an inept piece of direction that it's anybody's guess whether De Bont understands how to convey where two characters are in spatial relation to each other or in relation to the action.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: This may be hard to believe, but there's not a single moment of drama or tension in any of the action sequences. And the film is made up almost entirely of action.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
review: The kinetics aren't that good, the twaddle is off the charts and the characters seem written by monkeys on amphetamines with crayons.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: Eddie Murphy's latest comedy, The Adventures of Pluto Nash, takes place in the year 2087, which is about the earliest he can hope to be forgiven.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: There are worse movies, but that's no excuse. Rarely has so much money delivered so little entertainment.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: A limp Eddie Murphy vehicle that even he seems embarrassed to be part of.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: Only Quaid, as a semiretarded horny robot, and Cleese as a fussy chauffeur hologram seem to get it. Even Murphy, as the titular nightclub big shot in outer space, forgets to be actually funny until the climax.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: In terms of execution this movie is careless and unfocused.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: The proper mix is never found. Ill-conceived and expensive project that winds up looking like a bunch of talented thesps slumming it.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: It's not awful, but the high cost of a movie ticket these days seems like a steep price to pay for 90 minutes of air conditioning and production design.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: Murphy slogs his way through this dismally dull sci-fi comedy.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: A headache-inducing mess without direction or purpose.

title: The Adventures of Pluto Nash
review: So unremittingly awful that labeling it a dog probably constitutes cruelty to canines.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: A second-rate regurgitation of "The Lord of the Rings." Everything about it, down to the set and costume design, apes Peter Jackson's epic trilogy. However, while "The Lord of the Rings" was a grand story of scope and power, In the Name of the King feels small in more ways than one.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: Its convictionless competence is merely dull, denying the pleasures of an outright howler without providing much else.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: Is this movie so god-awful bad that it's hilariously good? Can't be bothered deciding. Figure that's an answer in itself.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: This is the sort of movie where men stand blankly over dead loved ones, then start digging. Masculine stoicism or emotional botox? You decide.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: Cultists will be happy to discover that In The Name Of The King bears all the so-bad-it's-good hallmarks of a classic Boll production.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: Director Uwe Boll sticks with what he knows -- how to turn video games into dull, cheap-looking movies.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: An awkward “Lord of the Rings” knockoff, it features both elaborate battles and bumbling humor, though it’s never quite clear when you should be laughing.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: Who among us can explain the enigma wrapped in a riddle surrounded by fierce, ravening, razor-toothed conundrums that is German director Uwe Boll?

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: It's completely undone by its terrible screenplay, inept direction, oppressive musical score and muddy visual palette.

title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
review: A plodding patchwork of derivative fantasy-adventure, medieval production design, risible dialogue, unimpressive CGI trickery and haphazardly edited action sequences.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Still, it's refreshing that the animals don't talk.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: While Fraser’s presence doesn’t necessarily elevate Furry Vengeance into something better than the dumb, lowbrow timewaster it aspires to be, Fraser does make it a little easier to digest.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: On the sliding critter-comedy scale, Furry Vengeance falls somewhere between the Chipmunks and the Chihuahua (the one from Beverly Hills).

title: Furry Vengeance
review: The message that needs to be posted at the theater door is "No trespassing."

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Furry Vengeance isn’t really a movie at all; it's a message provided by the good people at Participant Media.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Furry Vengeance is a slapstick stinker, easily the worst movie of the year.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Maybe your kids will insist that you see Furry Vengeance. Then again, wouldn't this be the perfect time to let them test their independence and sit through it alone? Otherwise, good luck. You have my condolences.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: The movie's simple-minded lesson that forests are good and development is bad is undercut the minute one pauses to think about how many natural resources were wasted on this sorry excuse for a motion picture.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Vengeance has the odor of court-ordered community service. The jokes never rise above the groin. The trees look plastic, the characters more so.

title: Furry Vengeance
review: Furry Vengeance is unbearable.

title: The Love Guru
review: If you're a Toronto native or a big-time hockey geek, there are enough little in jokes to probably carry you through the leaden pacing and barrel-scraping gross-out humor, but it's an awfully dull ride for the rest of us.

title: The Love Guru
review: So relentlessly juvenile as to merit a new twist on the PG-13 rating -- one that strongly cautions not only those under 13 but anyone much above it, too.

title: The Love Guru
review: The Love Guru”does not bring out Myer's best, and aside from a deft early Bollywood parody, there’s nothing visually to help the fun along.

title: The Love Guru
review: Myers combines his love of references, silly names, and mindless repetition by having his guru use "Mariska Hargitay" as a greeting/mantra. The first time it's employed, it's merely unfunny; by the 13th or 40th time, it's almost hypnotic in its awfulness.

title: The Love Guru
review: Not only does the film stumble badly from one skit to another, the skits themselves have too much dead air.

title: The Love Guru
review: Now and again some pungent writing leaks through to poke fun at the excruciating banality of guru wisdom. But mostly it’s dreary dick jokes and elephant poop, slack directing by Marco Schnabel, and, of all fatal errors, Mike Myers, shooting for cuddly.

title: The Love Guru
review: The results are a wheezy, tired attempt to milk more laughs out of the '60s, by doing exactly what "Austin Powers" did.

title: The Love Guru
review: Myers has made some funny movies, but this film could have been written on toilet walls by callow adolescents.

title: The Love Guru
review: It recycles gags from earlier and better Myers movies and hopes that the audience won't notice because they're too busy staring at Timberlake's bursting Speedo.

title: The Love Guru
review: None of them -- not one, not for a moment -- is remotely funny.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: Graced with unusually expressive and seamless voice work by Drew Barrymore and George Lopez, the best of its kind since "Babe."

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: The picture might not be as fresh and clever as it could have been, but its spirited voice cast delivers the whole enchilada.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: This being Disney, wholesome character-building messages abound, but for once they're freshly spun as cautions against stereotyping both ethnic and canine.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: Okay, the concept for the movie is admittedly lame, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with watching a passel of adorable pooches wrinkle their brows and bark while human voices come out of their mouths.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: Alpo is served with a burrito chaser in Beverly Hills Chihuahua, Disney's fish-out-of-water comedy in which the fish is … well, read the title.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: A filthy-rich fantasy for these cash-strapped times, Beverly Hills Chihuahua features the voices of Drew Barrymore and much of the industry's top Latino talent in a live-action talking-dog lark that should please young pups.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: It's very slick and small children will enjoy it, but it has little of its model's special magic.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: This is not a movie for anyone who's aged past the "Oh! Cute!" phase of moviegoing. It's paced for little minds with short attention spans.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: Despite its superficial lip-service to self-actualization/realization, there has to be more to life than what Beverly Hills Chihuahua is putting out there, which is fit for neither man nor beast.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
review: While George Lopez, Cheech Marin, and Paul Rodriguez are funny men, it's amazing how boring these Latin-shtick cutups can be when none of them gets a single good line.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: The trouble with Holmes & Watson, a witless Sherlock Holmes spoof that supplies fewer laughs in its entirety than “Step Brothers” does in its deleted scenes, is that the movie can never decide how dumb it wants to be. Or, more accurately, what kind of dumb it wants to be.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: There is still intermittent joy to be found in their autumnal bromance.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: The trouble is, Sherlock Holmes exists so large in audiences’ minds already that the pair’s uninspired take feels neither definitive nor an especially fresh take, but just an off-brand, garden-variety parody.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: Because of the talent involved, every now and then Holmes & Watson hits on something bizarrely inspired.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: A brilliant supporting cast, which includes Hugh Laurie, Steve Coogan, Ralph Fiennes, Lauren Lapkus, Rebecca Hall, and Kelly MacDonald, is utterly wasted on this lame and forgettable outing. The only real mystery is why they wanted to be apart of this project at all.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: Combined with some awfully lazy riffs on Holmes’s fondness for his seven-per-cent solution, Holmes & Watson is not so much a case of whodunit as it is a question why bother.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: It’s just not funny.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: So excruciatingly awful that you have to wonder what it was, other than their paychecks, that could have possessed the cast and crew to keep coming back each day, when it must have been obvious from the first day of shooting that the project was the most hopeless of cases imaginable.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: Making their previous vehicles Step Brothers and Talladega Nights seem the height of comic sophistication by comparison, Holmes & Watson features the duo parodying Arthur Conan Doyle's famous characters to devastatingly unfunny effect.

title: Holmes & Watson
review: If there are any new jokes left to tell about Holmes, they’re nowhere to be found in the abysmal Holmes & Watson, which might be the worst feature-length film ever made about the “consulting detective” from Baker Street.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: Far more grotesque than the first Human Centipede - in fact, The Human Centipede 2 (Full Sequence) could be the sickest B movie ever made.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: Like the original, the most shocking aspect comes from the revelation that Six can actually tell a story.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: Whatever gothic originality the first Human Centipede possessed is altogether lacking in this sorry follow-up.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: The desire to eat someone's ass is almost always superficial; there's no thought of sustenance, and more sophisticated pleasures are usually imminent. Not so with The Human Centipede 2 (Full Sequence).

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: The first Human Centipede had audacity on its side. Human Centipede II has only excess.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: More boring than stomach-churning, the film nevertheless contains scattered scenes and sequences so far beyond the tolerance of the squeamish that it can't be overstated.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: The question remains: Exploitative films are a dime a dozen, but how low will two-faced art-film distributor IFC go?

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: Nasty and over the top, The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence) feels like a horror movie that hates horror fans.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: The movie is a reductio ad absurdum, a sick joke taken to extremes, beginning with a goof on the notion that horror movies inspire copycats and ending with a test to determine whether some people will watch anything.

title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
review: It's perhaps the sequel we deserve. But that doesn't mean this dumb, blunt follow-up - both more unspeakably grotesque and less scary than the first film - is worth sitting through. Once Six's conceptual project becomes clear, his escalating audience-mocking torture is increasingly pointless.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Instantly forgettable but fun while it lasts, Disney's live-action adaptation of the classic cartoon is an ideal action-adventure thrill ride for kids who may be a little too young for the latest Bond extravaganza.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: By turns frenetic and flat-footed, Mr. Magoo is an uninspired live-action comedy.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Crashingly unimaginative. But its real offense is making such poor use of Nielsen.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Only a couple of good gags in its pileup of otherwise lame jokes keep the production from being an unqualified stinker.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Nielsen's performance is truly dreadful, yet somehow it seems strangely fitting for the movie, which is unlikely even to engage the younger audience for whom it is so obviously intended. When even the outtakes you see over the end titles don't raise a single titter, you know you're in trouble.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Poor old Mr. Magoo should have been allowed to rest in piece. This film suggests that when you loot a crypt, you're likely to find a corpse.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: Mr. Magoo is transcendently bad. It soars above ordinary badness as the eagle outreaches the fly. There is not a laugh in it. Not one. I counted.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: If you really hate your kids, pack them off to this slapdash farce, whose only funny moment is the PC disclaimer at the end about the Disney company's humanist concern for blind people (which even literate toddlers will have trouble understanding anyway).

title: Mr. Magoo
review: It's a mess best left to the nitrate ashes of forgotten film and television history.

title: Mr. Magoo
review: With Mr. Magoo, it’s the filmmakers who seem blind.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: It's moderately engaging for the first half-hour, somewhat trying during the second half hour, and virtually unbearable over the final twenty minutes. It's a marginally recommendable film for kids, but not necessarily for parents.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Myers is the movie's fatal flaw, squeezing out the other characters who fatten the plot, mostly with an eye to parents.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Although a literal movie adaptation of Seuss' 1957 classic "The Cat in the Hat" might have run 20 minutes, is it too much to ask that the filmed material preserve the author's sensibility?

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Someone (Myers?) came up with the bright idea of turning the Cat in the Hat into the worst Vegas nightclub spritzer of 1958. He's become a furry version of Rip Taylor: a walking, talking vaudeville idiot box.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: It's a sort of soullessly cheerful cynicism that is about as far from Seuss as one can imagine.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Talk about your quick-buck exploitation.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: As a British politician said of a corrupt but articulate peer, "The Cat in the Hat" is like a rotten mackerel seen by moonlight: It shines as it stinks.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Charmless and grating and immediately forgettable.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Such a remarkable rift between its charming source material and its heinous cinematic realization that the producers may as well have skipped the hassle of securing licensing rights and simply called this mess Mike Myers: A--hole in Fur.

title: The Cat in the Hat
review: Comes scarily close to being the most unendurable Hollywood creation of the last dozen years.

title: Prom Night
review: A surprisingly effective teen-skewing thriller that soft-pedals graphic violence (in marked contrast to the R-rated 1980 original) while generating a fair degree of suspense.

title: Prom Night
review: Formulaic to the core, this reworking of the fondly remembered high-school slasher picture works surprisingly well on its own terms.

title: Prom Night
review: Without the gore, this old school slasher rehash is one anemic bore.

title: Prom Night
review: This is as listless, mindless and utterly useless a piece of corporate brain-clog as one is likely to come across for quite some time.

title: Prom Night
review: Despite having the same title and a similar premise to a 1980 Jamie Lee Curtis flick (kids getting slaughtered on prom night), this is NOT a remake. In fact, it really doesn't have much of a plot. It's basically "The O.C." with a body count.

title: Prom Night
review: McCormick and screenwriter J.S. Cardone don’t have one original thought between them, but they do appear to share an obsession with characters opening hotel-room closets in which the steel hangers gleam ominously.

title: Prom Night
review: The movie offers less gore than the average Band-Aid commercial and fewer scares than the elimination episodes of "Dancing With the Stars."

title: Prom Night
review: There's really nothing much to Prom Night: No twists, no atmosphere, no big Grand Guignol setpieces, not a single moment when it tries to do something novel with the event, the killings, the villain, or the victims. It's a little like going on a tour of the slaughterhouse, where death is meted out with mechanical regularity, but visitors are kept at a safe, PG-13 distance from all the butchering.

title: Prom Night
review: When Jamie Lee Curtis ran from a killer in 1980's "Prom Night," she was 22 and had a unique gift for belting out fear. She was the Beverly Sills of slasher flicks. That "Prom Night" was dumb, but it wasn't insulting in the way this remake is.

title: Prom Night
review: A bland, timid and thoroughly un-thrilling teen thriller.

title: RoboCop 3
review: The familiarity of the high-armour shoot-outs and sfx-assisted set-pieces make most of this sequel feel surprisingly low-tech. Not bad entertainment, though.

title: RoboCop 3
review: There's probably sufficient energy and violence in RoboCop 3 to satisfy undemanding action fans, but it's as mechanical as its cyborg hero.

title: RoboCop 3
review: Though the story is tired, most of ROBOCOP 3's action sequences and special effects are imaginative and effective, and the gruesomeness of the first two films has been toned down in a commercially wise attempt to make it more accessible to the younger audiences who love Robocop.

title: RoboCop 3
review: The show has its moments-some funny scenes, some wild stop-motion Phil Tippett computer action, some of Torn's scenery-chewing. But they're only moments. RoboCop 3's main problem is that nobody fouled up its program. It's a RoboMovie. [05 Nov 1993, p.C]

title: RoboCop 3
review: Unsurprisingly this is the worst in the RoboCop trilogy, with the plot proving ridiculous, excelling itself particularly in the climax. For what was a promising debut, it's reputation was quickly tarnished with the drivvel such as this that followed.

title: RoboCop 3
review: This latest widget off the RoboCop assembly line is a bit better than the first sequel, which amounts to damnation with faint praise. Limiting the gore, but not the carnage, in pursuit of a PG-13 rating and more youngsters, pic remains a cluttered, nasty exercise that seems principally intent on selling action figures.

title: RoboCop 3
review: Why do they persist in making these retreads? Because RoboCop is a brand name, I guess, and this is this year's new model. It's an old tradition in Detroit to take an old design and slap on some fresh chrome.

title: RoboCop 3
review: The movie, which is deadly slow and full of Japanese-bashing, is also an undisguised merchandising promo.

title: RoboCop 3
review: As for the conflict, it's hardly riveting and often it's downright silly. The sets and effects betray their downsized budget. And the Japanese bashing is less artful than in Rising Sun, though just as obnoxious.

title: RoboCop 3
review: About as two-dimensional as a comic book, RoboCop 3 should be regarded as the last strike-out.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Gets credit for avoiding the easy path. Too bad the path it chooses doesn't lead us anywhere we want to be taken.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: The assault is against our ears, as the soundtrack pours forth a stream of thrash and Goth music.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: The characters are boring, the violence generic, the suspense nonexistent.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Can't scare up a decent plot.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Berlinger has approached Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2 with intelligence and even a bit of thematic heft. But, frankly, the cheap thrill is gone.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Resembles an old Nine Inch Nails video. Missing from the mix are any characters with whom you'd want to spend one minute around a campfire.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Admirers of "The Blair Witch Project" are going to be left high and dry.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: There's nothing scarier than a group of hormone-crazed 20-somethings, but this sequel isn't much more than a footnote of a footnote.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: A schizoid monster slapped together by uneasy bedfellows.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
review: Guaranteed to inspire many more belly laughs than it does actual shivers. Boo, scary? I think not.

title: Material Girls
review: The Duffs are certainly cute together, but not even their natural chemistry can enliven all the preachy bits about hard work and the meaning of happiness.

title: Material Girls
review: Isn't as witty, stylish, or sophisticated as the similarly themed "The Devil Wears Prada." Material Girls is pitched to the Seventeen crowd, and it succeeds on its own terms. These days, even pre teens live in a material world.

title: Material Girls
review: It's less substantial than cotton candy, but Material Girls is as slickly produced as one of the Marchetta TV spots.

title: Material Girls
review: A superficial tween comedy that mocks celebutantes like the Olsen twins while simultaneously pushing stars Hilary and Haylie Duff as their replacements.

title: Material Girls
review: The Duffs don't even fully commit to their characters here -- they’'e seemingly undecided about whether they can get away with being shallow and bratty without ruining their family-friendly images.

title: Material Girls
review: The real-life sisters Hilary and Haylie Duff star in this incompetent spin on the poor-little-rich-girl story.

title: Material Girls
review: The most shocking moment comes during the closing credits, when it's revealed that not one, not two, but three screenwriters were responsible for a plot that someone seems to have hastily slapped together after taking a walk around a Sephora outlet while listening to "Beat Of My Heart" on loop.

title: Material Girls
review: Painfully unfunny comedy.

title: Material Girls
review: There is plenty of blame to go around for this laughless mess.

title: Material Girls
review: Even by the low standards of the genre it represents, this female teen comedy represents a new nadir.

title: Norbit
review: The fun in Norbit is watching Murphy at work – the guy has a knack for bringing the physicality of his comic characters to life.

title: Norbit
review: Not exactly uproarious. But Mr. Murphy, going back at least to his Gumby and Buckwheat days on "Saturday Night Live," has always had the ability to turn broad caricature into something stranger and more inventive.

title: Norbit
review: Much of the movie -- which Murphy wrote with a small posse of collaborators -- is taken up with the torturously dull, not to mention unbelievable, romance between Norbit and Kate (a disappointingly lackluster Newton) and the tedious agenda of Cuba Gooding Jr. as a schemer-manipulator.

title: Norbit
review: Murphy speaks in a breathy lisp, as if his mouth had been partially buttoned shut, and he doesn't give himself the nerd's traditional redeeming feature of a geeky, slide-rule intellect. Norbit, all frozen gawk, is just a very dim bulb.

title: Norbit
review: It's hard to know who is the intended audience for this misguided mess.

title: Norbit
review: Mean-spirited and depressing, this horror movie in comedy disguise delights in the twin spectacles of morbid obesity and domestic abuse, of which children are often the target.

title: Norbit
review: Racially insensitive, politically incorrect and beyond crude.

title: Norbit
review: Murphy and his brother Charlie, who collaborated on the screenplay, seem to have drawn the wrong lesson from the latter's stint on "Chappelle's Show." Where Dave Chappelle used stereotypes to confront prejudice, the Murphys (and their co-screenwriters Jay Scherick and David Ronn) merely squeeze a few grudging drops from caricatures that were wrung dry in the age of vaudeville.

title: Norbit
review: It's an astonishingly crass and vulgar film, crudely directed on a cut-rate budget by Brian Robbins, never more than almost funny or less than disturbing.

title: Norbit
review: It's recidivist Murphy: bad-skit comedy populated by caricatures in search of a movie.

title: One Missed Call
review: The result is yet another tired, ultimately incoherent horror movie that undoes the promise of its pretty good premise and potentially interesting story structure with dull scares, sloppy ending and a pair of unconvincing, leaden lead performances.

title: One Missed Call
review: On the shortlist for least essential movie of the decade, a copy of a copy of a copy that's so worn down, it's about as fresh and vital as a fifth-generation dub of "The Star Wars Holiday Special."

title: One Missed Call
review: This decent if derivative scare machine should benefit from a lack of genre competition.

title: One Missed Call
review: Uninspired and painfully familiar.

title: One Missed Call
review: While director Eric Valette provides the occasional chill, the disturbing spooks aren't enough to make this boat float. Burns sleepwalks through One Missed Call totally devoid of charisma, and Sossamon muddles along, going through the motions.

title: One Missed Call
review: Give this call a miss.

title: One Missed Call
review: A poker-faced puzzle whose biggest shock is the absence of Sarah Michelle Gellar.

title: One Missed Call
review: The direction is uninspired, acting is lifeless, and the script borders on the inept.

title: One Missed Call
review: One Missed Call was originally a so-so Takashi Miike freak-out. Now it's a worse-worse American eyesore.

title: One Missed Call
review: The original movie One Missed Call is based on was pretty tame, at least by Miike standards. And since it appears studios have no intention of halting this flood of abysmal rehashes, allow me to suggest that they at least have the stones not to pussyfoot around and give us a remake worthy of Hollywood, of America, and of an audience that lacks the willpower to stop buying tickets to half-assed crap.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: Shark Night isn't fantastic, but it's a good enough time, and it'll never be better than when it's watched with a rowdy crowd in a theater.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: It's refreshing to see Shark Night 3D director David R. Ellis try to pull off a semi-sincere second-generation "Jaws" rip-off, even if he doesn't quite succeed.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: The equivalent of a skin flick in which all the sex scenes are tastefully obscured by blankets and sheets.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: Unlike his "Snakes on a Plane," director David R. Ellis' sharks-in-a-lake thriller displays little sense of its scenario's camp potential. Gore, too, is in short supply on account of the pic's PG-13 rating, which renders the attack scenes nearly toothless.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: The PG-13 film is heavy on scenes of cloudy blood in the water but almost entirely lacking shock shots of flesh torn asunder. (And while marketing relies heavily on bikinis, the movie's light on that kind of flesh as well.)

title: Shark Night 3D
review: The worst movie of the summer, arriving on the last weekend of the summer.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: A ho-hum series of kills and lulls so predictable that it doesn't even look like much fun for the sharks; when they open wide, they might as well be yawning.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: The one crime a B-movie should never commit is boring its audience. By even these low standards, Shark Night 3D is dead in the water.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: A thoroughly shabby attempt to piggyback on the success of last year's "Piranha 3D," Shark Night 3D embraces convention with a voraciousness matched only by its predictability, amateurishness and all-around tameness.

title: Shark Night 3D
review: Shark Night 3D barely bothered to show up, let alone deliver the minimal goods.
After multiple "Saw" franchise releases, writer-director Darren Lynn Bousman goes it alone for 11-11-11, with at best tepid results elaborating an unconvincing premise.
One and one (and one and one and one and one) never quite add up to two in Darren Lynn Bousman's 11-11-11, a rather anemic entry in the biblical-prophecy horror subgenre.
The film has the feel of something conceived and whipped together in very little time, perhaps to make its own built-in deadline.
If only 11-11-11 had arrived a little closer to Thanksgiving - the turkey connection would have been entirely appropriate.

A veteran of the Saw franchise, Darren Lynn Bousman trades torture-porn antics for an old-fashioned Euro-horror vibe, complete with old dark houses and creepy maids; he then wastes what little suspense he generates with endless dorm-room philosophical debates about faith versus atheism and religio-conspiracy theories so far-fetched they'd embarrass Dan Brown.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: The Last Exorcism Part II is an effectively unnerving, slow-burn supernatural horror tale. The film is smartly different enough from the original to survive on its own, though it lacks some of the first film's sense of surprise.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: At least this movie, like its predecessor, has Ashley Bell as Nell. An actress who suggests religious piety, carnal fire and satanic aggression with equal dexterity, Ms. Bell provides a pulse an audience can connect with amid the standard-issue atmospheric accouterments.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: Unfortunately, no one involved seems to have bent over backwards to make the movie either original or even all that scary.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: At the end of the day, it’s a sure-handed sequel, but not a terribly thrilling one.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: Unfortunately, while director/co-writer Ed Gass-Donnelly displays an admirable restraint in his general eschewing of gratuitous gore, quick editing and flashy visuals, the results have a generally soporific feel.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: Part II is every bit as cheap and far more generic, nothing more than a run of the mill ghost story masquerading as The Devil Made Her Do It.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: It’s the kind of garbage that does a disservice to the fearless possibilities of the horror genre and its knack for sly social commentary.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: An ineffective excursion that maintains a few direct ties back to the original film but never moves the story forward.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: An abysmal sequel that abandons the found-footage concept, along with the pockets of wit and originality that made its predecessor salvageable.

title: The Last Exorcism Part II
review: Scenes of solemn importance drag on to the point of self-parody in an attempt at establishing mood, while dialogue reeks of connect-the-dots spoonfeeding.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: It makes clearer much that was so vague in the original; it even jokes about how confusing its premise is. In short, audiences who made the first film successful enough to warrant a second will be getting a bit more for their money.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: With its fancifully moldering sets and technical effects, Highlander 2 is little more than a barbarous arena, a Conanistic return to paganism for those among us who still laugh at violence.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: No plot, no real story, no point really.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: The problem is – the film plays more like a brainstorm exercise than a feature length film. There are gobs of great ideas here, but none of them connect in the way fans likely wanted.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: Audiences unfamiliar with the first film will be hard put to follow the action as it incoherently hops about in time and space.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: The acting is terrible,with Connery, at his lowest common denominator, stealing the show. For those of you who worry that MTV video art will destroy cinema, the ineptitudes of this film vividly detail the radical difference in forms. It sucks. But it would have made a great comic book.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: Highlander 2 is beautiful. But it's largely incoherent. The film is desperately overplotted; events and years rush by and pile up like cars in an interstate wreck. It's also terribly overexplained.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: The dullest and shoddiest action-adventure flick of the year, with only a few cute Sean Connery moments to rescue it from total, sheer and utter bogosity. [01 Nov 1991, p.29]

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: Leaden, laden with effects, short on imagination.

title: Highlander II: The Quickening
review: Highlander 2: The Quickening is the most hilariously incomprehensible movie I've seen in many a long day - a movie almost awesome in its badness.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Inspector Gadget may be a live-action movie, but at its heart it's more cartoonish than most cartoons.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: What a joyless, fussy contraption of a movie!

title: Inspector Gadget
review: The plot was an arbitrary concoction.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Gadget instead ends up as another mindless, noisy thrill ride that gorges its audience on bright effects and leaves it queasy from overconsumption.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: In the end the elaborate gimmickry of Inspector Gadget cannot conceal its very ordinary storytelling.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Like the cartoon on which it's based, Inspector Gadget has moments of absurd fun and droll wit, but they are fleeting and few.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Disney has struck once again, taking a passably entertaining cartoon and turning it into a motion picture so lifeless that it's almost unwatchable.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Anyone older than eight is likely to find it a ridiculously extravagant exercise in stupidity.

title: Inspector Gadget
review: Are there really legions of postboomers out there sighing nostalgically over the happy hours they spent watching Inspector Gadget?

title: Inspector Gadget
review: A new standard for wretched excess is established by Inspector Gadget, a joyless and charmless disaster in which state-of-the-art special effects are squandered on pain-in-the-backside folly.

title: Halloween: Resurrection
review: Rosenthal observes all the ritual elements -- a veteran of the series, he seems to understand that its fans crave certainty over shock.

title: Halloween: Resurrection
review: Thing is, movie's 100 percent mystery-free, but mildly creative, mixing Psych 101 with cynical Hollywood in-jokes with Tylenol-sponsored grainy-cam footage. Best revelation is source of Myers' superhuman strength: eats big rats, apparently.

title: Halloween: Resurrection
review: If, as it appears, Rosenthal is competing with the knife-wielding Myers for the title of biggest hack, he wins by unanimous decision.

title: Halloween: Resurrection
review: It seems content to plod listlessly through the motions.

title: Halloween: Resurrection

title: Marmaduke
review: As doggy movies go, this one gets two paws out of four.

title: Marmaduke
review: With extended closing credits, Marmaduke clocks in at 88 minutes and feels longer.

title: Marmaduke
review: A dull but harmless big-screen comedy aimed at the youngest movie goers.

title: Marmaduke
review: One thing Marmaduke does have in common with the earlier Disney titles is a blessed scarcity of crass bodily-function gags that often pass as family comedy.

title: Marmaduke
review: "Beverly Hills Chihuahua," we owe you an apology. Among talking-dog movies, Marmaduke is the runt of the litter.

title: Marmaduke
review: Marmaduke saves its farts for the beginning and end, but the stink carries through the whole movie.

title: Marmaduke
review: Very small children may well take a shine to the big, goofy dog and his furry friends, but parents and older siblings will be left squirming in their seats at a bland, predictable blend of bad comedy and sentimentality.

title: Marmaduke
review: We’ve just been treated like a fire hydrant.

title: Area 51
review: Though Peli stages a few fun and creepy effects shots, nothing that happens here couldn’t be surmised from simply reading the film’s title.

title: Area 51
review: To be fair, the slow burn does eventually catch fire and there’s lots of screaming and heavy breathing and dark tunnels and running and what-not. The relatively tense final half-hour is clearly the reason that very smart producer Jason Blum thought this would be a solid follow-up to “Paranormal Activity.” It’s that first hour that is the reason it took six years to (barely) get released.

title: Area 51
review: Area 51 is everything that's wrong with not only found footage films, but also weak-minded sci-fi thrillers that think crazed talking heads and fuzzy shadows are scary enough.

title: Area 51
review: Tedious, visually unsatisfying, poorly acted and narratively disjointed, Area 51 is a textbook example of directorial sophomore slump.

title: The Devil Inside
review: While this religio-horror effort does contain some nice scares, and a memorably unnerving turn from Crowley, The Devil Inside's biggest shock arrives when it abruptly ends - just as it hits its stride. The result is a found-footage movie whose third act remains missing.

title: The Devil Inside
review: Despite the palpable air of deja vu that hangs over it like a light fog, The Devil Inside generates a fair amount of suspense during sizable swaths of its familiar but serviceable exorcism-centric scenario.

title: The Devil Inside
review: All hell breaks loose and it's a heck of a lot of fun to watch.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The mother/daughter drama should have played a bigger part in this film as the 87-minute runtime passes quickly and leaves us feeling utterly short-changed.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The reality of The Devil Inside is that it's a half-hearted patchwork of ideas blatantly lifted from better films, with characters who have to act increasingly foolish in order to allow the action to go forward and an ending so anticlimactic and abrupt that the audience at the screening I attended erupted in enraged boos as the credits rolled.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The film's contradictory and nullifying dilemma of wanting to be both scripted and vérité at once, a plight that affects so much contemporary TV, is temporarily quelled in heated scenes of curse-laden levitation and Linda Blair contortion, which dutifully deliver the scares.

title: The Devil Inside
review: Never gets off the ground, trotting out the same predictable twisting heads and psycho-babble without a whiff of originality or discernible visual flair. As a result, the would-be thriller proves as scary and unsettling as a slab of devil's food cake - only considerably less satisfying.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The Devil Inside joins a long, woozy-camera parade of found-footage scare pictures, among them "The Blair Witch Project," the "Paranormal Activity" films and certain wedding videos that won't go away.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The scariest thing about The Devil Inside is that a major studio like Paramount Pictures, which is distributing it, may be able to squeeze more profit out of a tedious, tediously exhausted subgenre that was already creatively tapped out when "The Blair Witch Project" spooked audiences more than a decade ago.

title: The Devil Inside
review: The hilariously convoluted thriller contains all the elements for a wacky parody of exorcism movies, except a sense of humor about itself: The Devil Inside never acknowledges its innate ridiculousness, so the laughs are unintentional.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: Awash in bold colors, bright patterns and ebullient kids, director Ava DuVernay’s new take on A Wrinkle in Time dazzles its way across time and space even if it doesn’t quite stick the landing.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: A Wrinkle in Time is ambitious, hopeful, and imaginative, but it’s also messy, overwrought, and oddly paced.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: It almost doesn’t matter that the movie is too emotionally prescriptive to have any real power, or too high on imagination to leave any room for wonder; DuVernay evinces such faith in who she is and what she’s doing that “A Wrinkle in Time” remains true to itself even when everything on screen reads false.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: Only the faintest glimmers of genuine, earned emotion pierce through the layers of intense calculation that encumber Ava DuVernay's A Wrinkle in Time.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: A Wrinkle in Time is wildly uneven, weirdly suspenseless, and tonally all over the place, relying on wall-to-wall music to supply the missing emotional connection and trowel over huge plot holes.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: The film may involve the instant movement among unfathomable distances and the shattered limits of space and time, but it’s only Storm Reid's character who feels multidimensional.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: DuVernay finds herself in the unenviable position of being both the right and wrong person for an important job. A Wrinkle in Time is gratifying for what it is, a step forward for creative women of color, and so disappointing for what it turns out to be.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: The film is tentative and over-protective, as though it’s terrified that a story empowering kids to help good battle evil could give someone a nightmare. It reduces the whole universe to one girl’s self-esteem.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: It’s honestly a little baffling how so many good choices could produce something so frustrating.

title: A Wrinkle in Time
review: Which is a big build-up to essentially saying, “This movie’s a stiff.”

title: The Gallows
review: Lofing and Cluff certainly know the found-footage ropes, and the tropes; we'll see if their next project reveals a little more imagination.

title: The Gallows
review: This is another found-footage movie that, with a little art direction and some actual cinematography, could easily have been a decent little terrorizer. Instead, it comes mostly unglued thanks to its hacky gimmick.

title: The Gallows
review: Any film that tries to revive this technique needs a clever story or unusual filmmaking ingenuity to stand out from the crowd. The Gallows has neither. It has enough mild scares to captivate the under-25 crowd.

title: The Gallows
review: The film is sstrictly a high-tech spin on one of those Scary Stories to Tell in the Dark.

title: The Gallows
review: The Gallows is not without thrills. What it lacks is the thrill of the chase.

title: The Gallows
review: Making audiences care about the characters is always a more effective fear-generating strategy than just knocking off a bunch of dimwits in the dark.

title: The Gallows
review: The Gallows offers up few new ideas and very few genuine scares.

title: The Gallows
review: If you’re not laughing at this, early and often, you’re made of sterner stuff than the players they paid to show up for this, but didn’t.

title: The Gallows
review: Sorry, but this kind of high-school horror was old when Jamie Lee Curtis was young. All the ugly, shaky, night-vision camerawork in the world will not make it seem fresh. Or remotely scary.

title: The Gallows
review: The Gallows offers exactly none of the frisson or pleasure of a found-footage film done right.

title: Vice
review: Bad doesn’t have to mean boring. Case in point: Vice, a bargain-bin high-concept sci-fi thriller full of Joel Schumacher-esque canted Steadicam moves, leaden expository dialogue, and cheap fluorescents-glued-to-the-wall sets.

title: Vice
review: Vice is a low-budget sci-fi thriller that borrows heavily from “Blade Runner” and “Westworld,” and serves as an answer to the question “How much movie can you get when you shoot your $10 million film in Mobile, Alabama? The answer is, quite a lot — with modernist buildings, striking control room sets and the city’s docks serving as a backdrop.

title: Vice
review: A loud, dopey chase film filled with substandard shootouts.

title: Vice
review: Everything about Vice feels like recycled goods. It's basically "Westworld" meets "Blade Runner" programmed by glitchy filmmaking replicators.

title: Vice
review: The film unspools with a momentum that mitigates its artless brutality, kinda, but it's a high-pressure firehose of stupid.

title: Vice
review: Perversely low-budget and oddly devoid of imagination, Vice seems less like a proper film than a bargain-basement SyFy pilot, shot on the cheap and drafting off Willis and Jane’s star power. It’s about androids aching to be real, but it doesn’t have an ounce of genuine humanity in its tin heart.

title: Vice
review: Vice takes the basic premise from 1973's Westworld and morphs it into an incoherent slog.

title: Vice
review: Dull and lifeless, Vice fails on the promise of even its lowest ambitions.

title: Vice
review: Here’s hoping Bruce Willis bought something special with whatever cash he earned from this pointless, brutally ugly rehash of 1973’s “Westworld.”

title: Vice
review: Evidencing more bullets than brains, Vice — a bit of ephemeral science-fiction twaddle directed by Brian A. Miller — has absolutely nothing to recommend it.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: Grab on for dear life and expect a freakish, wild, and seriously f#cked up ride from start to finish - which, of course, is every horror fan's dream.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: While the scares are in short supply, there’s a surfeit of macabre, tongue-in-cheek creativity to be found here.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: Although it’s by far the weakest of the three, there are some genuinely creative moments that spark the brain and fry the hairs.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: Overall, this is easily the weakest of the three V/H/S anthologies thus far, particularly due to its connecting thread.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: Each propulsive segment features a handful of disturbing sequences... But such pleasures barely compensate for the vapidity of V/H/S: Viral's sketches.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: Getting four mediocre horror efforts for the price of one doesn't exactly represent a significant bargain.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: One need go no further than the film's first segment to grasp how little interest the latest entry in the anthology series has in generating chills from the lo-fi.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: A sequel so slapdash and ineffectual that its army of directors — six of them total, counting the poor sucker whose contribution got axed — might well be accused of intentionally burying the franchise. More charitably, perhaps they were trying to put a nail in the coffin of all found-footage horror. Some good must come from this much bad.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: It feels like the series has run its course, and should be relegated to the dustbin of history alongside the hardware it so lovingly pays tribute to.

title: V/H/S Viral
review: There was little reason to expect such a horrendous drop in quality as there is to “Viral,” a film that contains some of the sloppiest, most ineffective filmmaking I’ve seen all year.

title: Grease 2
review: "Grease 2" is the most serendipitous sequel in recent memory. It is an ingratiating, jubilant improvement on a crummy original.

title: Grease 2
review: Where this film has a decided edge on its predecessor is in the staging and cutting of the musical sequences. Choreographer and director Patricia Birch has come up with some unusual settings (a bowling alley, a bomb shelter) for some of the scenes, and employs some sharp montage to give most of the songs and dances a fair amount of punch.

title: Grease 2
review: Light years ahead of Randal Kleiser's 1978 original, this 1982 sequel employs the Shakespearean marriage plot so beloved of classic musicals, in which two mismatched couples are straightened out and the songs express the moral distinctions of love and sex.

title: Grease 2
review: Birch's confidence as a director ebbs and flows throughout -it's odd that she can direct the complicated musical numbers so well and bungle the action scenes so badly. Yet in the end it's hard to resist the movie's bubble-gum romanticism. There's even a dream sequence in which the heroine sings to a vision of her fantasy boyfriend, who appears in heaven in a silver-lame biker's outfit. What can-you say in the face of such sublime silliness but hooray for Hollywood? [14 June 1982, p.88]

title: Grease 2
review: Definitely of the so-bad-it's-almost-good genre, this kinda stands the test of time in a camp way, mainly because of the charm of Pfeiffer and Carrington.

title: Grease 2
review: Such niceties as a plausible plot and three-dimensional characters are trampled under Weejun-shod foot, but sheer energy, a handful of good tunes (including a great theme song from the Four Tops), and some very funny one-liners save the day.

title: Grease 2
review: This movie just recycles "Grease," without the stars, without the energy, without the freshness and without the grease.

title: Grease 2
review: Most conspicuously absent is John Travolta, replaced here by Maxwell Caulfield, who can't lift the original greaser's comb. Michelle Pfeiffer (MARRIED TO THE MOB; DANGEROUS LIAISONS) fares better as Olivia Newton-John's replacement, but the whole movie looks as if it has been slapped together to capitalize on its predecessor's success, and no doubt, it was.

title: Grease 2
review: The sequel to Grease is not much more than a remake, wherein every minute detail is nothing more than an attempt to pilfer the magic of the first film.

title: Grease 2
review: Less a sequel than a retread...Dizzy and slight, with an even more negligible plot than its predecessor had. This time the story can't even masquerade as an excuse for stringing the songs together.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: Director Peter Bonerz and writer Stephen J. Curwick (the latter taking his second Academy shift) both cut their teeth on TV sitcoms, and it shows. Rarely has a film cried out so desperately for a laughtrack.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: There are some witty moments, as when the straight man, Proctor, played as usual by Lance Kinsey, uses a squeaky rubber squeegie to wash a window while his partner, Harris (G. W. Bailey), holds a stethoscope to the window to eavesdrop on a conversation taking place on the other side. But most of what takes place in Police Academy 6, from the flying billiard balls to the exploding cigars, are things you have seen someplace before. [3 March 1989, p.1-17]

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: Except there are all these dumb pranks even a third-grade schoolboy would be too embarrassed to commit - putting glue on chairs, making silly faces and stupid noises, setting off fireworks at the precinct house. [13 March 1989, p.5D]

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
