review: This is probably worse than you’d expect, even from a sequel to a sequel to a sequel to a sequel to a sequel.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: On the plus side, POLICE ACADEMY 6 is skillfully photographed by Charles Rosher, Jr., and has a very good soundtrack, supplied by Robert Folk. Unfortunately, high production values are wasted on films this slow-paced and silly.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: Surely the nadir of the rehash genre, a string of unconnected party pieces by a cast whose world weariness would imply that they know exactly how cynical this whole venture has become.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: In Police Academy 6: City Under Siege, the humor (kind word, that one) vacillates between the soporific and the moronic.

title: Police Academy 6: City Under Siege
review: This is comedy so insidious it could scarcely be less than diabolically inspired; to know these 84 minutes is to know an endless living death. [14 March 1989, p.C6]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: Though many characters are dispatched in various gory ways, the film gives them more to do than the have-sex-and-die victims of past entries. Director Adam Marcus and writers Dean Lorey and Jay Huguely give them some personality, and the acting is also generally better than in the previous Fridays.

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: After a promising opening, with Jason on a rampage and a cold, peculiar bounty hunter (Steven Williams) on Jason's trail, Jason Goes to Hell switches focus midway to the young couple, and from there things go downhill. Still, the film has its moments. [14 Aug 1993, p.F1]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: The scriptwriters try to conjure some history/mythology to validate the plot's twists and turns, but the whole thing ends up more confusing than Days of Our Lives on fast-forward.

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: One might have hoped for some semblance of vitality and ingenuity in this, Jason's ninth and final solo killing spree, but it's a retread to its rotten core. [14 Aug 1993, p.C3]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: It's as stupid, unimaginative and cheesy as the rest of them. [16 Aug 1993, p.C2]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: A largely incoherent movie that generates little suspense and relies for the majority of its thrills on close-up gore.

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: On the movie's feeble plus side are Richard Gant's acting (as the coroner), Manfredini's music and one funny joke in the last half-minute. On the minus side: ludicrous characters. Garbled nonstop gore. Persistent loud, clanging noises that give you the impression of being trapped inside a malfunctioning radiator. Shadowy lighting that makes you feel as if you're staggering around in the dark. [16 Aug 1993, p.F3]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: Not that anyone expected logic, but no one expected the series to so completely abandon much of what was familiar to the audience and become an amalgam of countless other horror-fantasies and pop culture media. [16 Aug 1993, p.24]

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: Jason goes to hell, and not a moment too soon. His descent has been far too long in coming, as the exhausted, witless Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday demonstrates.

title: Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday
review: While the Nightmare on Elm Street movies possess a sick yet clever surrealism, and the first Halloween was at least well crafted, the Friday the 13th series has always been the cut-rate horror franchise, offering barely functional sex-and-slash pitched straight at the moron brigade. Jason Goes to Hell varies the formula a bit, with ideas swiped from The Terminator, The Hidden, and Alien, but after nine installments the impalements and dismemberments all look the same. So go to hell already, Jason — and take Sean Cunningham, the ”brains” behind this dreck, with you.

title: Thunderbirds
review: Smartly written by William Osborne and Michael McCullers, Thunderbirds expertly targets kids. Yet parents won't be entirely bored.

title: Thunderbirds
review: This special-effects-crammed action blockbuster is not rocket science. It's more like rocket fun.

title: Thunderbirds
review: It's a pretty entertaining, extremely good-looking cinematic blip--not important, not outstanding, but better than a lot of PG stuff that attempts to reach both parents and their 8-year-old kids.

title: Thunderbirds
review: Without fail its upbeat cheesy wholesomeness is always good for a smile.

title: Thunderbirds
review: The story rarely gets fired up to "maximum thrust," to use the rocket-speed parlance of its heroes.

title: Thunderbirds
review: Kids are most likely to be entertained by this live-action offering, although baby-boomer fans of the series will appreciate how closely it hews to the show's foundation.

title: Thunderbirds
review: It's clean and cheerful entertainment, blithely piggybacking on a beloved classic. No wonder Anderson washed his hands of this project - the filmmakers tampered with and trampled on his magic formula.

title: Thunderbirds
review: Thunderbirds is devoted to the principle that character and story are but rude interruptions to the real order of business, an endless display of profound vehicle fetish.

title: Thunderbirds
review: Watching a misfire like Thunderbirds illustrates how impressive the "Spy Kids" movies are.

title: Thunderbirds
review: As the dapper Lady Penelope, Sophia Myles tries to infuse the enterprise with some "Charlie's Angels" verve, but she's only one life vest, and the movie is a downed plane.

title: Zoom
review: If August has turned the children in your life into Bored Girl and Fidget Boy, you could find worse ways to keep them entertained.

title: Zoom
review: Pure Saturday matinee kiddie fodder and this close to going straight to DVD.

title: Zoom
review: A family-friendly adventure.

title: Zoom
review: Zoom is a movie that would make Dr. Frankenstein proud. Put together with parts from so many other movies, the thing positively clanks.

title: Zoom
review: This tepid comic-bookish comedy should zip through its theatrical run faster than a speeding bullet. It likely won't perform much more superheroically in ancillary venues.

title: Zoom
review: Tim Allen gamely brings some humanity to the role of the retired, powerless hero Captain Zoom, but is thwarted at every turn by bad special effects, slapdash editing, interminable pop-song montages, and a goofy performance by Courteney Cox.

title: Zoom
review: Bleeds boredom from every frame.

title: Zoom
review: One of the most dismal excuses for family entertainment ever perpetrated by a major studio, this crude, lazy variation on Disney's "Sky High" (2005) revolves around the education of four "special" youngsters at the hands of a washed-up superhero.

title: Zoom
review: Zoom is a C-list production in every possible way, from the actors and the special effects to the music and the script. Even the product placement is completely third rate.

title: Zoom
review: A kid comedy that's been zapped by extraterrestrial suckiness rays.

title: Fat Albert
review: The film is sweet and often genuinely funny, with lively musical numbers and a cast of entertaining personalities.

title: Fat Albert
review: A spirited re-creation of the series that once ruled Saturday mornings.

title: Fat Albert
review: An awkward blend of live action and animation.

title: Fat Albert
review: The animated scenes conjure aromas of the stilted "Clifford," and the overall approach is to throw preordained movie sequences (rap number, shopping spree) together and hope for the best.

title: Fat Albert
review: Kenan Thompson may not look the part, but he's instantly likeable as Fat Albert.

title: Fat Albert
review: Fat Albert's originality is lost on the big screen.

title: Fat Albert
review: While endearing as cartoons, they don't wear flesh well.

title: Fat Albert
review: fFat-footed and ham-handed in its attempt to reconstitute a popular '70s TV cartoon show as a full-length, family-skewing feature.

title: Fat Albert
review: Alas, this eternally sunny character's mantra, "I don't have a problem, I solve problems," makes for paltry dramatic tension.

title: Fat Albert
review: Basic knowledge of the original series is mandatory, but the more familiar you are, the more glaring this movie's considerable deficiencies will seem.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Basic Instinct 2 isn't bad, exactly, but it lacks the entertaining vulgarity of the first film; it's Basic Instinct redone with more ''class'' and less thrust.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Those hoping for either a sizzling -- or an unintentionally hilarious -- good time will be disappointed by this inexplicably dull sequel.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Basic Instinct 2 pushes diligently along in a murder-and-mayhem-stuffed effort to demonstrate that (a) a sillier and more hackneyed movie than "Basic Instinct" is possible and (b) that shrinks have ids too, by golly.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Once the credits are done rolling it's a dour, enervated mystery, selling the old cat-and-mouse games.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Where is the suspense part? There is no suspense part. Suspense demands clarity of motive and action, and this screenplay never provides it.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Basic Instinct 2 is pretty awful. Rarely has a meaningless thriller had so many meaningful glances, or such arch acting by good actors who know better.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Fortunately, as a showcase for Sharon Stone's physique, Basic Instinct 2 is a rousing success. In every other respect, it's a colossal failure.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: A disaster of the highest or perhaps lowest order.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: Stone still dazzles the eye, but this wholly unwarranted sequel is so outrageously preposterous (and so very chockablock with quotable examples of the fine art of bad dialogue) that the end result achieves a basement grandeur of near-epic proportions.

title: Basic Instinct 2
review: The laughs to be had in this deliciously awful sequel are all unintentional. A bummer for film buffs, but a ball for fans of the misbegotten.

title: Cell
review: This apocalyptic thriller is a run-of-the-mill zombie flick that goes through the genre motions efficiently enough but fails to live up to its credits.

title: Cell
review: While it’s nice to see Cusack and costar Samuel L. Jackson downplay rather than go big, Cell has a been-there-done-that quality that winds up feeling a bit disappointing.

title: Cell
review: Directed by Tod Williams (Paranormal Activity 2) and co-scripted by King himself, it brings a best seller to the big screen with a minimum of spectacle, a maximum of affordable Georgia locations, and a couple of names to splash prominently across the Amazon rental thumbnail.

title: Cell
review: This is the undead equivalent of fast food. Some might find comfort in all these known quantities. Those looking for anything of substance would do better to wait for an upgrade.

title: Cell
review: Though it's better than its "dump this thing" theatrical release would suggest, Cell is far from excellent.

title: Cell
review: King worked on the script for Cell, which isn’t that surprising given that many of the worst adaptations of his work have his name on them. It only proves how hard a job it is to adapt King. Even the author himself can’t ace it.

title: Cell
review: The film insufficiently connects the book's prophecy with its present-day, real-world forms of realization.

title: Cell
review: For John Cusack in Cell, the bad news is that his phone just ran out of juice. The good news, sort of, is that those who are on their phones were just attacked by a piercing signal that turned them into flesh-munching zombies.

title: Cell
review: Given the absurdity of the premise, Cell isn’t nearly as luridly entertaining as it should be.

title: Cell
review: King's decision to co-write the script and turn it into a CliffsNotes version of The Stand only makes things worse.

title: College Road Trip
review: You know a movie has taken a very strange turn when you find yourself eagerly awaiting the next appearance by Donny Osmond.

title: College Road Trip
review: At its best when it drops any pretense of plot for sheer goof (as when a Japanese sightseer belts ''Sister Christian'' on a karaoke tour bus), and at its worst when Lawrence manages to out-ham even his porky four-legged costar.

title: College Road Trip
review: This overplayed, underachieving laffer feels thoroughly manufactured to Disney specifications.

title: College Road Trip
review: Lawrence's descent from hyperactive foulmouth to G-rated father figure has been in evidence for years now, but watching director Roger Kumble move from flawed but juicy projects like "Cruel Intentions" to pap like this is a depressing career development.

title: College Road Trip
review: Perhaps there will be people who do laugh at Lawrence and Raven-Symon screaming in tandem, or mugging their way along every tortured mile of their road trip, or unwittingly joining a sky-diving club and having to parachute into Washington so Melanie can make her interview. Heck, it was all really funny when they did it on "I Love Lucy."

title: College Road Trip
review: What is puzzling is the incompatibility of the two leads with their roles. Raven is supposed to be a high school senior on a road trip to check out prospective universities. But she acts like a adolescent on a sugar high during a weekend sleepover.

title: College Road Trip
review: Eyes popping and mouths agape, Martin Lawrence and Raven-Symoné mug their way through College Road Trip as if it were a silent movie -- which, come to think of it, would have been a lot less irritating.

title: College Road Trip
review: As generic as its title, College Road Trip feels like a first draft, the one the studio brings to the rewrite team that, in this case, never got hired.

title: College Road Trip
review: Lawrence runs through his usual repertory of mugging, seething and generally acting like a fool, only to be regularly upstaged by Arnold, Trey's pet piglet.

title: College Road Trip
review: The tagline for College Road Trip is "You Can't Get There Fast Enough." But for those who sit through this humorless and massively predictable movie, a more apt phrase would be: "You Can't Get Out of There Fast Enough."

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: So it's a half-certainty, half-shock that Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance is both good and bad, a sequel that's hungry for thrills but bereft of the cohesiveness - and budget - to be a full meal.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: Cage-ophiles will find some delectable freakouts in Blaze's transformation - or near transformation - scenes. Otherwise, the committee-penned script combines yokel-friendly haw-haw irreverence (non-sequitur cutaways to the Rider pissing in a flamethrower pattern) and sweaty monologues about "controlling the Rider" (the character is basically a mean drunk's superhero).

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: Spirit of Vengeance is so focused and, as a result, so impoverished that you actually feel bad for Cage. The actor tries to bring the weird (though at this point one wonders if he can even do anything else) but the film more often than not leaves him high and dry, saddling him with standard-issue action hero lines and boilerplate action set-pieces.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: The smugness of the film grows wearying long before the end. Just because the people on and behind the camera are willing to acknowledge what we're watching is ridiculous crap doesn't really change the fact that, well, it is.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance offers Cage plenty of opportunities to tap his inner circus geek, to twitch, cackle and flail without shame, going full tilt batwing crazy. Not since he danced in a pagan bear suit in The Wicker Man has Cage appeared this unconcerned about what the audience will think.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: Like "Ghost Rider: Low Voltage," this is a surprisingly underpowered excursion into Marvel's mad world by Neveldine and Taylor. More purgatory than hellfire.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: A water-treading sequel offering just enough kooky color to keep less-discerning funnybook fans occupied, Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance nudges its obscure hero's mythology forward a bit without seeming to care much how it gets there.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: Most of the movie's action-horror set pieces play like lame Gwar music video outtakes, and Cage's signature mix of irony and off-the-rails mugging only works when you can see the actor's face. In Ghost Rider form, his character is just a skeletal automaton with neither a tongue nor a cheek to put it in.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: The only part of this movie anyone's ever going to remember is the pair of scenes in which Ghost Rider pees flame.

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
review: One look at the dreadful mess that is Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance will turn your whisper into a primal Cage scream: MAKE THIS MOVIE STOP!

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: A faster, funnier follow-up in which CGI-enhanced canines and felines effect a temporary truce to combat a common enemy.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: A clever, funny movie that will entertain kids and adults.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: This isn't so much that the story and characters are weak -- though they very much are -- but that animatronics and computer animation so anthropomorphize these critters that they bear more resemblance to cartoons than actual flesh-and-fur animals.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: The movie is geared to preschoolers, so only parents dragged with them may complain. There's only that Looney Tunes overture to savor before the Acme production begins.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: Tedious time-killer of a kiddie comedy.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: Although it's great fun for the under-8 set and for those of us monitoring the chaos theory that is Nolte's career of late, this film is otherwise mediocre and features some of the most uninvolving 3-D CGI since "Clash of the Titans" earlier this year.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: About as unremarkable as a film about talking animals organized into competing intelligence agencies can be.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: No movie -- whether aimed at adults or kids or canines themselves -- has the right to be as tiresome and unoriginal as this action-comedy mutt.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: Fails to deliver enough clever gags, emotional warmth, or eye-popping 3D to compete with recent family releases.

title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
review: And it's still, in the spirit of the original film, an unbelievable piece of sh--.

title: Movie 43
review: At its best, Movie 43 resembles a risqué episode of Saturday Night Live - a comparison reinforced by the presence of both parody ads and Jason Sudeikis. At its worst? Let's just say that Hugh Jackman fans who want to remember the actor as Jean Valjean and not as a guy with a scrotum sprouting from his neck should make alternate plans this weekend.

title: Movie 43
review: An oddity recommended for only the most fervent, undemanding comedy junkies.

title: Movie 43
review: The kindest thing to be said of Movie 43, a star-saturated collection of crude one-joke vignettes made with big-time directors, is that most of the participants seem to relish being naughty.

title: Movie 43
review: Quite why A-listers Kate Winslet, Hugh Jackman and Emma Stone (among others) aligned themselves with this excruciatingly moronic compilation of shorts is anybody's guess.

title: Movie 43
review: Just no.

title: Movie 43
review: As sick-making sketch comedies go, this stupefyingly bad one-somehow rife with A-list talent-must rank near the very bottom.

title: Movie 43
review: The sketches aren't united by a half-ignored framing device, so much as by an enduring fascination with bodily functions. Movie 43 is the most star-studded collection of jokes involving menstruation, flatulence, incest, bestiality, Snooki, and nutsacks ever assembled, but the stars don't elevate the material-they just descend to its level.

title: Movie 43
review: Despite the dizzying array of talent involved both in front of and behind the camera, this godawful exercise is so painfully unfunny, so screamingly bad that it immediately qualifies as one of the worst films of all time.

title: Movie 43
review: If you mashed-up the worst parts of the infamous "Howard the Duck,'' "Gigli,'' "Ishtar'' and every other awful movie I've seen since I started reviewing professionally in 1981, it wouldn't begin to approach the sheer soul-sucking badness of the cringe-inducing Movie 43.

title: Movie 43
review: This is barely a movie at all, mostly due to its structural similarities to "SNL", but also because it acknowledges the fact that its own premises are inherently unfilmable.

title: Fantastic Four
review: Ultimately, Fox’s stab at reviving one of its inherited Marvel properties feels less like a blockbuster for this age of comics-oriented tentpoles than it does another also-ran — not an embarrassment, but an experiment that didn’t gel.

title: Fantastic Four
review: Director Josh Trank, whose debut feature “Chronicle” put a smart new spin on superhero tropes, has assembled a quartet of engaging, charismatic performers and stranded them in a miasma of exposition and set-up that sinks the movie.

title: Fantastic Four
review: This reboot of the Marvel superhero franchise is a film of two halves: the first likeable and fun, the second tiresome and loud.

title: Fantastic Four
review: The cast are some of the most promising actors of their generation, but what chemistry there is between them is swept away by wave after wave of expository dialogue and ludicrous exclamation.

title: Fantastic Four
review: Ponderous, pretentious and, most damning of all, just not much fun.

title: Fantastic Four
review: As an origin story that’s all origins and no story, there’s a hollow, stale feeling to this occasionally admirable attempt to Nolanise Marvel’s dysfunctional family.

title: Fantastic Four
review: A good cast led by Miles Teller gets swallowed up in a narrative that grows progressively more muddled and tedious.

title: Fantastic Four
review: In turning his back on the familiar tropes of blockbuster comic book movies, Trank doesn't have a clear new identity for Fantastic Four to distinguish itself with, and the result is a movie rich with possibilities, but trapped in the basic structure of a superhero movie, with no idea of how to wholly circumvent traditional expectations.

title: Fantastic Four
review: Fantastic Four is so bereft of all the things we expect from a superhero movie — humor, excitement, adventure, awe — that it plays like a drawn-out pilot episode for an upcoming TV series no one would ever watch again.

title: Fantastic Four
review: A sense of heaviness, gloom and complete disappointment settles in during the second half, as the mundane set-up results in no dramatic or sensory dividends whatsoever.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Yoga Hosers is the best film Kevin Smith has made in a long time, which admittedly isn’t saying much. But this new cult comedy-thriller may well represent a turning point for the writer-director.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Yoga Hosers isn’t a bad time at the movies, but it’s painful when the gags fall flat.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Yoga Hosers is a movie that feels like it was more fun to make than to watch.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: While Yoga Hosers continues Smith’s quest to push himself into increasingly strange and uncomfortable directions as a filmmaker, it’s either too derivative or too malformed to work the vast majority of the time.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Kevin Smith's Yoga Hosers is a flabby, goofy, comically inert cartoon.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Even fans who've stuck with Smith for two decades may draw the line at this outing, which offers ingredients just as inexplicable as those in Tusk (it's a sort of spinoff of that film) without the captivating weirdness that sometimes brought that midnighter to life.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Any of the film's attempts at moralizing are subsumed by Kevin Smith’s obsession with taking aim at his critics.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: [A] lazy affair that aims for inspired lunacy but misses the mark by a mile.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: If it’s true, as Kevin Smith noted in his lengthy introductory remarks at Sundance, that “failure is just success training,” then he should be in the best shape of his career after Yoga Hosers, an imbecilic, strenuously wacky helping of see-what-sticks juvenilia.

title: Yoga Hosers
review: Yoga Hosers is lazy, unfunny, and self-indulgent.

title: Exposed
review: Asking far more questions than it could ever answer, Exposed ends on a note so flat and predictable that it undermines all that went before. But there are strange and memorable moments here, and a mood of eerie foreboding that’s hard to shake.

title: Exposed
review: In certain mutilated pictures, you can detect the lineaments of greatness: Consider Orson Welles’s “The Magnificent Ambersons.” Here, that’s not the case.

title: Exposed
review: Exposed mainly serves to expose the often torturous process of moviemaking and distribution.

title: Exposed
review: If it’s any consolation to the parties involved, Exposed could have ended up being worse; however, it’s unlikely that it could have been much better. Trainwreck-bad movie enthusiasts will be disappointed to find a film largely defined by its lack of energy, in which every scene seems to be stalling for time.

title: Exposed
review: It’s hard to imagine how anything salvageable could have been made out of [Gee Malik Linton's] comically pretentious script with its heavily religious overtones and plotting that grows more ridiculous by the minute.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: Led by a few strong performances, and delivering plenty of heart-clutching moments, The Bye Bye Man is sure to appeal to horror lovers of all stripes.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: Title deploys a fairly effective range of horror techniques, including jump scares, misdirection and some oddly unattractive VFX to ratchet up the tension, although gore is at a minimum.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: Even when it seems to be making things up as it goes along, its slapdash hallucinatory quality is a token gesture toward placing you inside the characters’ heads.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: The borderline campy The Bye Bye Man is a horror movie in search of an urban legend. Based on a chapter in the 2005 collection of allegedly strange-but-true paranormal tales "The President’s Vampire," the premise is second-rate Stephen King.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: What we’re left with are a few PG-13 murders, uninspired performances, some not-so-scary urban legends and a couple of actresses who must be wondering how they got here.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: The concept is derivative of about a dozen other movies and their sequels.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: The Bye Bye Man is a moldy slice of Wisconsin-set cheese, a horror film that manages as many unwanted laughs as frights.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: Title’s command of the material is haphazard, her direction not artful enough to know when expository clunkiness is undercutting the chance to dig into the meat of personalities in deterioration.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: The Bye Bye Man just skirts so-bad-it’s-good territory, unintentionally making the audience laugh more than they gasp.

title: The Bye Bye Man
review: The Bye Bye Man is an unfathomably inept horror film; one that’s an obvious byproduct of The Babadook/It Follows brand of horror success. It is, without apology, one of the emptiest, nonsensical haunted thrillers ever to fail genre audiences.

title: Supergirl
review: It is a wonderfully wacko work, sparked with Cook's oomph, Dunaway's cackle and the superstar power of the sensational Slater. What a face! As long as people prevail over effects, Supergirl glitters, she glows. [23 Nov 1984, p.27]

title: Supergirl
review: Director Jeannot Szwarc could have done more with the action scenes, but he has a snappy sense of pace and comic timing. Blond, blue-eyed Slater brings an engaging sweetness to Supergirl; and she plays Linda with an awkward, gawky girlishness, subtly different from her Supergirl role.

title: Supergirl
review: Helen Slater is a find: blonde as Supergirl, dark-haired as Linda Lee, she’s an appealing young heroine in either guise. Screenplay is filled with witty lines and enjoyable characters, but Jeannot Szwarc’s direction is rather flat.

title: Supergirl
review: Most delightful of the Super-series for its good-natured disregard of narrative considerations.

title: Supergirl
review: The gift of Christopher Reeve, in his best scenes and when the filmmakers allow it, is to play Superman without laughing, to take him seriously so that we can have some innocent escapist fun. Helen Slater has the same gift, but is given even less chance to exercise it in Supergirl, and the result is an unhappy, unfunny, unexciting movie.

title: Supergirl
review: Supergirl arouses some initial curiosity about the differences between the two cousins; for instance, that Supergirl can't change in phone booths and is much the better flier of the two. However the film, as directed by Jeannot Szwarc and written by David Odell, quickly loses its novelty.

title: Supergirl
review: Supergirl was directed by Jeannot Szwarc, whose previous big credit was Jaws II. The two films have something in common beyond their status as sequels to successful originals; both have a curiously flat, almost stale feel about them. And both are as disposable as Supertissue. [21 Nov 1984, p.C1]

title: Supergirl
review: Slater not only makes for a dull Supergirl, but she's stuck in a clumsy, silly film that tries for the light touch of Richard Lester's Superman II and fails decisively.

title: Supergirl
review: Jeannot Szwarc's direction is flat and uninspired, emphasizing the jokey elements without any sense at all for the material.

title: Supergirl
review: Queasily suspended between drag theatrics (Faye Dunaway and Brenda Vaccaro camping it up on a soundstage replica of a carnival spook house) and Spielbergian wholesomeness (Canadian Helen Slater as a toothy, Aryan Ubermadchen), this is one comic-book feature that doesn't fly.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Lame, but in a good way.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Highlander: The Final Dimension is elementary and vague, but this purportedly last installment works well enough on a comic book level. Music video veteran Andy Morahan, in his feature directorial debut, has the right idea: Go for as much energy, pace and visual panache as possible. [30 Jan 1995, p.F8]

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Lambert is as uncharismatic as ever, while Van Peebles is as frightening as a wrestler in mock angry mood, and just as ridiculous. To Morahan's credit, however, he smoothly continues the series' tradition of flashy images, showy sfx, aerial landscape shots and driving rock tunes.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Although Christopher Lambert repeats his film role as the immortal action hero, he is less dynamic than he was in Highlander or even Highlander 2, The Quickening. He is also far less charismatic and interesting to watch than Adrian Paul of the European television serial. Moreover, in this film, Lambert inexplicably whispers his lines, while the special effects are deafening.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Those immortals keep noting that there can be only one. Perhaps they mean there should have been only one.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Highlander: The Final Dimension is no more compelling than the average pile of bricks.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Highlander: The Final Dimension is exactly what it seems - drivel. [30 Jan 1995, p.D01]

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: An incoherent mess.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: An unbelievably trashy meltdown of the tartan warrior franchise, Highlander III checks in as a breakneck, roller-coaster genre ride that’s brainless fodder for undiscriminating auds.

title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer
review: Highlander 3 has an edge over its prequels in that it's so shoddily directed that it's probably a great deal of fun to watch after a couple of six-packs. Actually, that's probably the only time it might be fun to watch, and I'm not going to be the guy to put that theory to the test for you.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: Leisurely and overly familiar pic should appeal to young teen girls, but won't be breaking any B.O. bricks with its bare hands.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: This film feels like a desperate attempt to squeeze a few last bucks out of what was once a very obliging cash cow.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: The fourth film in the series, the newest installment has a new director, Chris Cain, and a female Kid, Hilary Swank, but otherwise it reprises the formula established by John G. Avildsen in 1984: A troubled teen conquers self-doubt and the local bullies with the help of an enigmatic karate teacher.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: If this installment is just slightly less laborious than Karate Kid II or III, it's not from Mark Lee's surprise-free script or Christopher Cain's placid direction, but because young Swank really might be a find. Early on, she's such a convincingly testy teen that parents may flinch, but she does seem to blossom before your eyes.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: Overlong and utterly predictable, The Next Karate Kid offers little excitement, even in its culminating fight sequence.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: Clearly, three sequels haven’t improved Miyagi’s English, but there is something bitchin’ about seeing a babe give a bully a good thwack. Not that girls will go see this or boys will care.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: Almost a guilty pleasure. But not quite.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: There's really nothing new here (as if anyone expected there would be), but it's a decent enough entry into the Karate Kid series, if you don't mind having seen it all done before, and better.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: The Next Karate Kid is harmless as children's entertainment, but for 104 very long minutes, there isn't a recognizable human being in sight.

title: The Next Karate Kid
review: It should be obvious to anyone at this point in time that Kid is getting a little long in the tooth. As Miyagi might say: Those who keep milking same idea . . . end up killing cash cow.

title: Bio-Dome
review: Even with the low expectations any reasonable viewer brings to a Shore flick, this rates only stupid-plus. The bongs-and-pajamas set, though, should be riveted.

title: Bio-Dome
review: A potentially amusing comic premise -- dropping a pair of anarchic stoners into the spaced-out, sanctimonious world of New Age bio-dome enthusiasts -- gets submerged in a shower of witless gags and the feeble one-joke persona of MTV celebrity Pauly Shore.

title: Bio-Dome
review: Thoroughly incoherent... A dreary fizzle. [12 Jan 1996, p.C12]

title: Bio-Dome
review: Shore possesses only two talents -- his ability to assume yoga-like positions and fondle his own behind, and his mystifying knack for getting starring roles in bad movies.

title: Bio-Dome
review: Pauly Shore is less a comedian than a class clown, and his dim-witted mugging makes Jim Carrey's antics seem creative triumphs by comparison. Vapid, vulgar, and more to the point, not funny.

title: Bio-Dome
review: A nonstop moronathon... Bio-Dome offers a pants-load of poop and masturbation jokes, deviant innuendo and simian sight gags destined to gross out and offend just about everyone.

title: Bio-Dome
review: This film may set an all-time record for shortest time between the big screen and your local video store.

title: Bio-Dome
review: Neither the script nor direction lives up to the concept, and the picture evolves into a "Bio"-degradable hash rather than a zany sendup of potent issues and serious intents gone awry.

title: Bio-Dome
review: [Shore] seems convinced that the antics of his retarded persona amount to some manner of postmodernist anti-comedy and this makes the resultant boredom seem all the more pathetic.

title: Bio-Dome
review: The sheer ineptitude of the movie is supposed to be funny, but there's no lunacy behind it: Shore and his writers are like comedians on Prozac, smiling through the fart jokes without a hint of desperation.

title: Species II
review: Most of this is silly, dim-witted stuff, but a few of the shocks carry some of the crude power of Jack Arnold's low-budget horror films of the 50s.

title: Species II
review: The only thing that distinguishes Species 2 is how awful it is.

title: Species II
review: "Species" at least had the benefit of Henstridge's glazed porn-doll perversity, but this time any glimmers of sexual ominousness are buried in a lame, desultory chase plot and in the woefully underimagined special effects.

title: Species II
review: Though it never really taps into the whole JFK-as-alien-sex-fiend plot as a source of satire, Species 2 is still the superior piece of trash its predecessor should have been.

title: Species II
review: What ensues is a Halloween-style blood bath accompanied by graphic sex scenes.

title: Species II
review: Shoddily plotted and unimaginative, Species II is a slapdash effort at best, creepily unaffecting and minus the T&A this sort of film so desperately hinges on.

title: Species II
review: Though Species II is far from serious and aimed squarely at the hairy-palmed, it really didn't need to be quite this rotten.

title: Species II
review: The best advice to give anyone who wants to see Species II--other than "don't go!"--is "don't eat!"

title: Species II
review: In the spring a monster's fancy lethally turns to thoughts of lust. This thought, reduced to a level contemptuous of taste and reasonable intelligence, underlies Species II.

title: Species II
review: Brain-melting, head-spinning rank toxicity that shows no evidence of intelligence as we know it.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: Eight different characters, all played by Murphy, all convincing, each with its own personality. This is not just a stunt. It is some kind of brilliance.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: This is a parlor trick, but it's a hell of a good one.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: Murphy is remarkably convincing -- even endearing -- as each of the characters.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: It's just like Paul McCartney's first solo album after the Beatles broke up; he played all the instruments himself -- because he could.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: Sporadically funny, the film seems weighted down, literally, with bulging, bulbous Murphys flatulating endlessly.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: An amazing technical accomplishment that never becomes a coherent movie.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: An annoying, unclever, unlikable movie.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: Wastes most of its 110 minutes making impotent jokes about male sexual behavior and the repugnance of old women.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: What was a ragged but often hilarious charmer has been genetically altered into a deafening and desperate mutant.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
review: It will linger like a foul odor or the taste of tinfoil between the teeth.

title: Jason X
review: A happily self-aware body-count flick that's as brutally funny as it is plain-old brutal. A broad slash of scary, sci-fi fun, the project leapfrogs all the Scream and Last Summer junk to carve itself a new, high-tech niche.

title: Jason X
review: The film has spunk. Unfortunately, the gore comes with brutal regularity, so that, despite Farmer and Isaac's attempts to liven things up, the film still just wears you down.

title: Jason X
review: The premise of Jason X is silly but strangely believable.

title: Jason X
review: It gets much more watchable in the last half-hour.

title: Jason X
review: A moviegoer's only defense against Jason is to avoid theaters showing this gruesome and derivative movie.

title: Jason X
review: There's a hint of nostalgia toward the end, with Jason encountering two nubile female campers in a virtual reality Camp Crystal Lake -- but it merely serves as a reminder that the franchise should have quit while it was ahead.

title: Jason X
review: Too much of Jason X plays it straight, and that means boredom. Murder and mayhem of this sort quickly becomes monotonous.

title: Jason X
review: Despite the futuristic setting, which relies so heavily on GGI effects that it looks like a feature-length production concept painting, this film is painfully predictable.

title: Jason X
review: The kind of a moron movie, which is built to be watched by people who haven’t even seen the other nine.

title: Jason X
review: The only chills to be found are courtesy of your theater's central air, and the suspense will come from the wait to see which disappointed kid in a hockey mask will be the first to slash the screen.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: Jumps at chance to be silly.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: Likable but negligible.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: A dumb, by-the-numbers children's movie.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: The 'roo doesn't talk, except in a dream sequence…I'm dying here.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: In the life-is-too-short category, file Kangaroo Jack as a sub-Farrelly Brothers, dumb-plus-dumber buddy picture.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: Indeed, the largely computer-generated Jack acts the pants off his co-stars, which can and should be taken with a whole trough full of salt.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: Straight from the fiery, churning bowels of high-concept hell comes Kangaroo Jack, Bruckheimer's idea of kid-friendly fare, and some of the longest 90 minutes ever committed to film.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: What better to do with such a quiet, majestic landscape than to liven it up with the noise and vulgarity of lowest-common-denominator American pop culture?

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: Were it not for the involvement of producer Bruckheimer, who has made billions by conning millions into believing they can't live without his celluloid crack, it's doubtful Kangaroo Jack would even exist. As it stands now, the "movie" barely exists anyway.

title: Kangaroo Jack
review: It's fitting that the kangaroo gives the most lifelike performance.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: What's fun is that the road to that climactic Capitol showdown is paved with one ridiculous and relentlessly edited set piece after another.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: A smooth blend of visual special effects, exceptional stunts, fluid photography, sharp design and a possible best-selling soundtrack.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: Most of the movie is standard action fare, but the political commentary is interesting when it's allowed to surface.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: Basically the first movie all over again, with plenty more of the bridge-jumping, rocket-launching action that audiences loved about the original.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: You'd half expect the Xbox logo to pop up on the credit roll for XXX: State of the Union, since what's on view is closer to a videogame than a movie. While that will be music to the ears of young gamers, it's noise to anyone hoping for a coherent action movie.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: What isn't scary--or exciting, amusing or fun--is XXX: State of the Union, a movie so preposterous, cliché-packed and over the top that it makes the original "XXX" seem as good as the original "State of the Union."

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: One can give Ice Cube props for attitude, but not much more.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: The special effects excite at first but wear out their welcome.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: Loud, dumb and obnoxious.

title: xXx: State of the Union
review: Appalling sequel.

title: Ultraviolet
review: For this violent yet gore-free film, clearly designed for horny teenaged video game wizards, writer-director Kurt Wimmer stages a succession of fight sequences that pit V against helmeted thugs who appear to have raided the Star Wars storm trooper costume closet.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Amid every action cliche in the book, outmoded stereotypes, and a plot derivative of every futuristic drama made in the last fifteen years, Ultraviolet comes off as nothing more than a pale copy of better, more inventive films.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Mr. Wimmer is more concerned with fetishizing his heroine and patronizing his audience. The verdict? Ultrasilly.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Director Kurt Wimmer has an eye for jackboot chic (Equilibrium), and the images here have been digitally polished so that the characters' skin is smoother than porcelain. It's a cool effect--I spent most of this interminable actioner wondering if one could bounce a quarter off Jovovich's bare midriff.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Ultraviolet, unscreened for critics, is unfit for consumption.

title: Ultraviolet
review: An all-but-incoherent mess whose main components are palpably fake-looking CGI effects, video-game-style action sequences and Milla Jovovich's admirably taut abdomen, Kurt Wimmer's film epitomizes just about everything wrong with post-MATRIX, comic book-/video-game-inspired, Hong Kong-action-style sci-fi thrillers.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Jovovich is bad, and not in a good way. She turns in an epically expressionless performance (maybe she thought it was one of her modeling gigs?) but she sure looks great.

title: Ultraviolet
review: The latest entry in the "This film is so bad we're not screening it for critics" genre.

title: Ultraviolet
review: Pic is hermetically sealed in a synthetic wrapping that's so total -- Sony's top-flight high-def cameras, visibly low-budget CG work, exceptionally hackneyed and imitative action and dialogue --that it arrives a nearly lifeless film.

title: Ultraviolet
review: A cut-rate ripoff of "Aeon Flux" with Milla Jovovich as a butt-kicking futuristic heroine in a midriff-baring bodysuit, is ultrastupid, ultra-incoherent, ultrasilly - and way, way ultraboring.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: The star (Allen), unleashed, is so energetic in his approximation of a bearded collie -- his nose sniffing the air, his whole being (which toggles between human and canine form) overcome by the need to fetch any stick thrown -- that his slobbery charm carries the picture.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: A fast-moving Walt Disney Co. comedy that manages to sail past many of the cliches usually found in this genre while throwing together a wild story line more apt for a new millennium.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: Ms. Curtin is one of several examples of quirky casting that make this Shaggy Dog much more fun than it might have been.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: In this serviceable remake of the fondly remembered 1959 Disney comedy (which starred Fred MacMurray), an impressively dexterous Tim Allen plays Dave Douglas.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: There are precious few surprises here, but parents will find director Robbins' breezy remake a painless affair and, judging by the yowls of laughter from the peanut gallery at the screening I attended, the kids will be barking all the way home.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: It says something for Robert Downey Jr. that in a movie where a man becomes a dog, Downey creates the weirdest character.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: Strictly for the very young who will find giggles in the anthropomorphic mash-ups and won't be too distracted by the predictably mawkish sitcom plot.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: This fur-fetched tale is bearable family viewing.

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: Okay, so when does the fun start?

title: The Shaggy Dog
review: As a comic actor, Allen's palette is limited to varying degrees of beige. He is not only boring, he's obnoxious and narcissistic. Where's the ASPCA -- the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Audiences -- when you need 'em?

title: Little Man
review: Almost in spite of itself, Little Man manages to deliver big laughs. It's not enough to make it a consistently funny movie, but this one-trick pony from the Wayans brothers has flashes of humor and sincerity that almost save it from its disastrous ending.

title: Little Man
review: There's no question, though, that the Wayanses have dialed down the outrageousness to nearly sub-PG-13 levels.

title: Little Man
review: The slapstick is funnier for the nifty CGI, and the script gets in some sly digs at racist cops and multitasking soccer moms.

title: Little Man
review: I'd be lying if I said I didn't laugh at some of this--though it's not as funny as Laurel and Hardy as toddlers in "Brats." But I wanted to slap myself whenever I did.

title: Little Man
review: Little Man only proves that some should just stick to the sketch comedy, and leave the big screen to "Big Daddys" like Adam Sandler who the critics tend to snub, but who know how to make an audience laugh.

title: Little Man
review: It's seldom a good sign when a Rob Schneider cameo elevates a comedy, but Little Man aims so low and fires so often that it can't miss all the time.

title: Little Man
review: Yes, in this day and age, a tall man can pretend to be a very short man pretending to be a baby who uses his innocent disguise to molest women and whack men in the nuts. Isn't that funny? No, actually, not so much.

title: Little Man
review: Once the initial round of breast-feeding and rectal thermometer bits is fired off, the picture starts to give off the funky whiff of unattended Pampers.

title: Little Man
review: There are probably some moviegoers who can laugh at the sight of a groin-punching, breast-grabbing baby, possibly even find it cute. Everyone else should steer clear of Little Man, which welds Marlon Wayans' head to a diminutive body double, offering up the creepiest bigscreen dwarf since the last David Lynch movie.

title: Little Man
review: Somewhere within all the crude slapstick and crass stereotypes, Little Man operates as a vulgar burlesque on the crisis of African-American manhood, particularly the relationships, or lack thereof, between fathers and sons.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: Handles the strained daddy/daughter bond with sufficient lightness and laughs so that fathers won't mind accompanying their spawn.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: A goofily endearing romp that might even lasso a few new fans.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: If you are a big fan of country music, you will enjoy it for the Taylor Swift, Rascal Flatts, Billy Ray Cyrus and of course, Miley Cyrus performances.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: There are sufficient pratfalls and Miley/Hannah quick-changes to satisfy the fans, while Cyrus retains that natural, unforced likability that made her a star in the first place.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: Like 2003's "Lizzie McGuire" movie, "Hannah" breaks little new ground but makes the big screen shift with liveliness and sense of humor impressively intact.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: In the end, Hannah Montana: The Movie is big, beautiful, a little boring and utterly safe. There are flashes of inspiration -- the "Hoedown Throwdown" dance, the scenes between Martindale and the Cyruses -- but it also is what it is: Miley Cyrus' next big step.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: It's almost foolish to review Hannah Montana: The Movie as anything other than the latest cog in a cultural phenomenon/mass-marketing juggernaut. The film itself certainly doesn't aspire to anything more.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: I like the end-credits sequence best, which has nothing to do with hoary complications or the miseries of stardom or the magical spellbinding powers of a cheap wig.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: Miley may vacillate, but for now her indentured servitude to Disney continues. The image that comes to mind is Princess Leia chained to Jabba the Hutt, but that's probably just me.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
review: The only folks Montana is interested in pleasing are prepubescent girls and Disney stockholders.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: If the movie is a mess, it's a purposeful mess, cannily, if not artfully, pushing all the right buttons to ensure Perry will be back for another round.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: Though he plays two other roles, Perry only really cuts loose when he dons Madea's housecoat, turning her into a devilishly funny voice of reason. Likewise, the movie tenses up when she's offscreen, becoming the sort of moralistic soap opera we've seen from Perry before.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: Madea's physical comedy is loud enough to wake the dead, but its drama is just as excessive. In a neat bit of economy, Perry stages a wedding that doubles as a breakup, and triples as the villain's crowd-pleasing comeuppance. Now that is some serious multitasking.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: It's a tale soggy with the kind of race/class lessons that Madea, the director-star's battle-ax alter ego, doles out far more handily (and entertainingly) in a single church-lady-from-hell zinger.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: Wildly uneven effort, which is notably more strained and slapdash than such earlier efforts as "Madea's Family Reunion" and "Tyler Perry's Meet the Browns."

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: There is, however, Viola Davis, who might win an Oscar tomorrow for her one scene in "Doubt." Her part here - a minister combing the street for crack-whores to rescue - is about three times as large.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: It's great that Perry has seized opportunity for himself and for the performers he employs. But has he succeeded only in creating a kind of ghetto for black-themed entertainment that's of sub-par quality -- one that, admittedly, makes him a lot of money?

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: For all its staleness, the melodramatic main story does contain enough good acting and resonant scenes.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: There is something both satisfying and frustrating about Madea Goes to Jail. Mr. Perry dutifully gives his audience what it wants, but you can't help feeling that he might also have more to offer: more coherent narratives, smoother direction, better movies.

title: Madea Goes to Jail
review: Check off all of Perry’s motifs: vilification of the black bourgie princess, tough-love Christian messages, Academy Award–nominated actresses (Viola Davis, this time) managing to maintain their dignity.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: So even if Sex and the City 2 consisted of nothing but a two-hour fashion show, it would draw crowds. But it also has the returning cast members in fine comic form, and it has more cutting-edge humor than the first movie.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: Part of the action occurs in the desert, which inadvertently proves apt, since the oases of enjoyable moments -- and they do exist -- suffer from being spaced too widely in what's otherwise a long, arid trek.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: If “the gals” have to bow out, at least they try to do it in a sprint -- in their Manolo Blahniks. It’s a pity nobody told them you can’t run in heels -- in sand dunes.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: The "Fab Four's" dramadies continue for the audiences who love them. Trouble is the surrounding story and its supposedly fun sojourns are as embarrassing as granny panties.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: Sex and the City 2 isn't a feature film as much as it is consumer porn. The audience is not asked to relate to the characters, or at least what we remember of them, as much as to their shoes, their bags, their apartments, their couture, their stuff.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: It's over the top, and over the rainbow. But just like Carrie's worries about the "sparkle" leaving her marriage, this movie is like once-brilliant Champagne, carelessly left out overnight. And gone flat.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: One wrongheaded jaw-dropper follows another.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: An insult to the memory of the cleverly written show and its celebration of friendship, it's a slap in the face for the four gal pals (often photographed at unflattering angles) and an affront to Muslims.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: The most depressing thing about Sex and the City 2 is that it seems to justify every nasty thing said and written about the series and first feature film.

title: Sex and the City 2
review: Like its predecessor, SATC2--with a script that's basically a sack full of not very funny gag-lines wrapped in strung-together episodic mini-scenes--is not suited to be a movie.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: It goes down like a canned but genial '80s comedy: Without fanfare or much nutrition; part of your balanced breakfast.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Kind of a drag when it resorts to frantic slapstick and tired action-comedy tropes, but modestly engaging during stretches that suggest the project would have worked better as an exuberant musical.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Won't likely disappoint fans of men-in-drag comedy but doesn't offer much that's original or funny.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: John Whitesell's extraordinarily witless movie operates as a checklist for cultural and racial clichés.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Lawrence's gender-bending jokes are played out, and his slapstick is wooden and slow.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: A humorless mashup of "White Chicks" and "Glee."

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Fresh or not, creatively merited or not, here it comes: the third installment of Martin Lawrence's big, dopey franchise.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Whoever demanded a third installment of Lawrence's mirthless mash-up of weak gags and cross-dressing horrors should be imprisoned and forced to watch it on repeat until they repent. Avoid.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: Starved of humor and energy, the interminable Big Mommas: Life Father, Like Son could force Lawrence and co-star Brandon T. Jackson undercover for real.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
review: A film so drained of entertainment or simple humanity it is difficult to relate to as anything other than industrial artifact.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Unlike its obvious influence, the 1999 Japanese shocker "Audition," The Human Centipede has no real-world echoes. It's an only-in-the-movies sick goof.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Centipede plays on the notion that the only thing more frightening than death is a state bridging life and death, in which, though one's body is no longer his own to control, the mind remains conscious.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Dieter Laser is grand as the doc, a character Christopher Walken would be comfortable doing, and Akihiro Kitamura provides laughs as the first part of the centipede.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: More of a stunt than a script, The Human Centipede (First Sequence) should get a modest amount of I-dare-you ticket sales, but it's about as mass market as a dogfight.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: The only way to react is by bringing a barf bag or a strong sense of gallows humor.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Only real payoff is seeing the monstrosity assembled, and though that will surely earn the Dutch writer-director a cult reputation on the genre circuit, "going there" does not a movie make.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Excruciatingly stupid movie.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Six has now made a film deliberately intended to inspire incredulity, nausea and hopefully outrage. It's being booked as a midnight movie, and is it ever. Boozy fanboys will treat it like a thrill ride.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: The movie stinks to heaven.

title: The Human Centipede (First Sequence)
review: Crosses the line from horror to just plain sick.

title: Skyline
review: Technically ambitious, dramatically basic. Still, it's a major step up from an AvP sequel and delivers all the Saturday night whizz-bang and Sunday morning brain-ripping you could want.

title: Skyline
review: This sci-fi thriller manages to blend genuine suspense with unintentional laughs.

title: Skyline
review: Their (The Brothers Strause) effects are pretty good, on a fairly limited budget. And that's about all you can say for Skyline.

title: Skyline
review: Beyond the dazzling "first contact" sequences seen in the trailers, Skyline is a spasmodic and incoherent shambles hampered by an astoundingly stupid screenplay.

title: Skyline
review: The Strauses don't care about how to keep an audience. Their movie has no sense of suspense or dread - Skyline is an apocalypse movie that plods like one of Romero's zombies.

title: Skyline
review: So intent are the Strausses on showing off their visual chops, they leave the film's story, dialogue and acting in shambles.

title: Skyline
review: Skyline plays like an effects guru's resume reel, not a movie.

title: Skyline
review: Skyline is a piece of junk, even in a movie climate littered with expensive - though sometimes fun - junkiness.

title: Skyline
review: It's finally here: The most boring alien-invasion movie ever.

title: Skyline
review: Just plain bad. Boring. Unwatchable.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Either the "Alvin and the Chipmunks" movies are getting better, or I've accidentally buried my brain for the winter. The third entry in the franchise - Chip-Wrecked - is, dare I say, the charm.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: The sequel's target audience may be too young to realize that the best punch lines are long past their expiration date, but at least they're learning the idea of the catchphrase. They can hear the exclamation points.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Good news: The shrill CG rodents, who last infested theaters in 2009's Squeakquel, are stranded on a jungle island with little hope of survival. Bad news: They've brought us along.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Number of chipmunks who speak fluent chola when necessary: three. Number of Spider-Man/Pepe Le Pew mash-ups I can't really get into: one.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: With its wall-to-wall pop covers, Chipwrecked isn't a kids' movie so much as a brightly animated, instantly forgettable animated feature-length advertisement for the NOW That's What I Call Music! compilation series of contemporary pop hits.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Whatever character they bring to their lines, the actors' voices are mostly unrecognizable after being digitally 'munk-ified.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Every bit as frantic, frenetic, groan-inducing and all around grating as its two predecessors.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: Chipwrecked is the sort of Sunday afternoon trifle that will mollify children and mortify their parents, an eyesore that auto-tunes its strong cast into anonymity and undercuts its convincingly rendered CG leads by confining them to hideously cheap environments.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: It's that rare thing, a movie that clocks in under 90 minutes, but feels like an endurance test in every moment, at every plot concern, and every musical number.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
review: I really think the entire payoff to the Chipmunks' gambit comes in those inevitable moments when Dave bellows in exasperation, "Alvin." Maybe if we all bellow in unison it will be forceful enough to put an end to this painful film franchise.

title: The Darkness
review: It’s vaguely endearing to watch Bacon and Mitchell actually try to act their way through the film’s family drama, as though it weren’t a perfunctory pretext to jump scares. The Darkness needs their chops. It needs anything to distract horror fans from the fact that there’s nothing new here.

title: The Darkness
review: While McLean and company admirably aim for some relevance by tying the Taylors’ haunting to their personal demons, ultimately The Darkness is just the same old show: things that go bump in the night, and the tasteful decor they defile.

title: The Darkness
review: The Darkness offers very few new scares, mainly because it's so haunted by the ghosts of far better horror movies.

title: The Darkness
review: Bacon, Mitchell and especially young Lucy Fry are all quite effective in these dramatic scenes. But this isn’t a drama. It’s a dumbass, inexpensive horror flick which means anything real is thrown away so that poorly rendered CG ghosts can hover about and smash up windows.

title: The Darkness
review: The scariest thing about The Darkness turns out to be the trailers to this summer’s more promising horror offerings, “Lights Out” and “Don’t Breathe.”

title: The Darkness
review: At some point in the production process, co-writer/director Greg McLean must have believed he was making John Cassavetes’ “Poltergeist,” but this odd fusion of psychodrama and supernatural hokum gets away from him.

title: The Darkness
review: It’s like being haunted by outsized chimney sweeps that never bathe. And for the most part, it’s about that scary.

title: The Darkness
review: The Darkness is pretty much a total bust—it isn’t scary, it isn’t exciting and it plods along at such a snails pace that even though it clocks in at just over 90 minutes, it plays like it runs at least twice that.

title: The Darkness
review: This enterprise is so listless that one can't even work up a proper head of self-righteous steam over the spooky Native American clichés that drive the plot.

title: The Darkness
review: Amid the rarely very creepy buildup to the Amityville-ish showdown to come, the screenplay piles on more unrelated domestic drama than the picture can take.

title: Getaway
review: For the most part, Getaway lacks tension and violence. Strobe cuts rob the stunts of any sense of motion; twisting metal, seen in half-second snippets, becomes abstracted texture. While it’s possible to appreciate this stuff on an individual level, it doesn’t quite add up to an action-movie whole.

title: Getaway
review: What Getaway needed most is enough juice to get to the finish line, narratively speaking. Because while jumping into the car is great, the fun dies fast if there’s nowhere to go.

title: Getaway
review: Maybe they all took a gander at that random, ridiculous scenario and hoped that the car would be cool enough to bail them out. It isn’t.

title: Getaway
review: Easily one of the dopiest major studio releases since Elie Samaha got out of the business.

title: Getaway
review: This is not a remake of Sam Peckinpah's "The Getaway," but a new effort. The film is loaded with action and violence, although not in any logical or accessible way.

title: Getaway
review: It couldn’t be a simpler, more workable premise for a good B-movie, but the amount of effort put into making it fast and edgy is inversely proportional to the scant thrills it yields.

title: Getaway
review: Gomez plays ... well, that’s one of the problems. Her character is so underdeveloped in director Courtney Solomon’s movie that she doesn’t actually have a name.

title: Getaway
review: The film blinks too fast to maintain a coherent vision.

title: Getaway
review: Getaway seems built for non-English speaking territories in which dialogue is as disposable as Bulgarian police cars. If only those audiences were as dumb as the action itself.

title: Getaway
review: It's understandable that larger scale movies will want to spawn sequels, but this is about two degrees away from being a movie that premieres on Cinemax on a Friday night, sandwiched between two soft core porn movies with funny titles. Getaway is stuck in neutral. And that's where it'll stay.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: If anything, Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2 ups that sadness quotient, spending much of its opening proving that just because these movies are stupider than "Observe And Report" doesn’t mean they have to be less cripplingly depressing.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: It’s not that the film is particularly loathsome, or that Blart is an overweeningly horrible character. What rankles is that he’s barely anything at all; a stereotype of a stereotype; a half-remembered punchline; a stomach with a moustache and wheels. As you watch the film, it’s already forgotten.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Is it never funny? No, it’s not never funny. It’s just not funny nearly often enough.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Sequels are cynical by nature, but this one, with its casino product placement ad and director Andy Fickman apparently checking his text messages instead of trying to punch the limp gags into shape, is purely a paycheck. James may not deserve better, but the kids they’re pitching this to do.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2 does all it was created to do: exist.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Given that it comes courtesy of Adam Sandler’s production company Happy Madison... it’s no surprise that Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2 is a lazy, witless, laugh-free experience. But even by their standards, this is a slog to sit through, so glacially paced that at times it achieves an almost zen-like level of anti-comedy.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: While the original was no classic, it had a few mild laughs and the plus-sized actor displayed a certain buffoonish charm. Such is not the case with this painfully unfunny, slapdash follow-up in which the title character is so relentlessly obnoxious that you'll be cheering for the villains.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Nothing aired by WikiLeaks could possibly be more destructive to Sony’s reputation than the release of Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2, the sort of movie that goes beyond mere mediocrity to offer possible evidence of a civilization in decline.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: Nobody was expecting much from Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2, but did it have to be this unimaginative and lifeless?

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2
review: James' everyman appeal is stretched to the limits here, like that polyester shirt he wears.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: While the actors do a yeoman’s job in presenting their characters with aplomb (especially Jesse Metcalfe, as Wesley’s lawyer), the entire film simply comes off as a two-hour, jazzed-up movie version of a sermon.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: Its pulls back from the original film’s cruelty and comeuppances for non-believers, yet its non-Christian characters are still parodies of human evil: greedy, bitter, violent, and out to prove that “God is dead.”

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: There are serious movies about the Christian faith, about the persecution of the faithful, and about the intolerance that goes both ways. God's Not Dead 2 is not one of them.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: In a righteous world, the better-acted, upbeat and faith-affirming “Miracles from Heaven” would eat this angry tirade for lunch.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: The first film pandered to a heavy persecution complex; this installment’s relatively subtler, but there are dog whistles aplenty.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: There is a tone of anger that sneaks out of the film in even its moments of levity.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: God’s Not Dead 2 is a much better movie than God’s Not Dead, but that’s a bit like saying a glass of milk left on the table hasn’t curdled and is merely sour.

title: God's Not Dead 2
review: Dramatically speaking, God’s Not Dead 2 operates at the level of your average middle-school play – except with far greater levels of upside-down logic and bald-faced intolerance for anyone not enraptured by the New Testament.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: Despite the final escape of star Steve Guttenberg, and the loss, long since, of the original director and writers, this is almost a good movie. It's an incremental, heavily qualified success, but "PA 5" is an improvement on the elephantine, witless "2," "3" and "4."

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: But the formula is pretty long in the tooth by now, and all the extra turns of plot can't disguise that.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: Miami field trip only brings a pastel backdrop to the insipid infighting of the boobs in blue.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: Comedy doesn't have to be refined or original to be entertaining, but it ought to have a little flair. The gags of this "Academy" are blunt and literal, delivered without the careful set-ups or rhythms that, in the hands of a Laurel and Hardy, can make physical comedy into its own kind of poetry. [22 Mar 1988, p.C3]

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: The jokes? Passing gas, large breasts, schoolyard double entendre -- the usual run of recess humor. On the faces of most of the cast, one can clearly read despair, occasionally even irritation. They know: If you're much over 10, Police Academy 5 isn't going to keep you awake. [23 March 1988, p.C7]

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: Pretty terrible sequel in every respect.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: POLICE ACADEMY 5 presents a patchwork of ideas borrowed from a score of wittier and better-done comedies, not to mention earlier entries in the series. In short, it's exactly what you would expect it to be.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: The Apocalypse Now-style Wagnerian soundtrack that accompanies the air boat chase across the Everglades almost raises a smile. Otherwise it's business as usual: fart jokes.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: Those bumbling boys and girls in blue are back on the streets in Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach. And they're more moronic than ever -- '80s Keystone Kops dropping their pants, breaking wind and parading their big American "mangoes." Nothing is too degrading for these troupers. Gradually the more employable members of the original squad, such as Steve Guttenberg (not that he's so great), have gone on to better assignments. But the desperate have returned to reprise their roles in this fifth-rate rehash of the rather wonderful original. "5" is a comic assault, batteries not included, an insufferable collage of coarse slapstick vignettes.

title: Police Academy 5: Assignment: Miami Beach
review: I didn't laugh once during the entire film-not at the slapstick, not at the humor, all of which is pitched at the preschool level. [25 March 1988, p.A]

title: On Deadly Ground
review: The fuzzy thinking allows for gorgeous outdoor photography and a few too many dead spots, but Seagal the director shows real muscle by staging one of the screen's best-ever exploding helicopters and allowing Seagal the star to spit out tough talk, as when he refuses to shoot Caine because, "I don't want to dirty my bullets."

title: On Deadly Ground
review: Although you could certainly wish that Seagal and his writers, Ed Horowitz and Robin U. Russin, could have found less preachy ways to express themselves, On Deadly Ground is otherwise lively entertainment for action fans.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: It isn't difficult to identify those who will and won't like this film. There's plenty of violence, lots of fights and explosions, and the miniatures special effects work is impressive. A sizable portion of the Seagal crowd will likely be annoyed by the environmental message and the Eskimo religious practices because they interfere with On Deadly Ground's pacing. In the end, however, there's probably enough bang to overcome these flaws for Seagal's fans, if not anyone else.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: This is a vanity production parading as a social statement. It nonetheless has enough sound, fury and flash to satisfy the action crowd who have propped up Seagal’s career.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: Loud, stupid and clumsy.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: Mr. Seagal's own film is awesomely incoherent, a mixture of poorly executed violence and Dances With Wolves-style astral musings.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: This fuzzily illustrated sermon is mostly an attempt to prove that the internal combustion engine is obsolete, and that oil companies everywhere are conspiring to wipe out alternative methods.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: Martial arts maven Seagal has long been on deadly ground with critics, and this, his directorial debut, is likely to keep him there.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: Certain things must be answered, like Seagal's environmental lip service that is utterly mocked by the movie's need to blow things up and destroy property.

title: On Deadly Ground
review: What is there to do but laugh in self-defense at such pompous self-regard when blood gushes, fuses pop, and Seagal scowls in a series of snappy, embroidered buckskin jackets?

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: The problem here isn't as much the talent in front of the camera as it is the weak and hackneyed script. Vampire in Brooklyn is in need of an infusion (or should that be transfusion?) of originality and creativity -- two qualities that are blatantly absent.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Vampire in Brooklyn is neither funny nor frightening and comes up a tedious middle-road hybrid from veteran scaremeister Wes Craven, who directed.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Vampire is hardly a consequential film, nor does it suggest hitherto buried reserves of Murphy's talent. But it's a diverting mixture of horror, romance and comedy.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Vampire in Brooklyn isn't a disaster. In fact, it has some funny moments. But it's a long way from being the comeback movie Eddie Murphy needs. [27 Oct 1995, p.57]

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Neither all that scary nor all that hilarious, Vampire in Brooklyn falls directly between the two, into the valley of mediocrity.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
