review: The movie is unpleasant to look at. It's darker than "Seven," but without sufficient purpose, and my overall memory of it is of people screaming in the shadows. To call this a comedy is a sign of optimism; to call it a comeback for Murphy is a sign of blind faith.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: For years I've criticized Murphy for not working with the best directors or powerful female co-stars. But he does that here, and his movie is still a clunker. Relatives are listed in the credits; maybe he needs to stop trying to completely control the films he makes. Either that or it's time for another stand-up concert film. [27 Oct 1995, p.B]

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Eddie Murphy plays it straight rather than bawdy in A Vampire in Brooklyn. It takes some getting used to. As if to make up for all this seriousness, he plays a few funny characters in disguise. But despite his omnipresence, he seems comically missing.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Murphy has said that he wanted the picture to work both as a comedy and a horror movie, but he has succeeded at neither. Director Craven manages to wedge in some of his signature bits, but can't keep the comic elements in balance with the horror, and as a result there's no tension or dramatic pull.

title: Vampire in Brooklyn
review: Like so many Eddie Murphy misfires, Vampire in Brooklyn has no idea how to capitalize on the actor's immense appeal. The film was directed by the horror master Wes Craven and it turns out to be an Eddie Murphy-Wes Craven movie that is not funny or scary. Now that's a nightmare.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: The movie's comic heart consists of a series of indescribably loopy, elaborately conceived happenings that are at once rigorous and chaotic, idiotic and brilliant.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: The earnestness of some of the drama in the only deceptively unsophisticated narrative may be more shocking than any of the gross-outs.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: Not since Andy Kaufman's reign of terror has a supposed funnyman been so self-indulgently persistent in testing a fan's patience.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: Formidably stupid.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: Exhaustingly manic but curiously unfunny movie.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: It feels manufactured to be suitable for mass consumption.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: Do not bring children to this movie unless you want them to have nightmares for weeks.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: In a sense, this is a horror film, worse than anything Andy Kaufman could dream up, in which Green tries to outgross himself.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: Green, who looks like a chinless, hollow-eyed pederast at the best of times, is simply out of his league here, and the fact that the film drags interminably when it's actually a very average 90 minutes long betrays its essential emptiness.

title: Freddy Got Fingered
review: This movie doesn't scrape the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't below the bottom of the barrel. This movie doesn't deserve to be mentioned in the same sentence with barrels.

title: Baise-moi
review: A small revolution tucked inside clichés and willful artistic ineptitude.

title: Baise-moi
review: Seeks to shock and to outrage, and so far it's done both quite nicely.

title: Baise-moi
review: Certainly blunt, and since Anderson and Bach are veterans of the porn trade, there is no skimping on the sex.

title: Baise-moi
review: Strictly for adventurous moviegoers, a peculiar experience -- a polemic that is at once watchable and repellent.

title: Baise-moi
review: Fast-moving shocker, but it's a dull shocker, so morally dead that it deadens you to watch it. After a while you couldn't care less if anyone is slaughtered or raped -- including the heroines.

title: Baise-moi
review: As has happened before in less extreme circumstances, filmmakers with purportedly serious intentions punish their viewers for watching their envelope-pushing depiction of sex on the screen by presenting it in the most profoundly negative context imaginable.

title: Baise-moi
review: The filmmakers have separated themselves from all the emotions of filmmaking except anger.

title: Baise-moi
review: Didactic, clumsily directed and abysmally acted, never lets go of its intellectualized approach long enough to deliver any real kinetic thrills.

title: Baise-moi
review: This hard-core pic is a half-baked, punk-inflected porn odyssey masquerading as a movie worth seeing and talking about.

title: Baise-moi
review: It's pornography of the most depressing sort.

title: Taxi
review: A surprisingly funny, female-driven romp — as long as you don't question too many plot particulars.

title: Taxi
review: Very little of it works.

title: Taxi
review: Throughout this Americanization of the Luc Besson–scripted French hit, Latifah itches to check her watch, Fallon appears mortified, and only Ann-Margret mainlines any comic adrenalin.

title: Taxi
review: A bland, half-finished film that seems to have been conceived as off-peak cable fodder.

title: Taxi
review: Queen Latifah is a natural-born charmer, but there's only so much she can do when paired with a costar so irritating it's hard not to squirm when he's on the screen, which is most of the time.

title: Taxi
review: This thoroughly repetitive, ill-conceived and poorly executed effort -- with an emphasis on the word "effort" -- defeats these two talented people more often than not.

title: Taxi
review: Commits any number of comedic violations during an aimless pursuit of laughs.

title: Taxi
review: Bad as he is, Fallon cannot claim Taxi's worst moment. That belongs to Ann-Margret.

title: Taxi
review: Taxi's only saving grace is an inexplicable, though delightful, turn by Ann-Margret as Andy's ever-tipsy mom. She's a stitch, and about 100 times better than her surrounding material.

title: Taxi
review: This witless action comedy begins to insult the audience's intelligence from the opening scene.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Muniz is quite winning as a plucky teen who is constantly being thrown into situations over his head. But the usually reliable Anthony Anderson e-mails in his performance as Cody's handler.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Kids should be reasonably diverted for a couple of hours, but odds are they'll have forgotten the whole thing by the next morning.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Try as it might, this glossy action adventure isn't nearly as clever as the "Spy Kids" franchise.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Stretching what was a cute concept to the breaking point.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: At bottom, there's just too much spy in young Cody, and too little kid. The writers might've taken (another) page from the ''Spy Kids'' playbook and infused the action with youth relevance.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Given the great premise and characters inherited from the first film, it's surprising that this sequel fails to match its predecessor's appeal. The humor is silly, broad, and surprisingly generic.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Muniz has a great face and body for physical comedy, but the numerous one-liners shoehorned into the script fall flat, unassisted by Anderson's numbing “street” ad-libs.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: It's a movie, and certain liberties are bound to be taken, but having Derek stop a moped-driving Brit on the street by pulling out some sort of identification and yelling, "CIA, I need your moped!" is not the way.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: In terms of inspiration or even the slightest shred of ingenuity, Banks ranks more like an 000 than an 007.

title: Agent Cody Banks 2: Destination London
review: Mr. Allen's work is compromised by an apparent inability to match his shots in a spatially coherent fashion. It's never easy to tell who is chasing whom and in which direction, a needless confusion that dampens many of the thrills and scuttles quite a few gags.

title: Soul Plane
review: A lot better than one would expect. It's amusing, it's inspired and hey, it's a lot wittier than the last two "Scary Movies" combined. Though, like most lampoons, it runs out of steam about half way through.

title: Soul Plane
review: An idea whose time is long overdue, a tricked-out jumbo jet custom fit to meet the needs of today's savvy black traveler.

title: Soul Plane
review: A raunchy spoof of the disaster-movie lampoon Airplane! - does everything to get the laugh. And in the way that a broken watch is right twice a day, a shotgun comedy like this one occasionally hits its target.

title: Soul Plane
review: Has moments of inspiration, but the scattershot spoofing never achieves enough momentum to get this flight airborne.

title: Soul Plane
review: If you're looking for comic insights beyond the well-documented ass differential between whites and blacks, well, golly, you ought to try another carrier.

title: Soul Plane
review: Flashy production design can't save Soul Plane from crashing and burning in a debris field strewn with stereotypes and raunch.

title: Soul Plane
review: With its excessive sleaze and gross-out gags, Soul Plane overshoots effective spoofery. Mostly it's a foul, eye-rolling experience.

title: Soul Plane
review: While this flight should have been permanently delayed due to extraordinarily offensive conditions, there are no signs instructing you to remain seated should you decide to discreetly exit before your tour of the unfriendly skies is over.

title: Soul Plane
review: An hour and a half of real airplane turbulence is better than sitting through the bad, offensive material that makes up Soul Plane.

title: Soul Plane
review: Let's make this simple: If you spend money on Soul Plane, you've been played.

title: Superhero Movie
review: Undiscriminating comedy fans hungering for the High School High of superhero parodies need look no further.

title: Superhero Movie
review: Given the abysmal quality of recent spoof pics, it's saying something that Superhero Movie provides a fairly steady stream of midsized laughs -- and even the 40% or so of gags that just lie there aren't actively painful.

title: Superhero Movie
review: How can you tell the target age for Superhero Movie is exactly 13 1/2 years? Because most of the jokes are Internet-related.

title: Superhero Movie
review: The very act of writing critically about Superhero Movie inspires something of an existential crisis -- no one likely to turn out for it is reading this review, and anybody reading this review is probably not inclined to see it under any circumstances.

title: Superhero Movie
review: By-the-numbers screen parody fails to resurrect an increasingly tired genre.

title: Superhero Movie
review: The gags are consistently weak, though actor Miles Fisher turns in a hair-raising impression of Tom Cruise.

title: Superhero Movie
review: What's shocking about Superhero Movie is not that it's been advertised to death on Nickelodeon to impressionable children, but that it's a completely on-the-nose satire of "Spider-Man.”

title: Superhero Movie
review: Predictable, flat, full of name-dropping, tragically unhip, and likely to make a decent amount of cash.

title: Superhero Movie
review: No real mockery is intended by this harmless, mindless grab bag of slightly used gags, which lampoons some of the conventions of recent comic-book epics and adds the expected staples of juvenile humor: urine, vomit and intestinal gas.

title: Superhero Movie
review: This abysmal "Spider-Man" satire has more in common with the lamentable spate of "Epic" and "Date Movies" than Zucker and Nielsen's truly funny "Naked Gun" series.

title: Postal
review: It's such an insanely fun ride that most of its flaws are forgivable.

title: Postal
review: A provocation first, an insult second, a publicity stunt third, and a film a distant fourth.

title: Postal
review: This anything-goes exercise isn't dull -- one just wishes the outrageousness were more consistently funny.

title: Postal
review: Postal's touches of wit are lost in the flying body parts, gross-out gags, and the full frontal spectacle of Foley's no-longer-private parts.

title: Postal
review: What Boll gives us is a boring beating over the head.

title: Postal
review: At last: Uwe Boll has made his first intentionally funny film.

title: Postal
review: Manages to be as toothless as he (Boll) is tasteless. Poorly framed, tone-deaf, and nonsensical (yet still Boll's best!).

title: Postal
review: Infantile, irreverent and boorish to the max, Postal explodes with bad attitude and lousy filmmaking.

title: Postal
review: Boll's rampant narcissistic showmanship creates such a bizarre, garish spectacle that it is almost tempting to give him credit for being something of a misunderstood artist after all. Almost, but not quite.

title: Postal
review: Where Boll's movies were once amusingly atrocious, Postal is so aggressively tasteless and knowingly idiotic, there's just no fun to be had.

title: Rings
review: Rings finds a couple of nice, if inconsequential, little chills.

title: Rings
review: At no point does the movie manage even a single sequence of sustained tension, or a frisson of genuine terror.

title: Rings
review: Rings is unsure as to whether it’s a sequel to the other entries in the series or a contemporary reboot.

title: Rings
review: Horror films that backstory the audience to death lose all hope of mining what’s eerie and unsettling about the unknown, and Rings is a perfect example: it doesn’t so much spread its familiar myth as dilute it.

title: Rings
review: Rings is too beholden with current trends to truly exploit the potential it displays in its early going.

title: Rings
review: More wearying than frightening, Rings is a total non-starter.

title: Rings
review: The movie, which will be lucky to eke out a weekend’s worth of business, isn’t scary, it isn’t awesome, and it doesn’t nudge you to think of technology in a new way. But it does make you wish that you could rewind those two hours, or maybe just erase them.

title: Rings
review: Filmmaker F. Javier Gutiérrez really doesn't have a lot to work with beyond a flimsy story, weak script and characters you'll have a hard time caring about.

title: Rings
review: Imagine simultaneously eating wallpaper paste, listening to Coldplay and watching the entire ‘Da Vinci Code’ trilogy back to back and you’ll have some idea how grindingly tedious the experience of watching Rings becomes.

title: Rings
review: Rings never solidifies into one of kind movie, cramming a handful of possibilities into its bloated running time.

title: Ouija
review: It’s endearing how this glorified haunted-house movie tries to reclaim all the old tools, and do so with a straight face and a PG-13 level of violence.

title: Ouija
review: Given its double burden of being both a toy adaptation and a bloodless kiddie horror show, Ouija winds up being more fun that you might think, even if it's the sort of film you can't really take seriously for a second.

title: Ouija
review: This silly but straight-faced supernatural thriller manages to elicit an occasional shudder in between cheap jolts and false scares, emerging as a feat of competent direction (by debuting helmer Stiles White) over derivative scripting (by White and writing partner Juliet Snowden).

title: Ouija
review: The film is effectively scary, filled with plenty of jump moments and a few slow-burning scenes, but the scares aren’t enough to balance the poor writing and lack of imagination.

title: Ouija
review: Cooke, a young Brit seen on TV’s “Bates Motel,” is strong as the diminutive brunette at the center of the interworldly fright-fest. Her charisma is almost enough to keep you from rolling your eyes at the script.

title: Ouija
review: The most pressing issue with Ouija is that Stiles and Snowden cannot seem to write a single interesting line of dialogue. They volley between conversational banalities and whatever exposition might be needed to get the film to its next scary setpiece.

title: Ouija
review: Directed by Stiles White, whose credits lean more heavily in the special-effect arenas, Ouija is bland, safe horror for those who like their scares nonexistent.

title: Ouija
review: In the absence of anything truly original in the screenplay he co-wrote with Juliet Snowden, director Stiles White vainly attempts to ratchet up the tension with a series of cheap jump scares fueled by loud noises that are the cinematic equivalent of shaking hands with someone wearing a joy buzzer.

title: Ouija
review: Ouija has something wrong with it from the first five minutes.

title: Ouija
review: A deadly dull and overly familiar movie about summoning ghosts that draws upon nearly every horror movie cliché.

title: Bitch Slap
review: Despite its obsession with décolletage, Bitch Slap is surprisingly puritanical (much teasing, no pleasing), substituting plentiful violence and a howlingly predictable "shock" ending for the payoff it promises.

title: Bitch Slap
review: Overblown and underwhelming, Bitch Slap is a desperately unfunny attempt to satirically recycle cliches and archetypes from sexploitation actioners of the 1960s and '70s within the time-trippy, multiple-flashback framework of a Quentin Tarantino. extravaganza.

title: Bitch Slap
review: Over-the-top -- and ultimately tiresome -- female mud-wrestling, kick-boxing and cat fights in a parody of old exploitation movies.

title: Bitch Slap
review: In keeping with the film’s giddy superficiality, what’s revealed is a series of sexy poses passed off as character depth. All the backstabbing, shifting alliances and dark motives are held together by adolescent, innuendo-laden dialogue and thick Sapphic overtones.

title: Bitch Slap
review: Bitch Slap is garbage. It's self-aware garbage - garbage that explores and celebrates, in postmodern fashion, precisely what it means to be garbage. But that doesn't make it stink any less.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: A frenetic but undeniably funny follow-up that offers twice the number of singing-and-dancing rodents in another seamless blend of CGI and live-action elements.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: It seems as if no professional actors were hired in the making of this motion picture.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: Closing out a pretty great year for children's movies—Betty Thomas's dutiful animated and live-action sequel to 2007's "Alvin and the Chipmunks" brings up the rear with capable mediocrity.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: Smarter than its predecessor, the movie aims for the "High School Musical" market.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: As shrill, partly-animated musicals about singing vermin go, Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel really isn't all that bad.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: If only for the sake of adults, couldn't the folks behind the Alvin films have had the good grace to turn Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel into a musical?

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: Alvin does high school rom-com and very poorly at that.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: Charmless sequel.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: Almost but not quite as obnoxious as its title. Little kids will love it. You’ll need a hazmat suit.

title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
review: The Squeakquel might be appreciated by filmgoers aged 10 or younger.

title: Death Note
review: What’s frustrating is that with better lead performers and a tighter script, Wingard could have made a great adaptation. Instead it settles when it should have soared.

title: Death Note
review: Whereas the more grounded scenes of Death Note anchor a startlingly bloody fantasy of power run amok, the scenes that fixate on super powers and code-busting seldom manage to rise above the realm of serviceable YA fiction.

title: Death Note
review: Perhaps stifled by the cultural and commercial clout of its source material (a multimedia juggernaut of books, movies, television shows and a stage musical), Death Note feels rushed and constricted.

title: Death Note
review: Rather than relying on amplifying typical genre conventions, Wingard methodically lays the foundation to set up this particular Death Note adaptation for a potential sequel, but the outcome is more deliberate than inspired.

title: Death Note
review: The whole thing feels like the pilot episode of a third-rate comic-book vigilante TV show.

title: Death Note
review: The movie never quite reckons with just how twisted a concept it’s peddling, and that’s easily the scariest thing about it.

title: Death Note
review: What Wingard has delivered is a fitfully entertaining, clearly compromised hybrid of action, horror and science-fiction.

title: Death Note
review: The only reason to take such a uniquely Japanese story and transplant it to Seattle is to explore how its thorny moral questions might inspire different answers in an American context, so for this retread to all but reduce America to its whiteness indicates an absence of context more than anything else. It’s the most glaring symptom of a film that utterly fails to investigate its premise.

title: Death Note
review: Wingard’s film is an incoherent mess of tones and styles, confused character motives, and murky narratives.

title: Death Note
review: The new horror-thriller is cheesy, asinine, convoluted and ludicrous. On the plus side, if your eyeballs need a vigorous workout, this will have them rolling nonstop.

title: Snatched
review: It’s got enough laughs to get by.

title: Snatched
review: Schumer and Hawn know what funny looks and sounds like, and they lend their dialogue and gags — no matter how tepid — enough snap and personality to distract you, at least some of the time, from the utter laziness of the material.

title: Snatched
review: Often amusing but rarely shifting into a higher comedic gear, Snatched features fun chemistry between co-stars Amy Schumer and Goldie Hawn, some delightfully goofy moments of stray hilarity, yet not enough story or heart to keep this thin tale afloat.

title: Snatched
review: As Snatched’s blonde-leading-the-blonde farce careens on, it stumbles into moments of deranged inspiration.

title: Snatched
review: Though this movie ostensibly celebrates the spirit of adventure and openness to experience, it takes no risks and blazes no trails. It’s ultimately as complacent, self-absorbed and clueless as its heroine, and not always in an especially amusing way.

title: Snatched
review: The movie’s mother-daughter jokes are like firecrackers with damp fuses.

title: Snatched
review: What we’ve gotten in Snatched is an uninspired, scattershot disaster romp that mostly serves the talents of one half of the marquee pairing, underuses the other half, and struggles to blend R-rated humor, foreign misadventure, and oil-and-water mother-daughter dynamic into a cohesive diversion.

title: Snatched
review: The noxious self-absorption of straight white women that Schumer has sent up so blisteringly on her Comedy Central show is extolled more than it is lampooned.

title: Snatched
review: Too much of the humour derives from Emily’s insatiable appetite for booze, food and sex, while the central mother-daughter relationship is predictable.

title: Snatched
review: Pairing up talented comedians like Hawn and Schumer with a wacky plotline to match should spell comedy gold, but Snatched is about as cheap and disposable as a tourist trap tchotchke.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: Finally, the Fifty Shades phenomenon has yielded a disarming comedy that makes this ridiculous material fun to watch.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: It’s hard to find compliments for Jamie Dornan beyond “very athletic”—but from start to finish, one can’t give Johnson enough credit for making these asinine movies work as well as they do.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: It’s clichéd, stodgy and overly faithful to the original books.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: In terms of drama, or melodrama, or just bad drama, Freed rarely delivers the goods while trying hard to give fans what they came for.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: Departing only incidentally from E.L. James’s trashy tome, and making up for any short cuts with extra set dressing, this is brochure cinema of the most profuse order, selling its audience more on a lifestyle than on any of the lives inside it.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: At least this time, some of the laughs are intentional.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: Ostensibly aimed at an adult audience that craves equal parts romance and raunch, Fifty Shades Freed appears to have been written by a teenager – and not just because of its groan- and giggle-inducing dialogue, lack of emotional investment and thinly drawn characters. There’s no knowledge of any element of how the world functions, particularly in its approach to relationships.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: While we can quibble about the underused lead or the meandering plot, Fifty Shades Freed ultimately authors its own most stinging rebuke, closing on an extended montage highlighting major moments and turning points from the trilogy. Tellingly, none of them come from this film.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: This is a film in which one of the more emotionally detailed performances is given by a product-placement Audi.

title: Fifty Shades Freed
review: As usual it’s left entirely up to the beleaguered Johnson to make any of it even remotely watchable. She remains a compelling presence, trying her darnedest with lifeless words, but, again, she’s stranded by the energy-sucking vortex of nothingness that is Jamie Dornan. He’s better than this...but he knows it and his boredom is lazily apparent throughout.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Howard the Duck manages to be two or three types of fun: as a crazy comedy, it has some good risque/sick jokes to go along with its messy slapstick and bland rock music; as a monster movie, it has an outstanding performance from Jeffrey Jones as a scientist-cum-monster and an astonishingly repulsive Dark Overlord of the Universe shows up for the exciting climax.

title: Howard the Duck
review: There's something kitschy about Howard the Duck that makes it fun to watch. It tried hard and provided you're not a huge stick in the mud, there's something in this movie for everyone.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Howard the Duck' begins as a mild satire about a duck who fell to earth, but midway through, the star is upstaged by horrifying demons and dazzling light shows.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Pic lapses into formulaic predictability with nearly an hour of frenetic chase scenes and technically perfect explosions from Industrial Light & Magic. Action comes sporadically alive in scenes with scientist Jones, who becomes possessed by the spirit of an evil Dark Warlord that entered his body during the same fateful mishap that brought Howard to Earth. There is an abundant amount of special effects wizardry that emanates mostly from Jones as he transforms into a monster, but it is not spectacularly unique enough to distinguish this film from other, more entertaining, sci-fi thrillers.

title: Howard the Duck
review: The film resembles one of those Saturday Night Live sketches that has one joke and keeps going, and going, and going.

title: Howard the Duck
review: The problem was that it was supposed to be animated, but contractual obligations forced it to become a live-action movie — specifically, an unfunny, effects-driven, story-deprived live-action film about a talking duck.

title: Howard the Duck
review: There are a couple of mildly amusing moments, but overall Howard the Duck is a monumental waste of time.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Howard The Duck has several jokes, really, they're all just desperately unfunny.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Howard the Duck, the movie, is as bad as you've heard. Actually, it's worse. But its failings as a film have overshadowed the frequently brilliant 1970s comic book that inspired it. Using only the most superficial elements of its source material while discarding most of what made the comic interesting, the film serves as a textbook example of how to turn something into nothing.

title: Howard the Duck
review: Howard T Duck, of Marvel Comics, might well have a beef against Lucasfilm for transforming his magnetic comic strip personality into a zipperless polyester duck-suit (filled interchangeably by eight different actors, each apparently under four feet in height) in this aimless movie.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: For what it's worth (very little), probably the best in the series.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: Jensen Daggett is a standout as the troubled young girl on whom Jason is fixated. V.C. Dupree has vibrant energy in his boxing scenes, Sharlene Martin has a fine time with the bitch role, and Martin Cummins is funny as a video freak who compulsively films the proceedings.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: It seems that as long as Jason can keep his costs down-by hiring unknown young actors, desperate for any kind of a break, and hiring directors (Rob Hedden this time) straight out of television or film school-he`ll be with us forever. Conveniently devoid of any personality (a variety of anonymous stunt men have filled the role over the years), he`s as infinitely reproducible as one of Warhol`s soup cans, though considerably less expressive. [31 July 1989, p.C3]

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: To crystallize its fundamental flaw, here's a movie about Manhattan that takes 75 minutes just to get to Manhattan - followed by another 15 that could just as easily have been shot (and possibly were) in some East Topeka alley. [31 July 1989, p.4D]

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: During all of this tediously staged action, the virginal female heroine, Rennie Wickham (Jensen Daggett), suffers hallucinations about the young Jason. Not surprisingly, these scenes — which feel as if they belong in another movie — are among the most effective in the film, a welcome distraction from the mundane mechanics of the rest of this predictable effort.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: But (Jason) will never change and never die, not while cheap, dull ax-murder movies can yield one witty, misleading, probably lucrative commercial.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: Funny ad campaign; a real dunghill of a major motion picture.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: Also zero, which is the amount of inspiration and achievement in this continuing saga of the little boy who drowned in Crystal Lake 30 years, seven films and approximately 286 teenagers ago (30-7-286)

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: I'll maim, chop, slash, and I'll kill, Just as I please.

title: Friday the 13th Part VIII: Jason Takes Manhattan
review: Putting this hackneyed villain in The Big Apple is a tantalizing concept, but Hedden rarely takes advantage of it. He deserves credit for a few shocks and some laughs from a gloom- and-doom deck swabber, but this is highly derivative stuff. And like many slash directors, he replaces suspense with short chases and violence. If audience response is a meter, Jason VIII is a dud. Save a few shrieks, the crowd fell victim to boredom. [31 July 1989, p.C5]

title: Junior
review: A lot of actors can hold big machineguns and stand convincingly in front of special effects and explosions. Not many can stand in front of a camera and be nine months pregnant, and actually make us care.

title: Junior
review: A fleecy romantic caper with a dusting of feminism, the picture is basically a one-joke movie successfully nursed by director Ivan Reitman.

title: Junior
review: Neither hilarious nor horrible, Junior is the first would-be Arnold blockbuster that coasts on charm.

title: Junior
review: A daft movie, but one not without its moments of healthy radiance, spurred on by some bristling gags and a welcome comic return by Emma Thompson as a gauche fellow doctor caught in a romantic sub-plot.

title: Junior
review: Proceeds efficiently but never quite lives up to its own potential as a sight gag.

title: Junior
review: Junior is passable entertainment, but it could hardly be called fully developed.

title: Junior
review: Schwarzenegger’s willingness to flirt with femininity, to become truly radiant, is the most engaging aspect of Junior. Unfortunately, the script doesn’t portray his transformation to starry-eyed pregnant bliss with much comic ingenuity.

title: Junior
review: As a comedy, Junior has its share of laughs -- but no more than its share.

title: Junior
review: Let’s just say that, for the right audience, Junior may deliver. But there’s a whole lot of pregnancy to go through first.

title: Junior
review: The new Ivan Reitman/Arnold Schwarzenegger comedy is a one-joke affair, and it takes surprisingly little time for the potential humor in the situation to wear thin.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: Never quite as witty as it should be.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: A fairly silly and ultra-gory schlocker/shocker.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: It lacks humor. Unlike "Scream", this film is more of a horror-drama, with everybody taking themselves way too seriously.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: There's gore aplenty here, but precious little suspense or terror.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: More in the dumb and dumber tradition of "Halloween" and "Friday the 13th" sequels.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: Assembles the building blocks of idiot-proof slasher movies: Stings, Snicker-Snacks, false alarms and point-of-view baits-and-switches.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: If there's a blessing, it's that the sequel isn't appreciably worse than the original - but that's slim praise considering how bad the first one was.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: It's standard slasher fare but has its moments.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: The best that can be said about this film is that it's watchable, and that's not the way it could or should be.

title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
review: You want REAL terror? If this second outing proves profitable, we'll be looking at Yet Again I Recall the Summer Before the Summer Before Last. Now that's scary.

title: Driven
review: The movie is so filled with action that dramatic conflict would be more than we could handle, so all of the characters are nice.

title: Driven
review: Even if his (Stallone) own star may be fading, the popularity of car racing is enormous. These fans are not likely to be disappointed by Driven.

title: Driven
review: Driven is in both its script and its execution a paint-by-numbers affair.

title: Driven
review: Driven is recommended only to those gentle souls who want to know what it looks like to crash into a wall at 200 mph.

title: Driven
review: Stallone's script is well structured, though the jaw-droppingly banal dialogue gives us little reason to care.

title: Driven
review: It's outrageously stereotypical and weirdly personal, so loonily exaggerated it keeps surprising you.

title: Driven
review: Even fans of open-wheel racing, the high-speed, high-stress pastime that is the subject of Renny Harlin's hectic new film, may walk away from it more logy than exhilarated.

title: Driven
review: What we have here is a film where the first 20 minutes are repeated again and again until everything comes to an absolutely predictable end.

title: Driven
review: It's not quite as bad as "Cutthroat Island," I'll grant you, but it's woefully close.

title: Driven
review: An appallingly dull film set in the world of professional racing, director Renny Harlin and screenwriter Sylvester Stallone have found a way to drain all the adrenaline out of the sport.

title: Psycho
review: Norman Bates is alive and well, and just a tad kinkier than you remember him.

title: Psycho
review: William H. Macy is fine as the detective Arbogast, wearing a hat he could have borrowed from Martin Balsam in the original role.

title: Psycho
review: Cold, dull, lifeless. [5 December 1998, p.3]

title: Psycho
review: Untantalizingly reverent remake. [7 December 1998, p.4D]

title: Psycho
review: A faithful-unto-slavish remake of the 1960 Hitchcock classic, pic contains nothing to outrage or offend partisans of the original, yet neither does it stand to add much to their appreciation.

title: Psycho
review: The movie doesn't stink. The performances are good, potentially great, especially Vince Vaughn as Norman Bates.

title: Psycho
review: In the shock department, the ante has been upped, way up, and a mere kitchen knife through a shower curtain just doesn't cut it any more.

title: Psycho
review: Van Sant's film feels as dated as Hitchcock's, and Hitchcock's has the better excuse.

title: Psycho
review: The movie is an invaluable experiment in the theory of cinema, because it demonstrates that a shot-by-shot remake is pointless; genius apparently resides between or beneath the shots, or in chemistry that cannot be timed or counted.

title: Psycho
review: Redundant and unnecessary.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: At a time when crassness and dumbing down pervade popular entertainment, especially movies aimed at youthful audiences, Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen dares to be smart.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Only Carol Kane, hilarious in roller curls and wide tortoiseshell glasses, gets to sink her teeth into her role. At least for Lohan, "Confessions" is her stepping-off point. Now she has to find a film to be her "real" stage.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: A pretty little package whose perfect, fairy-tale ending is just a little too neat, the film's colorful wrapping includes veteran actress Carol Kane's bizarre but enjoyable performance as the school's uptight drama teacher.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Girls ages 6-14 will get a charge from the fashion show, animation effects and, to a lesser degree, the cartoonish antics. But like most adolescent histrionics, the pic's impact on adults will be limited to mild amusement alternating with annoyance.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Modest, mildly engaging film.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: A safely sanitized comedy with an important message about loyalty and individuality, plays to Lohan's strengths and gives the target audience a chance to live it up vicariously.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Tethered to screenwriter Gail Parent's adaptation of Dyan Sheldon's novel, plus the demands of bigwig producers, it's a testament to Sugarman's artistry that she sustains her funky playfulness--a hallmark of her earlier work--throughout most of this film.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Welsh director Sara Sugarman and the great cinematographer Stephen Burum (Hoffa, The Untouchables) keep the visuals bouncing along in bright, primary-color-intensive fashion, but the movie has no real heart and even less soul.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: It's a silly, giggly piece of pink-colored fluff, as hyperactive as its heroine and as redolent of bubble gum and Love's Baby Soft cologne as Lola apparently is. Yet the superficial sweetness masks something rotten.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
review: Shlocky, sloppy and crass adolescent comedy.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: Sufficient cheap thrills and enough of the prevailing camp quality.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: Sublimely trashy, this conceptual sequel to 1997's surprise hit, "Anaconda," doesn't expect to be taken any more seriously than its schlock predecessor, and keeps its tongue-in-cheek thrills flowing rapidly.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: To be fair, it's little better or worse than the original. But, to be honest, the original--minus its nascent stars--wasn't very good.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: From its jungle forays to its waterfall tumbles to its deadly spider bites - is entirely, utterly unoriginal.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: Supremely silly but undeniably fun sequel.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: A programmer that once upon a time would have played on the bottom half of double bills, Anacondas has no pretensions and gets its little job done effectively, providing some small-scale laughs and chills for the late summer season.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: Director Dwight Little, who has made many mediocre films as well as the gleefully gory Robert Englund version of "The Phantom of the Opera," gets at least one thing right -- he really does take time to establish the characters.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: There's no enjoyably outlandish hiss to this variation on the formula, and no Ice Cube or Owen Wilson, either. This time, a ship of capitalist fools (and no movie stars, unless you count utility player Morris Chestnut as a headliner) steams along the river in Borneo.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: What they don't do often enough is battle anacondas. It's all tease and no payoff.

title: Anacondas: The Hunt for the Blood Orchid
review: This movie didn't have to be good, but that it's so boring in its badness is tough to swallow.

title: Black Christmas
review: The flashbacks are wittily gothic, and the present-day murder scenes have the absurdist, chain-reaction intricacy of the "Final Destination" deaths.

title: Black Christmas
review: This film is an evocative, effective entry into the holiday blood-spray subgenre in its own right. And if it doesn't make your skin crawl ... you probably ate too much Christmas dinner.

title: Black Christmas
review: Silly, obvious, clumsy, and just gruesome enough to keep jaded genre fans from angrily throwing popcorn at the screen.

title: Black Christmas
review: Like an ugly tie or a pair of slipper socks, Black Christmas is destined to be forgotten the instant it's unwrapped, gathering dust until the season rolls around again.

title: Black Christmas
review: There are a couple clever touches here and there, including one sequence in which the end of a candy cane has been carefully licked into a highly lethal weapon, but for the most part the accompanying histrionics feel more regressive than retro.

title: Black Christmas
review: Lazy, perfunctory and free of tension, the new version will satisfy neither the admirers of the original nor anyone looking for a gory respite from seasonal good cheer.

title: Black Christmas
review: Bad film fans will think Christmas has come early, everyone else should ask for the receipt.

title: Black Christmas
review: With a peephole-riddled set and a flashback-heavy screenplay, Black Christmas smothers terror beneath a blanket of unnecessary information, revealing too much and teasing too little.

title: Black Christmas
review: It's debatable whether the original 1974 "Black Christmas" is, as its most rabid fans claim, the mother of all slasher movies. But there can be no argument regarding the scant merits of its slapdash, soporifically routine remake, suitable only for the least discriminating of gore hounds.

title: Black Christmas
review: The remake neither pays perceptive tribute to the original nor updates it in anything but hackneyed form.

title: Yogi Bear
review: There's nothing particularly inventive in the plot or grade-school humor, but the movie skates by on the timeless, undemanding charm of watching a tie-wearing bear try to steal people's lunches.

title: Yogi Bear
review: Adults will be thrilled to see Anna Faris as nature documentarian Rachel. Greeting Yogi by speaking in "brown bear," the actress never fails to be seriously goofy.

title: Yogi Bear
review: On the whole the film is not much fun to watch. A job is a job, though; Yogi Bear did little to make it more than that.

title: Yogi Bear
review: Yogi is still smarter than the average bear, but Yogi Bear is much less smart than most of the year's kid-friendly cartoons.

title: Yogi Bear
review: A bland and innocuous small-fry outing that retains a measure of the original Hanna-Barbera cartoon's charm, though scarcely enough to justify the time, expense and visual-effects trickery it must have taken to inflate an endearing 2D cartoon into a dopey 3D extravaganza.

title: Yogi Bear
review: A smarter-than-average bear becomes a dumber-than-usual kiddie flick with Yogi Bear, the lone Christmas release specifically aimed at children, so it automatically qualifies as their lump of coal.

title: Yogi Bear
review: The best you can say about this Yogi Bear is that he's harmless. No animal was harmed in the making of this picture except the one Hanna-Barbera made a bundle on almost 50 years ago.

title: Yogi Bear
review: Yogi Bear gives cheap hackwork a bad name. Which is a shame, because hackwork made this industry.

title: Yogi Bear
review: Even the presence of Dan Aykroyd as Yogi and Justin Timberlake as his pint-sized straight man Boo Boo, couldn't save the movie.

title: Yogi Bear
review: Yogi Bear on the big screen feels not just needless, but wasteful.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: The film is heavily reliant on jump scares, but its best moments are the ones before them, when the tension builds without the benefit of escalating music to queue you in to the approaching shock.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: Aside from the usual self-slamming doors and flying bodies, there are enough creepy kids and hiding knives to distract from a plot that's increasingly mobile yet running on the spot.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: Paranormal Activity 4 may mean more of the same, but in a modern horror landscape too often made up of equal parts of gore and boredom and resigned straight-to-video, it's a chiller designed to be seen in a crowded theater, and that alone makes it superior to its peers.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: Catfish pair Joost and Ariel Schulman keep the franchise firmly on track with a satisfyingly scary fourth instalment.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: This film's strong suit is that it finally feels contemporary.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: PA4 develops the story ever so slightly (not enough to satisfy fans) and delivers a few good scares (not enough to satisfy newbies); mostly, it plays like a overlong prologue for the already-in-the-works PA5. Here's hoping this is just the tension-racking lull before the next big scream.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: Fairly mild in tone and riffing -- if not quite ripping -- off a collection of horror classics that includes "The Shining," "Rosemary's Baby" and "Poltergeist," both the franchise's premise and its execution nevertheless remain rudimentary, with the narrative and character backstories representing more of a sketch than a fully realized vision of the supernatural world that Katie inhabits.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: Less reliant on slow-burn suspense and larded with fake-out jump scares, this is the first sequel in the series that fails to advance the overall mythology in any meaningful way.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: There's a point at which movies become only merchandise, and the Paranormal franchise may be heading for that nexus, that nadir.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
review: PA 4's best idea, besides reintroducing the slow-walking, statuesque Katie, is a strange video trick involving lots of little lights filling a darkened room. It's tough to describe, but the cameras, of course, capture a figure the characters can't.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: The Ghost Dimension isn’t exactly frightening — the setup is so well-worn now that it’s hard to be particularly startled by what transpires — but it’s able to wring sufficient dread out of this franchise’s go-to fears.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: To the bitter end, the series manages to wring some fun, solid scares out of something other invading something utterly familiar.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: By making it so that everyone can see the evil coming, it also robs the franchise of one of its most potent pleasures: studying the frame for signs of trouble, little telltale hints that something is about to go horribly, horribly wrong. Sentient inkblots are a poor substitution for that sensation.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: At its most basic level, the Paranormal Activity formula still has some kick, with its combination of creepy lo-fi video and tasteful suburbia creating some strong, unsettling dissonance.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: If only Ghost Dimension spent more time in the ghost dimension and less time in the people dimension, we might have had something.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: The Paranormal Activity movies have always been about carnival-ride sensations, the narrative through-line secondary. That’s fortunate, because those seeking closure to what continuity there has been will go home mostly disappointed.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: Even at this late stage in the evolution of the franchise, logical lapses in filmmaking technique undercut the integrity of the found-footage format.... What may be less acceptable, however, is the film’s unaccountably weak effort to sort out the mythology concerning the series of demonic hauntings.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: There may well be new and novel ways to spark audience shivers from not-so-bright homeowners inexplicably using their cameraphones to check out bumps in the night, but this series clearly has neither the patience nor the inclination to look for them anymore.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: It’s a test of one’s tolerance for watching predominantly empty frames – the anonymous performers scarcely count – in the hope something will jolt us from mounting tedium.

title: Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension
review: The sixth time is not the charm with this load of hooey that tries to make up for its lack of legitimate scares or basic narrative clarity by adding the alleged miracle of 3-D into the mix.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: For all its structural and psychological deficiencies, it’s hard not to enjoy Fifty Shades Darker on its own lusciously limited terms.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Whipping up a proper tone for the big screen versions of E.L. James’ wildly popular novels was always going to be the films’ biggest problem, and while director James Foley might not quite nail it, wily injections of humor prove to be an unexpectedly helpful addition to the kinky franchise.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Even with an improved Dornan, the movie still belongs to Johnson, a character actress capable of making light of a movie pretending to be darker.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: The last third of the film descends straight into a combination of "Dynasty" with shades of cult classic "The Room." It's fantastic because it's complete and utter silly madness. Helicopter crashes! Slaps! Drinks thrown in faces! Fully clothed shower sex! A framed "Chronicles of Riddick" poster! All the makings of an instant cult classic.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: It’s nice that the two photogenic leads are treating sex like a pleasurable activity rather than an onerous chore in this second entry, but overall, the film plays like an un-asked-for collaboration between the Hallmark and Playboy Channels.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Darker is strangely plotless and devoid of any real tension.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Sometimes sexy, sometimes campy, Fifty Shades Darker is a smorgasbord of silliness, its dopey pleasures indistinguishable from its many awkwardly melodramatic moments.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: A film which promises “darker” but delivers “funnier” — with some of the laughs intentional.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Pulseless, perfunctory and persistently watering down its kookier instincts, Fifty Shades Darker pales in comparison to the first. You might as well call it Fifty Shades Duller.

title: Fifty Shades Darker
review: Leonard and Foley offer enough semi-naked sex scenes here to prove that quantity is no substitute for chemistry.

title: Showgirls
review: What matters much more than the story or the Spicy Stuff is the dancing, the show-biz dancing. It's electric. Exciting. And there's lots of it. [23 Oct 1995]

title: Showgirls
review: As Nomi, Elizabeth Berkley has exactly two emotions -- hot and bothered -- but her party-doll blowsiness works for the picture.

title: Showgirls
review: If the plot and screenplay are juvenile, the production values are first-rate, and the lead performance by newcomer Elizabeth Berkley has a fierce energy that's always interesting.

title: Showgirls
review: The film's big lap-dance sequence is impressive, however, if only for the sheer athleticism of Elizabeth Berkley's contortion. Later, when she pulls the same stunt in a swimming pool, we recognize the show for what it is--a male fantasy film in which the women are little more than rag dolls. [22 Sept 1995]

title: Showgirls
review: To take Showgirls that seriously (as either trash-art or appalling pornography) wouldn't be worth the exertion.

title: Showgirls
review: After an onslaught of prerelease hype promising the erotic experience of a lifetime, Showgirls reveals itself as a 131-minute dose of cinematic saltpeter.

title: Showgirls
review: What's completely baffling is that everyone in the film thinks Nomi is one heck of a dancer, even though her one move -- throwing her arms out stiffly -- is straight out of "Dr. Strangelove."

title: Showgirls
review: The story is so shabbily built that it can make no valid claim to motives other than the filmmakers' mercenary desires to cash in on the public's prurient interests. And even on this bottom-feeder level, Showgirls fails to deliver the goods.

title: Showgirls
review: That Berkley cannot act is indisputable. But her dancing looks like a seizure.

title: Showgirls
review: Lacking the combustible Sharon Stone and Michael Douglas in leading roles, Showgirls descends into incoherent tedium. Though the filmmakers' incessant talk about vision, artistry and honest self-expression lead one to expect a sexually explicit biopic about the Dalai Lama, what is in fact provided is depressing and disappointing as well as dehumanizing.

title: Anaconda
review: A slick, scary, funny Creature Feature, beautifully photographed and splendidly acted in high adventure style.

title: Anaconda
review: An enjoyably cast, superbly shot, jolt-generating device...It isn't art, but it'll crush your bones.

title: Anaconda
review: Coil up with a tub of popcorn, get a stranglehold on your soda - this is a creepy, action-packed boat ride down a jungle river with lots of huge snakes dropping by for man-sized snacks.

title: Anaconda
review: Voight's performance -- one of the film's pure, trashy delights -- is all leer, sneer and macho swagger, while the rest of the actors feel like the disposable snake-fodder they are.

title: Anaconda
review: A silly and plodding "Jaws" rip-off about a 40-foot man-eating snake on the prowl in the Brazilian rain forest.

title: Anaconda
review: Feels like "Alien" as directed by Jim Henson. And the suspense is restricted to mundane slasher-movie tactics, including the frequent use of a mobile camera (call it the ’condacam) that’s supposed to represent the snake’s point of view.

title: Anaconda
review: Jon Voight, the all-purpose villain, does a pretty good job of imitating Marlon Brando imitating a Paraguayan snake expert, but the rest of the players--including Jennifer Lopez, Ice Cube, Eric Stoltz, Owen Wilson, Vincent Castellanos, Jonathan Hyde, and Kari Wuhrer--seem to be in a hurry to pick up their checks.

title: Anaconda
review: So desperate and silly that here and there, it's a lot of fun.

title: Anaconda
review: Charmless, unfrightening, and even devoid of the requisite gratuitous nudity, Anaconda just plain bites.

title: Anaconda
review: If only director Luis Llosa and his cast could see the joke and seize upon it; instead, like its computer-morphed snake, the film doesn't have a clever bone in its body.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Definitely merits its R rating with a fearless approach that will earn genuine laughs as it turns a few stomachs. Yes, a Rob Schneider movie that's funny. Strange but true.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: As before, there are moments, when Schneider is turned loose to do his anything-goes, creepy-funny shtick, that are crudely inspired.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: While sloppier than the sloppiest of seconds, is laudable in one important regard: Its obsession with the male body.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Every bit as vulgar, sophomoric and thoroughly tasteless as 1999's Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo. But what is most annoying is the sequel's capability of inducing laughter even as one hates oneself for so easily succumbing to the total silliness of it all.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Director Mike Bigelow maintains a mercifully swift pace, and while the film's humor is deliberately as crass as humanly possible, it is not truly mean-spirited, even though Amsterdam is depicted as a modern-day Sodom and Gomorrah.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Rude, crude and, uh, cosmopolitan, Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo waves the flag for R-rated politically incorrect studio comedy but doesn't top the laugh ratio of the first Deuce misadventure.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: It's not Deuce's satisfied clientele, but the audience, that gets the shaft.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: The director is first-timer Mike Bigelow. Nothing's paced or shaped for maximum payoff; the shooting and editing rhythms add only clutter and noise, and the slapstick is strictly of the skull-banging, ear-splitting variety.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Speaking in my official capacity as a Pulitzer Prize winner, Mr. Schneider, your movie sucks.

title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
review: Not that there are any actual jokes to be had. The film simply jumps to the punch lines, a non-stop barrage of crude dialogue and vulgar sight gags that passes as humor among adolescent boys. Who exactly is the audience for this R-rated film? The terminally immature?

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: It may not be classic sci-fi like the original “Alien,” which it has in its DNA, but it’s a perfectly respectable next step in the series.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: Provides enough cheap thrills and modest suspense to shake a few shekels from genre fans before really blasting off as homevid product.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: Chopped down to 40 minutes, this could be a wickedly cool short; as is, it’s a passable slasher that’s still nowhere near the interspecies smackdown we geeks have long imagined.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: A dull actioner that looks like a bad video game.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: Aliens vs. Predator -- Requiem simply exists, nodding to the continuity of the larger series and opening the door for, yes, another entry in the franchise. In Hollywood as in outer space, spawn begets spawn.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: The film's major draws are R-rated gore and some nice physical effects, proof that a man in a top-of-the-line monster suit can still be more effective than CGI.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: An orgy of mindless violence, a random collection of bloody bodies, alien misanthropy, and slobbering carnage designed to bore straight into the pleasure centers of 13-year-old boys and leave the rest of us wondering when the movies got so damn loud.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: --- Ho, ho, ho - the joke's on anyone who pays to see this.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: The problem with the "Alien vs. Predator" series is that the humans keep getting in the way.

title: AVPR: Aliens vs Predator - Requiem
review: A tasteless, witless, mindlessly perfunctory bloodbath that has the discourtesy to take itself seriously. Pitting aliens against predators may be the height of frivolity, but God forbid anyone have fun with it.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: These are standard youth-movie dilemmas, but they're brought to life by the high-energy cast and the musical numbers, which Ortega shoots with electrifying pizzazz.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: What it lacks in narrative ambition, it makes up for in dazzling choreography.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: For the most part, the film's musical numbers are dynamic, propelling the story forward. The same cannot be said about Peter Barsocchini's colorless screenplay.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: Exudes genuine appeal, thanks to director Kenny Ortega's brilliant choreography and a gifted cast.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: Even if the refreshing gust doesn't stay with you long, it's fun while it lasts.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: Efron is the epitome of sexless Disney heartthrobs, but he's an electrifying song-and-dance man, so much so that his castmates (Bleu excepted) look like they have concrete shoes by comparison.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: The result unfortunately has the blandness of a mediocre TV sitcom.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: While Ortega and fellow choreographers Charles Klapow and Bonnie Story stretch their imaginations, there's something almost lazy about the picture's underachiever script.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: Set against a production design seemingly inspired by the American flag, director Kenny Ortega's choreography is industrial and efficient, if haplessly stranded somewhere between Michael Jackson and the Village People.

title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
review: If you're gay and/or eight years old, HSM3 is the movie event of the year.

title: Jonah Hex
review: It's based on some DC Comics characters, which may explain the way the plot jumps around. We hear a lot about graphic novels, but this is more of a graphic anthology of strange occult ideas.

title: Jonah Hex
review: Brolin is so damned good in the saddle, in the hat and in the part that a half-sober viewer could half forget how half-arsed this movie he's starring in is.

title: Jonah Hex
review: The only thing sadder than Jonah Hex is what appears to have happened to his movie.

title: Jonah Hex
review: Jonah Hex isn't abrupt by design but by desperation.

title: Jonah Hex
review: It admittedly starts off great guns, but all too quickly it becomes apparent that the big-screen arrival of the supernatural Western DC Comics series Jonah Hex"is firing loud, empty blanks.

title: Jonah Hex
review: The film's noisy, slam-bang approach and lack of imagination in all nonvisual departments will keep it from rounding up a fresh generation of thrill-seekers.

title: Jonah Hex
review: A mercifully fleet and lamentably uninteresting adaptation of the DC Comic about a war-weary Confederate soldier.

title: Jonah Hex
review: Jonah Hex somehow manages to waste the talents of Josh Brolin, John Malkovich, Michael Fassbender, Will Arnett, Aidan Quinn and Jeffrey Dean Morgan in a story that combines vengeance, the occult and an Old West war on terror (really).

title: Jonah Hex
review: Jonah Hex tries to hedge its bets too much, and the result is a movie that probably won't please the few faithful with Jonah Hex bedsheets, nor fans of mindless summer action flicks.

title: Jonah Hex
review: Every once in a while, a film limps into theaters so stitched together, it's a wonder it doesn't rip apart in the projector. Jonah Hex is such a film.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Why does “New Moon” basically work, even with its grave self-seriousness? A few reasons. Weitz lets the material breathe, and his actors interact. The film does not try to eat you alive.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Carried by Kristen Stewart's compellingly dark performance, but also by helmer Chris Weitz's robust visuals.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: The werewolves have it all over the blood-suckers in The Twilight Saga: New Moon. When these oversize, hirsute creatures burst onto the screen, they inject life into a rather inert story.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Is this sequel defending its fan base and preempting criticism about its transparent agenda? This IS a soap opera, folks--and acceptable escapism for those old enough to see it yet still young enough to shriek at undead dreamboats.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Constrained by the plot of the novel, the film keeps the two lovers apart for quite a spell, robbing the project of the crazy-in-love energy that made "Twilight," the first entry in the series, such a guilty pleasure.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Weitz takes a looser approach than the series’ last director, Catherine Hardwicke, did. He has a better sense of humor, too.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Let's just say it: It's great there's a movie that makes teenage girls scream. Half the movies Hollywood makes are designed to make teenage boys scream, and those boy movies are just as ridiculous and a lot nastier than New Moon.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: Where the first film’s director, Catherine Hardwicke, plugged into Meyer’s vision of supernatural teenage lust with abandon, Chris Weitz is stuck with a sequel that’s a morning-after mope-fest.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: New Moon is supposed to be an exciting love story plus monster action. So where’s the excitement? Where’s the action?

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
review: The Twilight Saga: New Moon takes the tepid achievement of "Twilight" (1988), guts it, and leaves it for undead.

title: Zoolander 2
review: Mostly, Zoolander 2 hits the mark with style. Just don’t expect anything too deep.

title: Zoolander 2
review: There are always some laughs to be had here, and Ben Stiller’s couture legend now has an endearingly muppety look.

title: Zoolander 2
review: It’s fun to see Zoolander once more. It seems unlikely that the premise could ever sustain a third film, but if this is Derek’s swan song then he leaves amid a flurry of feathers and bustle – surely all a male model could wish for.

title: Zoolander 2
review: More Blue Steel than Magnum, this is a perfectly serviceable sequel, but dogged by repetition, it lacks the original's speed and sizzle.

title: Zoolander 2
review: Zoolander No. 2 is embarrassing, lazy, and aggressively unfunny. The only good news is that at the pace the franchise is moving, we won’t get Zoolander 3 until 2030.

title: Zoolander 2
review: Sure, it's a kick to see Stiller and Wilson back in the shoes of these camera-ready cretins, but for every joke that sparks there are several that just lay there.

title: Zoolander 2
review: The stakes are higher, the action is bigger, the ambitions are grander, the jokes are appreciably less funny. Like many comedy sequels, Zoolander 2 supersizes everything in such a way that it’s that much more apparent how few of the jokes are connecting.

title: Zoolander 2
review: A “high concept comedy” from the days when those were a thing, it’s basically a cacophony of cameos and random sight gags hurled at the viewer in a tsunami of haute couture hype.

title: Zoolander 2
review: There are no build-ups or pay-offs here, just a lot of random moments of people saying stupid stuff, and fashion people being gently lampooned.

title: Zoolander 2
review: The results may delight those who believe recycled gags and endless cameos to be the very essence of great screen comedy, but everyone else will likely recognize Stiller’s wannabe Magnum opus as a disappointment-slash-misfire, the orange mocha crappuccino of movie sequels.

title: Ra.One
review: Anubhav Sinha's exhilarating fantasy Ra.One is Bollywood at its best. It has energy, spectacle and humor, song and dance, but razzle-dazzle special effects and action stunts never overwhelm its story of enduring love that unfolds amid an intricate and inspired sci-fi odyssey.

title: Ra.One
review: This wildly entertaining Bollywood action-comedy, with Indian superstar Shahrukh Khan in two roles, pays homage to such '90s flicks as "Terminator 2: Judgment Day" and "The Matrix," adding whimsy and loads of heart.

title: Ra.One
review: If you're bored by the action scenes or the love story or the dopey domestic comedy, just wait three minutes for something else to come along - and whoever you are, you won't be bored by the musical numbers!

title: Ra.One
review: You don't have to be an enthusiast of Bollywood to embrace RA.ONE, but it sure would help.

title: Ra.One
review: If the storytelling disappoints (shocking!), the film mostly doesn't. It relies on action and effects and Bollywood's trump card, star power, to carry the day. This is Mr. Khan's movie, and once he sheds Shekhar's droopy locks, he shines as the deadpan, action-hero robot with digital snot and smooth moves on the dance floor.

title: Ra.One
review: Much of the film is marked by a sense of dead air, owing to the fact that there's not a lot of story, but nevertheless, per Bollywood conventions, a lot of time to fill.

title: Ra.One
review: And yes, the super effects are fantastic. But overall, Ra.One fails to impress.

title: Ra.One
review: But all the charm in the world wouldn't make Ra.One's sanctimoniousness seem any more genuine.

title: God's Not Dead
review: The film has entertaining moments, but these are clearly secondary to its proselytizing intentions.

title: God's Not Dead
review: The pace is stumbling, the characters are broad, the makeup and the performances uneven, though Sorbo dives into his tactless, unethical indoctrinator role with Satanic glee.

title: God's Not Dead
review: Even grading on a generous curve, this strident melodrama about the insidious efforts of America’s university system to silence true believers on campus is about as subtle as a stack of Bibles falling on your head.

title: God's Not Dead
review: Ban this sick filth.

title: God's Not Dead
review: Even by the rather lax standards of the Christian film industry, God’s Not Dead is a disaster.

title: God's Not Dead
review: Any just God would likely recoil from the ham-fisted and spurious defense put forth in this film.

title: Meet the Blacks
review: Meet the Blacks is an asinine film (though with a kernel of seriousness) but whenever it feels like it is running out of steam, something strange and surreal will happen to elevate it above a typical spoof movie.

title: Meet the Blacks
review: It’s more like an extremely confusing and sloppily written chunk of Purge fan-fiction—a tortured use of another movie’s absurd mythology to help make muddled quasi-satirical points, while indulging the apparently fail-safe punchline of saying the word “purge” about once a minute.

title: Meet the Blacks
review: Even by the standards of raunchy, comic spoofs, director and co-writer Deon Taylor’s film feels especially scattered.

title: Meet the Blacks
review: A wrongheaded, utterly incompetent, and nearly laugh-free satire.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: Parents who have had to sit through a myriad of mindless kids movies will appreciate a chance for their kids to be themselves at the theater and to be silly right alongside them. On the whole, it can serve as a good introduction to the movie-going experience.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: The song and dance interaction of kids hollering advice during Blue's Clues happens here on the big screen, which is meant to transform the movie into a social event of sorts.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: If today's youngsters grow up thinking of Christopher Lloyd as the old guy with the bongos from The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure, at least they'll be thinking of Christopher Lloyd at all.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: For the sake of the children, The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure should be allowed to quietly float away.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: Hallie's dad said it was Rocky Horror for toddlers whatever that is. Me and Hallie are 7 and we thought it was for babies.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: The low-budget production feels chintzy and impossibly square, even by tyke standards.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: Will your preschoolers enjoy it? Perhaps. Is it worth 88 minutes of their lives, or yours? Not in a world where "Sesame Street" is on TV every day. Not even in a world where "Sesame Street" didn't exist.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: The whole thing runs about an hour too long: It should have been a TV show. The adventure's too big for the kids who would love it the most.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: If only the movie could live up to its own potential. Instead, we're stuck with blandly unappealing costumed characters meandering through a boring quest to find some lost balloons.

title: The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure
review: Enduring this brainless kid's film is akin to witnessing the end of the world.
